<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Scales Down 9th Plan Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 10 (Xinhua) -- India Scaled down the growth
target of its ninth five-year plan (1997-2002) Tuesday to 6.5
percent from 7 percent due to poor performance during the first
two years.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee, who is also chairman of
the Planning Commission, directed the panel to incorporate
government's priorities on agriculture, infrastructure and social
sector during a 90-minute meeting of the commission held here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
S. R. Hashim, a secretary of the Commission told the press
after the meeting that the overall plan size might change
marginally from earlier 21,900 billion rupees (approximately 547.5
billion U.S. dollar) due to incorporation of the prime minister's
recent five-point special action program.
</P>
<P>
The detailed draft for the plan would be presented for
cabinet's approval by the first week of December and the National
development Council would be convened thereafter for finalization
of the plan.
</P>
<P>
The finalization of the ninth plan was delayed by political
uncertainties and subsequent mid-term elections later this month,
although the former United Front government released the draft
plan just a day before counting for Lower House elections began in
March this year.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Chairman Jaswant Singh's preoccupation with talks with
the U.S. administration following India's nuclear tests in May
also delayed the drafting of the ninth plan.
</P>
<P>
The Planning Commission approved the plan for the entire period
of 1997-2002 and there would not be any plan holiday due to delay
in finalization the plan, said Montek Singh Ahluwalia, a member of
the commission.
</P>
<P>
The panel would incorporate Vajpayee's special action program
which includes emphasis on agriculture, social sector,
infrastructure and information technology.
</P>
<P>
The government had earlier declared that it would earmark 60
percent of the plan funds for agriculture and rural development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
