<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Cancels Debt Owed by Honduras, Nicaragua </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 10 (Xinhua) -- France announced on Tuesday that
it will cancel all the debts owed by Honduras and Nicaragua, the
two Central American states which were worst struck by the
hurricane Mitch.
</P>
<P>
While making the announcement, French Minister of Finance and
Economy Dominique Strauss-Kahn said that France will go further by
establishing with Britain a fund for paying the debt of the
hurricane-struck Central American states to financial creditors
such as the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The debt owed by Honduras to France stands at 500 million
francs (83 million U.S. dollars) and that of Nicaragua 800 million
francs (133 million U.S. dollars), according to the French Foreign
Ministry assistant spokesman, Francois Rivasseau.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac will make a visit to Honduras,
Salvador and Nicaragua from November 14 to 16 after visiting
Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the French armed forces are staging an humanitarian
operation, ``Operation Cormoran,'' to provide emergency aid to
Central American states.
</P>
<P>
French military sources said that 400 French soldiers have been
mobilized for the operation which is focused on distributing
humanitarian aid materials and clearing roads.
</P>
<P>
Military planes and warships are deployed for sending materials
and rescuers to Central American states, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
When answering questions at the National Assembly, the minister
of finance and economy said that Honduras and Nicaragua are facing
the task of reconstructing their economy ``almost from zero,'' in
the wake of the passing of the hurricane.
</P>
<P>
France is standing by these countries by sending not only
humanitarian support such as emergency sanitary aid, but also
support in financial field, he said.
</P>
<P>
French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin Monday appealed to all the
creditor institutions or countries of Central American states to
partially cancel their debt and launch a moratorium postponing the
payment of their debt.
</P>
<P>
France has asked the member creditors of the Paris Club to
postpone the payment of debts owed by Central American states at
least by two years from 1999 to 2001.
</P>
<P>
A moratorium by the Paris Club will allow Honduras delay the
payment of some 500 million U.S. dollars and Nicaragua 250 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The total public debt owned by Honduras to international
creditors and foreign governments is estimated at 3.7 billion U.S.
dollars, and that of Nicaragua 6.1 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
