<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Housing Prices Rise in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Canada's new housing price
index was 0.9 percent higher in September compared with the same
period a year ago, Statistics Canada said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This was the 19th consecutive year-over-year increase after 31
consecutive declines from July 1994 to January 1997, the
statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
The annual changes of housing price varied considerably among
the Canadian cities surveyed.
</P>
<P>
The highest annual increase was the 8.2 percent jump recorded
in the booming Calgary market, while the largest drops were in
Victoria and Vancouver, which were down 6.8 percent and 5.5
percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
In Canada's largest city of Toronto, the annual increase was
3.2 percent. Because of its market size, this had a marked impact
on the national rate.
</P>
<P>
On a month-to-month basis, Canada's new housing price index
witnessed a slip of 0.1 percent in September, the second such drop
in the last 23 months, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
This decline was due mainly to declines in British Columbia
(B.C.) province. Although there are areas of activity in the B.C.
marketplace, conditions remain extremely competitive.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the monthly decline in September, the general
improvement in new housing markets in recent months has been
attributable to higher consumer confidence in Ontario and the
Praries, favourable mortgage interest rates and strong activity in
the resale market," the agency added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
