<HEADLINE> Chinese Defense Minister Visits S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Defense Minister
General Chi Haotian arrived here Tuesday, kicking off his
five-day official friendly visit to South Africa, the first of
its kind in the history of the two countries' troops.
</P>
<P>
In his written speech released at Johannesburg International
Airport, Chi, also vice-chairman of China's Central Military
Commission and state councillor, spoke highly of development of
bilateral ties since Beijing and Pretoria established official
diplomatic relations early this year.
</P>
<P>
"Since the establishment of diplomatic relations between China
and South Africa in January, the two countries have enjoyed
smooth development of the relations in various spheres and new
progress in political, economic, cultural and scientific and
technologicial fields."
</P>
<P>
He said the military-to-military relations constitutes an
important part of the state-to-state relations and the
development of the former should keep pace with the development
of the latter.
</P>
<P>
The general, who is here at the invitation of South African
Defense Minister Joe Modise, said his current visit was to
officially initiate the high-level exchanges between the two
defense ministries, and the two militaries, and create favorable
conditions of further developing an all-round relationship
between China and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Modise will reportedly hold a grand military review in
Pretoria, the administrative capital of the country, Wednesday to
welcome Chi.
</P>
<P>
Following his visit to South Africa, Chi will also visit
Botswana, Namibia, Mozambique and Singapore. 
</P>
</TEXT>
