<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Help in Angola Peace Process Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations has
asked South Africa to assist in efforts to find lasting peace in
war-torn Angola, South African state television SABC reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Visiting U.N. special envoy to Angola, Iffa Diallo, met South
African Deputy Foreign Minister Aziz Pahad Tuesday to convey the
message from U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
Diallo, who is touring countries in the region to save the
peace process in Angola, said renewed fighting between the
Angolan government and Jonas Savimbi's rebel UNITA movement is
putting the country on the brink of another civil war.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.N. Security Council believes that compliance
with the Lusaka protocol, signed in 1994, was the best way to
bring about peace in Angola.
</P>
<P>
He said UNITA leader Savimbi was the first to breach the
agreement, but some actions by the Angolan government also
amounted to an infringement. The government had, for example,
decided to suppress a number of privileges previously accorded to
Savimbi.
</P>
<P>
At Tuesday's meeting, Diallo told Pahad about the U.N.'s
concern about the deteriorating security situation in Angola and
again called on regional leaders to support the Lusaka agreement
and to isolate warlords.
</P>
<P>
Regional institutions such as the Organization for African
Unity (OAU) and the Southern African Development Community (SADC)
should tell Angola with one voice that war was not the solution
to its political problems, he said.
</P>
<P>
Diallo said he and Pahad did not discuss the possibility of
sending a regional peace-keeping force to Angola.
</P>
<P>
A few weeks ago, a meeting of SADC defense ministers raised
the possibility of sending troops to Angola to save the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
But Diallo said what Angola needed was a political solution.
</P>
<P>
Pahad said no decision on intervention was made yet. He added
that such a decision could be made only by the U.N. Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
Diallo, who arrived in South Africa from Angola Tuesday
morning, leaves later on the day for Namibia. He will also visit
Zimbabwe, Gabon, Cote d'Ivoire, and again Angola during the first
round of his diplomatic mission.
</P>
<P>
Several other countries will be visited before he returns to
South Africa in a few weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
