<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Foreign Investment Inflow Soars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 10 (Xinhua) -- South Africa was the
largest recipient of foreign direct investment (FDI) in Africa
last year, with inflows rising from 760 million U.S. Dollars in
1996 to 1.7 billion Dollars, a United Nations report has showed.
</P>
<P>
The figure was revealed in the annual report of the U.N.
Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD) on Monday, South
African Press Association (SAPA) reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
South Africa attracted more than a quarter of the continent's
FDI last year, which stood at 6.4 billion Dollars, SAPA said.
</P>
<P>
Releasing highlights of the annual UNCTAD report in
Johannesburg, the South African Industrial Development
Corporation said the sharp increase in capital inflow was largely
due to the privatization of public corporations.
</P>
<P>
These included the 30 percent sale of Telkom, the state-owned
telecommunications company, the sale of six radio stations and
Sun Air.
</P>
<P>
During the first half of 1998, FDI flows into South Africa
continued to be driven mainly by privatization, including the
purchase of a 20 percent share in the airport authority by an
Italian firm, an official of the corporation, Jorge Maia, said.
</P>
<P>
"Some foreign investment may also have been attracted by the
restructuring and unbundling of large South African conglomerate
companies," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, FDI unrelated to privatization appeared to have
declined between 1996 and 1997, Maia said.
</P>
<P>
About 80 percent of the incoming FDI came from the United
States, Malaysia, Britain, Germany and Japan. Some 60 percent of
the total inflow was in the form of mergers and acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
Excluding South Africa, FDI flows to Africa were just three
percent of total flows to developing countries last year, with a
volume of 4.7 billion Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria, Egypt, Morocco, Tunisia and Angola accounted for
two-thirds of this total.
</P>
<P>
Noting that foreign direct investment into Africa was low, the
U.N. report said there were signs of rising levels for the
future, as economic reforms and regulatory improvements in many
African countries were being recognized by foreign investors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
