<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Opposition's Presidential Petition Turned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Zambian Supreme Court here
Tuesday threw out a presidential petition in which five
opposition parties were challenging the parentage of President
Frederick Chiluba and the results of the 1996 elections.
</P>
<P>
Chief Justice Matthew Ngulube who led a full bench of five
judges ruled that Chiluba, who defeated former president Kenneth
Kaunda in Zambia's first multi-party elections held in 1991 and
was re-elected in the 1996 elections, is a Zambian and cleared
him of allegations that he is either a Congolese or Mozambican.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties including the country's largest
opposition party, the United National Independence Party led by
Kaunda, were petitioning, among other things, that the results of
the country's 1996 presidential elections should be declared null
and void because Chiluba was a foreigner and that he did not
qualify to stand for the elections held on November 18, 1996
under the constitution amendments.
</P>
<P>
The amendments adopted in May 1996 provide that foreign
nationals and those with foreign parentage are prohibited from
contesting the presidency.
</P>
<P>
The court also declared during a four-hour ruling that the
1996 elections were substantially conducted within the country's
electoral regulations despite a few flaws unearthed in the
electoral process by over 100 petitioners' witness.
</P>
<P>
As for Chiluba's controversial parentage, Ngulube cited
various authorities to prove that people born prior to October
24, 1964 when Zambia won its independence from Britain
automatically or by constitutional provisions became Zambian
citizens after independence.
</P>
<P>
Even though a number of witnesses in the one-year continuous
trial from February 1997 to January 1998, including the
self-proclaimed father of Chiluba, Luka Chabala Kafupi, had
testified that the president was born at a mission hospital in
former Zaire, Chiluba could still be a Zambian under the
pre-independence or post-independence constitution and laws, said
the chief justice.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the petitioners had called other witnesses who
testified that Chiluba was born of a father, Gym Zialale Nkonde,
from Mozambique while others had testified that he was born at a
village near Kitwe, 400 kilometers north of Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
Although the parentage of Chiluba was a matter of public
controversy, said Ngulube, the conflicting stories given by
witnesses regarding the president's origin could not be relied
upon.
</P>
<P>
He added that the court would rather rely on Chiluba's own
sworn testimony that he is a Zambian born at a northern Musangu
village and his mother Daina Kaimbe and his father Titus Jacob
Nkonde were Zambians.
</P>
<P>
The chief justice further pointed out that even if it were
true that Chabala or Nkonde from Mozambique were Chiluba's true
biological father, the question of citizenship would not arise
because he and all his alleged fathers would have become Zambian
citizens on October 24, 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
