<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Scientists Claim to Pinpoint Animal Protein </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Indian scientists have
claimed to have pinpointed the first ever "pure" animal protein
which can phenomenally trigger forward motility of sperms in
mammals.
</P>
<P>
The Press Trust of India (PTI) reported Tuesday that the
promising discovery might serve as the panacea for all male
infertility problems arising out of poor mammalian sperm motility
inside the female genital tract.
</P>
<P>
PTI said that the protein had been purified for the first time
from a biological fluid -- buffalo blood serum.
</P>
<P>
Two scientist, G. C. Majumder and M. Mandal, from the Indian
Institute of Chemical Biology in Calcutta struck upon the "pure"
animal glycoprotein while hunting for natural sperm motility
regulators in buffalo, PTI said.
</P>
<P>
All other motility promoting proteins earlier reported mostly
by American scientists are "impure" since they are a mix of a
group of proteins namely albumins and immunoglobins.
</P>
<P>
In a project sponsored by the Council of Scientific and
Industrial Research in collaboration with the Department of Atomic
Energy, PTI said, the scientist tested the protein on buffalo and
goat semen samples.
</P>
<P>
They reported "excellent" results at the National Congress on
Andrology and Reproductive Medicine held in Calcutta recently.
</P>
<P>
The research team had applied for patents for their discovery
in India, Japan, the United States and Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
