<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK High Street Sales Take A dive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 10 (Xinhua) - The UK retailers have suffered a
large slump in sales last month, which is said only the second
time since March 1995.
</P>
<P>
The sharp fall in UK High Street sales has heightened fears
that the country is heading for a recession and lead to fresh
calls for another cut in interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Figures from the British Retail Consortium (BRC), published
Tuesday, show that retail sales fell 0.6 percent in October.
</P>
<P>
The decline, it says, was caused by many shops putting on sales
throughout the month in an attempt to lure cautious shoppers to
spend money.
</P>
<P>
Bridget Rosewell, chief economic adviser to the BRC, said:
"These results show that the half-point cut in interest rates
announced last Thursday was well timed."
</P>
<P>
"The trend is still firmly downwards and will need to be
reversed shortly if the economy is to keep growing," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, many observers here believe that customers are now
keeping a tight hold on their wallets, fearing that they could
soon be out of a job if firms start laying off workers as the
economy deteriorates.
</P>
<P>
A series of high profile job losses in regions such as the
North East has created a crisis of confidence amongst shoppers.
</P>
<P>
There are now concerns that consumer confidence could collapse
further without another cut in interest rates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
