<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Injected Genes Help Grow New Blood Vessels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 10 (Xinhua) -- U.S. scientists have for
the first time shown that inserted genes into the heart could
enable patients to grow their new blood vessels, reported the
Washington Post Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that this approach could someday spare patients the
need for bypass surgery.
</P>
<P>
Currently several teams in the United States have injected a
gene that makes a protein called vascular endothelial growth
factor or VEGF into the hearts of people who have clogged vessels
but are too sick to go under ordinary bypass surgery or angioplasty.
</P>
<P>
The researchers found that the gene prompts the heart to sprout
tiny new blood vessels to nourish blood-starved muscle and relieve
crippling chest pain.
</P>
<P>
Reporting at a meeting held in Dallas Monday by American Heart
Association, Ronald G. Crystal of Cornell Medical School in New
York City said that among the 16 patients receiving the VSGF gene
injection, some were taking as many as 60 nitroglycerin tablets a
week for their pain, now the average dose is 2.5 pills weekly.
nearly half of the patients are entirely free of pain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
