<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Urges Turkey to Stop Military Action in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Ministry
spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi Tuesday called on Turkey to stop its
military action in northern Iraq and withdraw its troops from
Iraqi territory.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's territorial integrity should be preserved and any
action violating it should be avoided, Mohammadi was quoted by
the official news agency IRNA as saying.
</P>
<P>
About 20,000 Turkish troops moved into northern Iraq on Sunday
in a new cross-border offensive to wipe out the bases of the
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), outlawed in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The PKK militants have been fighting since 1984 for an
autonomous Kurdish homeland in southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi said such (military) actions would only deteriorate
the already fragile situation in the region.
</P>
<P>
"We understand Turkey's security concerns, but we believe that
military actions will further complicate the situation," he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Turkey should pull back its troops and settle
the issue through peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has launched series of cross-border military strikes to
try to eradicate Kurdish rebels taking shelter in northern Iraq,
over which Iraq lost control after the 1991 Gulf War when the
U.S. and its allies set up a de facto autonomous Kurdish zone.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has reportedly lost much of its support recently since
Turkey pressured Syria to stop its alleged aid to the rebels and
the Iraqi Kurdish factions controlling northern Iraq pledged to
fight it.
</P>
<P>
The lastest Turkish raid against the PKK was timed to talks
between two Iraqi Kurdish leaders in Ankara.
</P>
<P>
The two factions - the Kurdistan Democratic Party and the
Patriotic Union of Kurdistan - signed a peace accord in Washington
in September, agreeing to share power and hold elections next year.
</P>
<P>
The agreement upset Turkey, which opposes any move toward the
creation of an independent Kurdish state that could inspire the
PKK in its battle for autonomy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
