<HEADLINE> U.S. Denies Special Interest in Israel's Local Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. embassy in Israel
has denied that it has "special interest" in Israel's local
elections as reported by the local press.
</P>
<P>
Embassy spokesman Larry Schwartz told the Israel Radio Tuesday
that it is natural for the U.S. embassy to watch closely the local
election to see who will win, but that does not mean the embassy
has a particular and special interest in it.
</P>
<P>
Local English newspaper Ha'aretz reported Tuesday that the
U.S. embassy has been monitoring the municipal elections, which
started Tuesday morning, very closely, seeking clues for the
direction Israeli politics are heading for.
</P>
<P>
It said that embassy staff not only tried their best to gather
information about the elections, but also paid special attention
to the parties' general approach, campaign strategy and the
importance the parties attach to the results of the elections.
</P>
<P>
It also said the embassy set up a special team two months ago,
whose members did not bother to conceal the true reason for their
interest.
</P>
<P>
Based on the questions the embassy officials have been asking,
the embassy is interested primarily in the implications of the
Tuesday's voting for Israel's Knesset (parliament) elections, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
During the ongoing local elections, Israeli voters elect 161
mayors among 682 candidates and 2,800 municipal council members
among 20,000 hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
The number of eligible voters is about 4 million, 3.5 million
Jews and 350,000 Arabs.
</P>
<P>
Till Tuesday evening, the average turnout around the country
was nearly 30 percent and about 300 violent incidents, big or
small, were reported during the voting.
</P>
<P>
The polling stations will closed at 8:00 p.m. (1800 GMT) and
final results will be announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority has called on Arabs in East
Jerusalem to boycott the elections, saying East Jerusalem is an
occupied territory and Arab's participation would weaken the
Palestinian position in the final status negotiations over the
city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
