<HEADLINE> Saudi Crown Prince Gets Jordanian King's Message </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Crown Prince and
Deputy Prime Minister Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz received a message
Tuesday from King Hussein of Jordan on regional issues, especially
the standoff between Iraq and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The message was conveyed by visiting Jordanian Prime Minister
Fayez Tarawneh during a meeting with Abdullah, the Kuwait News
Agency reported. Saudi Foreign Minister Prince Saud Al-Faisal was
present at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources in Riyadh said that the message covered
developments of the region, mainly the Middle East peace process
and current Iraqi-U.N. standoff following Iraq's suspension of
cooperation with U.N. weapons inspectors late last month.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that Abdullah and Tarawneh reviewed, during
their talks, bilateral relations and means of developing them in
various fields.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed on the necessity to press Israel to
respect signed agreements within the peace process after Israel
halted the debate and ratification of the interim peace agreement
it signed with the Palestinians in Washington on October 23.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also urged Iraq to implement the U.N. Security
Council resolutions and resume cooperation with the U.N. Special
Commission in charge of disarming Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh, who arrived in Saudi Arabia earlier Tuesday, is
expected to meet Saudi King Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz later in the day
and relay a similar message from King Hussein, who is currently
in the U.S. for medical treatment of cancer. 
</P>
