<HEADLINE> Arafat Accuses Israel of Wasting Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) Chairman Yasser Arafat on Tuesday accused Israel
of wasting time in the implementation of the peace agreement
signed by the two sides last month.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Britain's Duke of Kent in the West Bank city
of Ramallah, Arafat expressed his doubts that Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu would fulfill Israel's obligations
under the agreement immediately.
</P>
<P>
"We expect that Netanyahu will waste a lot of time and he is
not going to implement the agreement honestly and quickly at all,"
Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
Senior Palestinian negotiator Hassan Asfour also told reporters
that the agreement should not be implemented unilaterally by the
Palestinian side.
</P>
<P>
He indicated that the PNA might stop fulfilling its
commitments under the agreement if Israeli cabinet failed to
ratify the accord in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, Israel is to withdraw troops from a
further 13 percent of the West Bank in the second redeployment.
In return, the PNA will take tougher measures against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
But Israeli government has delayed the implementation of the
agreement several times, which had been scheduled to begin on
November 2.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli Prime Minister's Office said on Tuesday that
Netanyahu hopes his cabinet will reconvene on Wednesday to
continue discussion over the agreement, which was disrupted by a
terror car bomb attack in Jerusalem on November 6. 
</P>
