<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Discusses State Role in Economic Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, November 10 (Xinhua) -- A panel of experts
Tuesday met at the U.N. headquarters here on the role of the State
in the management of Economy, also known as economic governance.
</P>
<P>
The discussion about the state role in economic management is
often characterized by extremes: a minimalistic State, or the
neoliberal view, with a restricted role in correcting market
failures, or an elaborate welfare State, U.N. sources said.
</P>
<P>
The theme of the discussion, organized by the Second Committee
of the General Assembly, is "The Third Way: Between Neoliberalism
and the Welfare State."
</P>
<P>
The "third way" concept tries to define a middle ground that
recognizes an active State role, but also the need to reform the
welfare State.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the concept stresses the need for effective public
management. This approach may combine a State role in providing
legal, regulatory frameworks for functioning markets, and in
setting a social policy, which recognizes the need for individual
responsibility, while assisting the truly needy.
</P>
<P>
The elaboration of practical policies to implement this concept
might provide a more realistic model for many countries, said a
U.N. report on Public Administration and Development.
</P>
<P>
Although there is no dispute concerning the essential role of
functioning national and global markets, there is a need for the
State to create the adequate institutional, legal and regulatory
frameworks.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, it is seen as necessary for the State to engage in
active social policies, based on sound financing options that are
tailored to real needs and do not undermine incentives for
self-responsibility and work. This calls for adjustments in the
welfare and social security systems, U.N. sources said.
</P>
<P>
Another aspect of the "third way" concept is the need to
introduce new public management methods, in order to balance
efficiency and equity.
</P>
<P>
These include new innovative system, such as the reform of
the civil service, the application of information technology,
decentralization of decision-making and new approaches to human
resources management.
</P>
<P>
The discussion of adequate institutional and regulatory regimes
is seen as an important part of the efforts to foster
socio-economic development.
</P>
<P>
The panel groups Anthony Giddens, director of London School of
Economics and Political Science, Jacques Baudot, director of the
Copenhagen Seminar on Social Policy, Linda Lim, director of the
Southeast Asia Program, School of Business at University of
Michigan, and Kwame Pianin, chief executive officer from New World
Investment, Ltd.
</P>
<P>
The Second Committee, in charge of economic and financial
matters in the world, considers annually issues relating to
public-sector economics and management.
</P>
<P>
This year, the relevant report of the U.N. Secretary-General is
being considered under a General Assembly agenda, entitled "Report
of the Economic and Social Council." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Hails Substantive Talks for EU Accession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot government has
welcomed the opening of substantive negotiations for Cyprus'
accession to the European Union (EU) in Brussels, Belgium, Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference Tuesday, government spokesman
Christos Stylianides said "we consider the start of substantive
negotiations as a very important event and an important landmark
in Cyprus' European course."
</P>
<P>
The EU started accession talks with the Greek Cypriot-dominated
Cypriot government last March, which was strongly opposed by the
Turkish Cypriots in the north and their ally Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 into Turkish Cypriot
controlled north and Greek Cypriot dominated south when Turkey
landed its troops and took over the northern third of the island
in the wake of a pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunite the east
Mediterranean island through a bi-communal formula. But the peace
talks were stalled last year when Turkish Cypriots opted out of
the negotiations to protest the EU's decision to began accession
talks with Cypriot government while excluding Turkey from its
immediate membership candidates list.
</P>
<P>
Some EU member states hold that the Cyprus problem should be
solved by political means before the island joins the EU.
</P>
<P>
However, the spokesman said that those who are trying to
associate in any way the island's accession course with the Cyprus
problem "do not help the peace process" because they "encourage
Turkey's intransigence."
</P>
<P>
Such words weaken EU's intention to act as a catalyst for a
settlement to the Cyprus problem, he added.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Monday's joint statement by France, Germany and
the Netherlands that Cyprus' division poses "particular
difficulties" to the Common European Foreign and Security Policy,
Stylianides described it as only "an expression of intent," saying
that "what is important and legally valid are the official
documents and decisions by the EU."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the accession course is the only
substantive lever that will exert continuous pressure on Turkey to
change its position regarding a settlement on the island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
