<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa, Good Place for Investment: OAU Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Organization of African
Unity (OAU) Assistant Secretary-General Vijay S. Makhan said
Tuesday that Africa is a good place for doing business.
</P>
<P>
There should no longer be room for negative images and such
stereotypes that the whole of Africa is a place of war and
instability, Makhan said when he was speaking at a ceremony for
the launching of "World Investment report 1998" at the United
Nations Conference center here.
</P>
<P>
First, the African continent is a highly profitable investment
location, said Makhan, who doubles as assistant chief of the
African Economic Community (AEC). "Data for United States and
Japanese affiliates of trans-national companies operating in
Africa show that they received rates of return that exceeded
those in other developing regions," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Second, Makhan said, notwithstanding exogenous developments
during 1997 including the El Nino weather phenomenon and the
weakening of commodity prices, the macro-economic fundamentals in
most African countries remain sound, continuing the steady trend
of improvement that has been observed throughout the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Third, he said that African governments have made enormous
efforts to improve their national policy frameworks for
attracting and retaining foreign direct investment.
</P>
<P>
According to Makhan, of the 53 African countries, 47 have
adopted liberal legal instruments to promote and facilitate
investment inflows.
</P>
<P>
In addition to these efforts, African countries have signed
bilateral investment treaties, which numbered 326 in 1997 mainly
with countries outside the continent.
</P>
<P>
Fourth, Makhan noted that efforts are being made throughout
the continent to reduce bureaucratic red tape, to streamline
procedures concerned with the administration of investment, and
to eliminate corruption.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-five African investment promotion agencies are now
members of the World Association of Investment Promotion
Agencies, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Makhan, four other elements are:
</P>
<P>
Fifth, despite all the constraints on many African countries
including an unsustainable debt burden, African governments have
been taking steps to improve the competitiveness of their
economies;
</P>
<P>
Sixth, African governments have created opportunities for
foreign direct investment by steadily expanding privatization
programs;
</P>
<P>
Seventh, at a sub-regional level, African governments are
factoring the advantages of regional cooperation and integration
into their efforts to attract foreign direct investment;
</P>
<P>
And eighth, although Africa's trade preferences have generally
been eroded by the Uruguay Round Agreements, most African
countries still have residual preferential access for exports to
the European Union through the Lome Convention.
</P>
<P>
Makhan said in conclusion that international investors should
look at African countries afresh especially in the light of the
changes that have been taking place.
</P>
<P>
Launching this year's investment report here, Samuel Nyambi,
Resident Representative of the United Nations Development
Program, said that this year's investment report will open a
wider discussion on policy issues related to trade liberalization
and foreign direct investment flows and the relative advantages
of developing countries in the competition to attract foreign
capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Not Blamed by DRC: Says FM Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian foreign
ministry spokesman Simeon Ileta Tuesday refuted media reports
that the government has been criticized as double-dealing in
mediating the crisis of Democratic of Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters in Dar es Salaam, Ileta, who is also the
Head of Information Department of the ministry, said neither the
DRC government nor its embassy here has made any complaints about
Tanzania's policy towards the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The stories about DRC's criticism of Tanzanian government are
merely fabricated, he said, adding that the Tanzanian government will not
take them into consideration.
</P>
<P>
Since war erupted in DRC, Ileta said, Tanzania as a sovereign
state and a Southern Africa Development Community (SADC) member
has maintained that solution to the conflict can only be dialogs
by warring parties.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania has distanced itself from military involvement in DRC
after rebels took up arms against President Laurent Kabila on
August 2.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Rwanda have reportedly backed rebel troops while
Angola, Zimbabwe, Namibia, Chad and Sudan have took sides with
the DRC government troops.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the Tanzanian government's position after Rwanda
has acknowledged its military presence in DRC, Ileta said it is a
positive step towards solving the crisis in the central African
country.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that SADC states will convene a summit in the near
future to create an environment suitable for all warring parties
find a political solution to the DRC conflicts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
