<HEADLINE> Former Russian Banking Officials to Face Investigation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prosecutor General Yuri
Skuratov said Tuesday that his office will open an investigation
into the alleged abuse of funds by several former senior Central
Bank officials.
</P>
<P>
The inquiry started in the wake of the August 17 default on
Russia's debts, Interfax quoted Skuratov as saying.
</P>
<P>
He did not give the names of the officials, who were suspected
of abusing Central Bank funds earmarked for specific purposes.
</P>
<P>
Skuratov said several criminal inquiries had already been
opened, and that documents on securities trading by individuals
were seized from the Moscow Interbank Currency Exchange.
</P>
<P>
The inquiry showed that some senior officials had used
classified information about prices on the Treasury-bill market in
their own interests, Skuratov said.
</P>
<P>
The bank's previous leadership committed "gross violations of
legislation," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The Central Bank sometimes issued a permit for a deal two
years after the deal had been effected," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, ex-chairman of the Central Bank Sergei Dubinin, now
vice-chairman of the Gazprom executive board, said he did not know
"what gross violations of the law in the Central Bank" Skuratov
meant.
</P>
<P>
"I have not seen any official documents dealing with what
Skuratov spoke about. The Prosecutor-General's Office did not ask
me any questions within the framework of a probe into this
problem. Nor did Skuratov quote any facts regarding it," Dubinin
said.
</P>
<P>
Regarding criminal proceedings initiated by the Prosecutor-
General's Office against highly-placed officials who allegedly
used information on GKOs in their own interests, Dubinin said that
he "as an individual did not perform any operations with
securities."
</P>
<P>
"I don't know whom exactly the prosecutor-general meant," he
said. "I know nothing about the use of information about
quotations on GKOs by any official for his own interests," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said that "previous statements concerning violations of
regulations on the use of IMF credits by the Central Bank were not
backed by any facts."
</P>
<P>
Skuratov said two letters to the Central Bank's current
chairman, Viktor Gerashchenko, have been prepared to notify him of
the early results of the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
The idea is to help the Central Bank's present leadership "to
avoid repeating the same errors," Skuratov added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
