<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil-for-Food Program Fails: Iraqi Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The Iraq-U.N. oil-for-food
program failed to alleviate the Iraqi people's suffering caused by
the trade sanctions imposed on Iraq for eight years, said a senior
Iraqi official on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Trade Minister Mohammed Mehdi Saleh made the remarks at
the closing ceremony of the 31st Baghdad International Fair which
opened on November 1.
</P>
<P>
Saleh told reporters that the fourth phase of the oil-for-food
program, which came into force last June, will expire by November
25. However, he said, only 10 percent of the contracted food has
arrived in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"What is even worse is that no contracted medicine under this
phase has reached Iraq at all," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Under the fourth phase of the oil-for-food deal, Iraq is
allowed to export 5.2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil to buy
food, medicine and other humanitarian supplies.
</P>
<P>
However, the amount of oil Iraq is allowed to export will not
exceed 3 billion dollars due to the low prices on world oil
markets.
</P>
<P>
Saleh termed the U.N. trade sanctions on Iraq as "equivalent to
mass genocide of the Iraqi people", elaborating that 5,000 Iraqi
children died every month due to shortages of medicine and food.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has the ability to meet all the requirements of its people
if the U.N. lifts the ongoing trade sanctions, said Saleh.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. imposed the crippling sanctions on Iraq following its
1990 invasion of Kuwait. According to U.N. resolutions, the
sanctions cannot be lifted unless U.N. arms inspectors verify that
Iraq has eliminated all its weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi minister also called on foreign countries to
strengthen economic and trade cooperation with Iraq, promising
that Iraq is able to cope with the current situation.
</P>
<P>
The 31st Baghdad International Fair, the largest since the
1991 Gulf War, opened one day after Iraq halted all forms of
cooperation with the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) on
disarming Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi leadership said it would not rescind its decision
until the U.N. Security Council considers lifting the economic
sanctions and restructuring the UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council adopted a resolution on November 5,
condemning Iraq's confrontation and urging it to resume
cooperation with U.N. arms inspectors, but Iraq has yet
turned a deaf ear to the U.N. call. 
</P>
</TEXT>
