<HEADLINE> EU to Offer 101m ECU of Aid to Hurricane Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The European Union said on
Tuesday that its member states and the European Commission would
combine to contribute 101.8 million ECU (111.98 million U.S.
dollars) to central America that fell prey to Hurricane Mitch.
</P>
<P>
The 15 European Union member states put together a humanitarian
aid worth 71 million ECU while the commission, the executive body
of the union, garnered 30.8 million ECU, according to commission
sources.
</P>
<P>
Spain accounted for half of the 71 million ECU contributed by
the member states.
</P>
<P>
The European Union aid will cover food aid and rehabilitation
in central America, where the hurricane already claimed a toll of
26,000 deaths and missing and left 3 million homeless.
</P>
<P>
France also offered to annul the debts the central American
countries owe it while the Netherlands decided to annul the
payment of debt interest and this year's installment of debt
payment by Honduras.
</P>
<P>
Hurricane Mitch triggered floods and mud slides that raked havoc
with the central American countries, especially in Honduras and
Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
Honduras and Nicaragua appealed for international creditors to
write off 11 billion dollars in debt owed by the two countries
whose economies have been ruined by the hurricane. 
</P>
</TEXT>
