<HEADLINE> Cyprus to Implement Law Regarding Spying Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government will
implement law and order regarding the recent alleged espionage
case of two Israelis against the Cypriot army, government
spokesman Christos Stylianides said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The government "has a duty and an obligation to implement the
law and order, to fully respect the laws and the constitutional
provisions and decisions of the courts on the issue," the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Two Israelis - Udi Argov, 37 and Ig'al Damari, 49 - were caught
spying in Cyprus' southern coastal village of Zygi between
November 6-7. Cyprus police said they found sophisticated
listening devices and radio scanners, tuned into police radio
frequencies during their search for suspects' apartment.
</P>
<P>
They were remanded in custody on Saturday by Larnaca District
Court for eight days pending investigation on suspicion of spying
on the Cyprus National Guard.
</P>
<P>
According to the Israeli embassy in Nicosia, the two suspects
have denied the charges against them.
</P>
<P>
Stylianides said in the daily press briefing that the
government does not wish to comment on any details of this case as
the legal procedure is still underway.
</P>
<P>
Referring to statements made by Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu, who said he will bring back home the two Israelis,
Stylianides said "it is his right to make any statements which
concern the repatriation of the two Israeli suspects."
</P>
<P>
However, he said, any repatriation must be done legally. The
Cypriot government will act according to the laws of the state, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Stylianides said the Israeli government did not make any
representations to the Cypriot embassy in Tel Aviv, nor did the
Cypriot government make any representations over Netanyahu's
statements.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Israeli President Ezer Weizman's message to
Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides will not be made public, noting
that negotiations regarding the two Israelis are underway through
diplomatic channels.
</P>
<P>
The message from Weizman, who paid a state visit to Cyprus last
week, was conveyed to Clerides by Weizman's Director General Ariel
Shumer.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Minister of Justice and Public Order Nicos Koshis
said Tuesday that the Cypriot authorities will continue their
investigation into the case.
</P>
<P>
All evidence will be submitted to the attorney-general for a
final decision, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
