<HEADLINE> Uganda Sets up Fund for Unemployed Graduates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government has
provided 500 million Shillings (400,000 U.S. Dollars) as start-up
capital for educated but unemployed graduates for self employment
and income generation.
</P>
<P>
Radio Uganda reported that an agreement was signed for the
management of the fund at Cooperative Bank here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
About 400 million Shillings (320,000 Dollars) has already been
released to the Cooperative Bank who will manage the revolving
credit program. Another 500 million Shillings (400,000 Dollars)
have been budgeted this financial year for the scheme, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The Entandikwa Secretariat will coordinate the scheme while
Uganda Manufacturers' Association and the Private Sector
Development Program will coordinate the training component.
</P>
<P>
The beneficiaries of the fund are youths from universities and
tertiary institutions between the ages of 18 to 30 years who must
undergo training in business skills development for three weeks.
</P>
<P>
After the training, the youths will be put in apprenticeship
attachments with ongoing successful enterprises in order to
orient them into real life situations of managing small
enterprises profitably.
</P>
<P>
They will then recommend to the Cooperative Bank to access the
loans which will be charged 16 percent each year.
</P>
<P>
Over 450 youths have received training for the scheme, the
report added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
