<HEADLINE> Ugandan Firm Refutes Report of Buying Commercial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's Greenland Investment
Limited (GIL) has denied having bought the 49 percent shares in
Uganda Commercial Bank (UCB) but vowed to participate in the
buying of the remaining 51 percent shares when they are floated.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference Tuesday, the GIL Chairman
Suleiman Kiggundu said his company has earlier showed interest
but lost to Westmont Land Behad Asia (WLBA), a Malaysian company.
</P>
<P>
A Radio Uganda report quoted the chairman as dismissing as
mere speculation that there have been agreements between his
company and the Malaysian partner.
</P>
<P>
Even if such agreements were contemplated, he said, they would
be inexecutable, null and void, since under the agreement between
the WLBA and the Ugandan government, the buyer has no powers of
selling the bank to any other party.
</P>
<P>
The WLBA finalized payment of the purchase of 49 percent
shares of UCB and assumed management and control of the bank in
April this year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Permanent Secretary of Finance Tumusiime Mutebile
has assured Ugandans who have deposits in UCB that their money is
safe and secure.
</P>
<P>
The intervention by the central bank to supervise the
commercial bank is a normal procedure monitoring all private
banks, he said, adding that UCB will continue to pursue a lending
policy that will guarantee that there is no non-performing loans.
</P>
<P>
Bank of Uganda temporarily suspended the operations of three
commercial banks here in September, sending waves of panic among
those who deposit money in commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
The continued depreciation of Shilling also contributes to
people's sensitivity to any movement in the financial sector.
</P>
