<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Police Ready for Action Against Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of Zimbabwean police
were deployed Tuesday night in all pockets of Harare to
monitor the potential volatile situation in face of the stayaway
scheduled for Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Police spokesman Wayne Budzijena told the Zimbabwe News Agency
Tuesday that all areas including residential areas, the city
center and townships were under police surveillance to ensure the
maintenance of law and peace during the stayaway.
</P>
<P>
"We just want to make sure that there will be no harassment of
those willing to go to work," he said, adding the police will
intensify road patrols to crack down on traffic offenders.
</P>
<P>
The police will not force the people to go to work nor the
commuters to operate but will only facilitate for those who would
be willing, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are not worried about those who decide to stay at home,
but we can not rule out that there could be others willing to go
to work," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe Congress of Trade Unions Tuesday urged workers to
stage a national strike, and demanded that the government
immediately withdraw the 68 percent fuel price increase effective
on october 31.  
