<HEADLINE> 35 Percent of Tanzanian Youth Smoke </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Some 35 percent of
Tanzanian young people aged 12 or above smoke tobacco regularly,
according to a seminar organized by World Health Organization
(WHO).
</P>
<P>
Prevalence of smoking varies from one region to another,
statistics made available at the two-day seminar on tobacco
control indicated.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, which ended in the central region of Morogoro
Tuesday, was told that 42 percent of youth aged 12 or above in
the northern region of Kilimanjaro smoke, compared with eight
percent in Mara, a Lake Victoria region.
</P>
<P>
The findings show that male to female ratio is 30 to one among
smokers in Kilimanjaro and three to one in Mara, Tanzania News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Among secondary school students in Dar es Salaam, 1.6 percent
of them appear to be smokers.
</P>
<P>
In his paper "Tobacco the Killer," Joseph Mbatta from the
Ministry of Health said although the Tanzania Tobacco Processing
Board Act of 1984 demands licensing for the production and sale
of cigarettes, it does not stipulate the legal age limit for
purchasing tobacco.
</P>
<P>
He said attempts to prevent tobacco usage have not been
effective enough due to lack of well planned coordination and
commitment of the relevant authorities.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, organized by the Ministry of Health in
collaboration with WHO, brought together about 20 participants
representing different non-governmental organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Foreign Debts Drop to 11.3 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Iran's foreign debts decreased
to 11.3 billion U.S. dollars during the first quarter of this
Iranian year which started on March 21, registering a drop of 800
million dollars in seven months.
</P>
<P>
The official news agency IRNA reported on Tuesday that Iran's
total external obligations amounted to 22.1 billion dollars if
contingent obligations, including opened letters of credit not
yet consigned and future interest were taken into account.
</P>
<P>
Quoting a report from the Central Bank of Iran, IRNA said that
Iran is due to pay off 5.567 billion dollars of the debt by the
end of the current Iranian year and 3.742 billion dollars more
in the next Iranian year.
</P>
<P>
The country's current account balance at the end of the first
quarter was 909 million dollars in red, showing a major contrast
with the surplus of 280 million dollars for the balance at the end
of the first quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
The country's exports, including oil and non-oil exports,
during the period only gained 3.202 billion dollars, some
1.600 billion dollars less than that for the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
The imports in the quarter was registered at 3.714 billion
dollars, showing a drop of over 270 million dollars compared to
that of last year's first quarter. 
</P>
