<HEADLINE> IMF Approves $16m Loan for Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) has approved a 16 million U.S. Dollar loan for Sierra Leone
to support the country's 1998/99 economic program aimed at
repairing the damage from recent civil unrest.
</P>
<P>
A report from Washington said the loan, approved by the IMF
Monday, will be extended under its emergency post-conflict
assistance scheme which was created in 1995 to help countries
trying to overcome the effects of conflict.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leone's economy has been laid waste by years of civil
unrest due to the rebel of the Revolutionary United Front and
most recently to the rule of the military junta led by Johnny
Paul Koromah from May 1997 to February 1998.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted the IMF as saying that the rebuilding of
Sierra Leone's institutions will lay the basis for more extensive
reforms, possibly backed by more IMF money under its Enhanced
Structural Adjustment Facility from mid-1999.
</P>
<P>
According to the IMF, Sierra Leone's real gross domestic
Product is expected to grow by 0.7 percent this year and by a
more impressive 5.9 percent in 1999, after shrinking by 20.2
percent in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
