<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Signs Bill for Enforcing Anti-Bribery in Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 10 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Tuesday signed bill pushing and enforcing an international
anti-bribery agreement in foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, which requires major U.S. trading partners to
adopt anti-bribery laws, is part of a Clinton administration
strategy for pushing forward U.S. exports even amid Asia's
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
The United States is one of the few countries with laws against
using bribes to win foreign business deals. U.S. businessmen and
executives have complained for years that the 1977 Foreign Corrupt
Practices Act puts them at a disadvantage in trying to win
business contracts overseas.
</P>
<P>
Congress passed legislation making the United States part of
the agreement on October 21.
</P>
<P>
"I'm sorry to say... it cost us a lot of business over the last
20 years to do the right thing, but it is clearly the right
thing," Clinton said. "American companies deserve a level playing
field... and now we will have it."
</P>
<P>
Addressing a Town Hall Meeting of students, teachers, business
leaders and members of his advisory Export Council, the president
also expressed concern that U.S. steel companies are suffering
from a surge of cut-rate steel imports from Japan, South Korea and
other economically distressed Asian nations.
</P>
<P>
The president, in remarks linked to an audience in six states
by video, telephone and the Internet, previewed his scheduled trip
to Asia this weekend to attend the annual gathering of leaders of
the Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation forum in Kuala Lumpur,
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Clinton met at the White House last week with U.S. steel
industry executives concerned about rising imports of Japanese and
other foreign steel.
</P>
<P>
"We are committed to a full, timely enforcement of our trade
laws... protecting this industry," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the Commerce Department Tuesday released new
regulations on enforcing trade laws in the steel sector.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is scheduled to visit Japan and South Korea after the
APEC summit. The APEC gathering coincides with strains in the
international financial system that began in East Asia in 1997,
spread this year to Russia and now threatens Brazil and other
Latin American nations.
</P>
<P>
"We have heavy responsibilities here in the United States," he
said. "We must continue with our efforts to generate greater
economic growth, to seek freer and fair trade, to see that trade
and global financial systems are modified to meet the needs of the
21st century, to roll back the present financial crisis and to
design efforts that will lift the lives of all people over the
long run."
</P>
<P>
"The restoration of growth in Japan, which has been stalled now
for more than five years, is absolutely essential to the
restoration of growth in the rest of Asia," Clinton added. "The
rest of us look to Japan to move quickly." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
