<HEADLINE> Cohen Warns Iraq Time Running Out to Comply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The United States said
Tuesday that time was running out for Iraqi government to resume
cooperation with U.N. arms inspections and ordered the aircraft
carrier Enterprise to speed its transit to the Gulf to replace
another carrier.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference with visiting Singapore Defense
Minister Tony Tan, Defense Secretary William Cohen told reporters
that impatience with Iraq's President Saddam Hussein was growing.
</P>
<P>
"We have all indicated that time is running out," he said when
asked if the United States was drawing closer to attack after Iraq
declared on October 31 that it would no longer cooperate with U.N.
weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
"The military option is still on the table," said Cohen.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said that he had ordered the carrier Enterprise, which
routinely left Norfolk Virginia, this week to replace the carrier
Eisenhower in the Gulf, to speed its transit and arrive on
November 23 instead of November 26.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said he did not now plan to keep both carriers in the
region within striking distance of Iraq. The Eisenhower is winding
up a six-months overseas deployment and scheduled to return to
Norfolk in early December.
</P>
<P>
The Marine helicopter carrier Belleau Wood is also heading to
the Gulf from Japan to replace the helicopter carrier Essex and
will arrive on November 26, Cohen added.
</P>
<P>
The United States has about 170 warplanes and 21 ships in
the Gulf region, including the Eisenhower and seven other ships
capable of launching long-range Tomahawk cruise missiles. An
eighth Tomahawk-armed ship, the cruiser Anzio, is moving toward
the Gulf through the Red Sea.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton again reviewed military and
diplomatic options with Cohen and other senior advisers on Tuesday
as the U.S. tried to determine the best response to Iraq's
defiance of the United Nations over weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said he did not expect
the meeting to produce a decision on whether the United States
would resort to military action to force Iraqi President Saddam
Hussein to back down.
</P>
<P>
So far no final ultimatum or deadline has been outlined by
Clinton, who is scheduled to leave on Saturday on a 10-day
Asia-Pacific tour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
