<HEADLINE> Turkey Says Its Concerns over Northern Iraq Eased </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Turkey heaved a sigh of relief
Tuesday following the declaration of an awaited trilateral
statement by Turkey, Britain and the United States on the future
of northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Deputy Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit said that the
statement was "an encouraging development" and Turkey's concerns
were eased, according to the Anatolia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
"A new era of relations is starting in northern Iraq," Ecevit
said.
</P>
<P>
The trilateral statement, which was first released by Ankara
and later by London and Washington, made it clear that Iraq's
territorial integrity should be fully respected.
</P>
<P>
Ankara was upset by a peace accord signed by two rival Iraqi
Kurdish groups - the Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP) led by
Massoud Barzani and the Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK) led by
Jalal Talabani - on September 17 in Washington.
</P>
<P>
Turkey feared that the KDP-PUK agreement on power sharing and
future elections could lead to a Kurdish state in northern Iraq,
which would further encourage the activities of Turkey's outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK).
</P>
<P>
The Turkish-U.S.-British statement also stressed that Turkey's
legitimate security concerns and its right to defend itself
against terrorism should be respected.
</P>
<P>
"We also welcome the clear commitment by the KDP and PUK to
deny sanctuary to the PKK, to eliminate all PKK Bases from the
region, and to safeguard the Turkish border," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Barzani, who visited Ankara last week, and Talabani, who is
still in Ankara for contacts with Turkish officials, have said
that they will join hands to fight the PKK and maintain peace and
tranquility in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
They also vowed to strengthen ties with Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Talabani, who allegedly keeps closer relations with the PKK,
also said that he would shut down all the PKK camps in areas
controlled by his group.
</P>
<P>
The PUK leader is expected to repeat the promises he has given
to Turkey during his meeting with Turkish Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz on Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
