<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Productivity Edges Healthy 2.3 Pct Rate in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. workers'
productivity growth rate improved in the third quarter after
nearly stalling during the previous quarter, the Labor Department
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The productivity of nonfarm, nonsupervisory workers, measured
as output per hour of work, rose at a seasonally adjusted 2.3
percent annual rate in the third quarter, according to the
department.
</P>
<P>
During the second quarter, productivity advanced at a scant 0.3
percent rate, the slowest increase in nearly two years.
Productivity was robust during the first three months of the year,
rising at a 3.5 percent rate.
</P>
<P>
After growing at a brisk 2.9 percent annual rate in the 1960s
and early 1970s, productivity slowed to a paltry 1 percent from
1974 through 1995. Since then, it's been growing at around a 2
percent rate.
</P>
<P>
That's led some economists to speculate that the economy has
embarked on a new era of productivity growth, driven by computers
and other high-tech innovations.
</P>
<P>
However, in Tuesday's report, there were signs of the strain
imposed on the economy by the world financial turmoil that began
in Asia last year and has depressed U.S. export sales.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing output, which represents 18 percent of the
economy, declined at a 0.6 percent rate, the first drop since
1991, during the last recession.
</P>
<P>
Hours worked at factories fell even further, at a 4.1 percent
rate. So, productivity within the sector remained strong, growing
at a 3.7 percent rate.
</P>
<P>
For all nonfarm businesses, output rose at a moderate 3.5
percent rate. Growth in hours worked was the smallest in a year,
rising at a 1.2 percent rate. Unit labor costs, a key measure of
inflation pressures, rose modestly, at a 1.7 percent rate, after
shooting up at a 3.7 percent rate in the second quarter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda Wants Security Concerns Resolved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Rwandan Foreign Minister
Anastase Gasana said Tuesday his country is now committed to
pulling its troops out of the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC),
but only on condition that its "legitimate" security concerns are
resolved.
</P>
<P>
Gasana predicted an early end to the fighting in the DRC
provided all parties involved in the conflict engaged in
political negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The minister admitted that Rwanda had soldiers from its
45,000-strong army fighting alongside rebel forces in the DRC but
could not give an exact figure of the military deployment.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone interview with the Zimbabwe News Agency, Gasana
catalogued for the first time six political problems that he said
must be ironed out at the negotiating table to bring about a
peaceful resolution to the three-month-old crisis in the war-torn
DRC.
</P>
<P>
"The first one is the armed forces or elements coming from the
Congo which used to kill our people, making cross border raids to
kill Rwandans," he said at his Foreign Ministry headquarters in
the Rwandan capital Kigali.
</P>
<P>
The second legitimate security concern for Rwanda is what he
termed "stateless" people such as the marauding Interahamwe and
the nihilistic Mai Mai who were roving on the country's border
with Congo.
</P>
<P>
"Congo has a big problem of citizenship. There is a big
stateless population and this is not secure for us. We think
Congo has to solve its problems of citizenship of its
population," he said.
</P>
<P>
He accused Congolese President Laurent Kabila's government of
waging a campaign of genocide against the minority Tutsi
population in the DRC and said this is the third legitimate
concern for Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
There was also a concentration of "terrorists" in the Congo
from such countries as Sudan, said Gasana, making this the fourth
security concern.
</P>
<P>
The fifth concern is the illegal trafficking in weapons of war
which he said was taking place in the DRC because the Kabila
government was not able to police its vast territory.
</P>
<P>
Next is the fact that Kabila and Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe had made declarations of war against his country, he said.
</P>
<P>
"They made the declarations in Kinshasa and Lubumbashi. We
think it is also a security concern for Rwanda coming from the
Congo," he said.
</P>
<P>
If the international community and all people involved can
give opportunities for these concerns to find a solution, Gasana
said, Rwanda is ready to bring its contribution for a peaceful
solution in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
These concerns can be addressed in negotiations between
Kabila, the rebels and their supporters, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
