<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Inflation Rate Lowest Since Unification </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 10 (Xinhua) -- German Inflation Rate rose 0.7
percent in October compared with the corresponding period of 1997,
the Federal Office of Statistics said Tuesday in Wiesbaden.
</P>
<P>
This is the lowest rate of inflation since German unification
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
In East Berlin and the former East Germany, the cost of living
was 0.6 percent, and in the former West Germany, the cost of
living was 0.7 percent, compared with the same month a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The statistics office said that seasonal factors were the main
reason for low figure for October with prices for fresh fruit
dropping 4.7 percent, potatoes becoming 2.7 percent cheaper and
package tours costing 6.4 percent less.
</P>
<P>
The office noted that it was the first time since January 1997
that eastern German inflation was lower than that in western
Germany.
</P>
<P>
Declining energy costs also were a factor in the lower
inflation. The office said that they dropped by 0.4 percent from
September to October, with natural gas down by 1.5 percent and
light heating oil 0.3 per cent lower.
</P>
<P>
Normal heating oil rose by 0.3 percent in October, but compared
with October 1997 levels, these prices were 21.8 per cent lower.
Motor fuel costs were up 0.1 percent from September to October,
but were seven percent lower than in October 1997.
</P>
<P>
Compared with October 1997 levels, overall energy costs were a
full 3.3 percent lower last month, the statistics office said.
Transportation and telecom rates were meanwhile 0.1 percent lower
on the year-to-year comparison.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
