<HEADLINE> Angolan Official Accuses UNITA of Killing 24 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, November 10 (Xinhua) -- An Angolan official Tuesday
accused the opposition National Union for the Total Independence
of Angola (UNITA) of killing 21 Angolans and three foreigners
last Sunday in a diamond mine in Lunda-Norte Province, east
Angola.
</P>
<P>
Alcides Pereira, Deputy Governor of the province, said Tuesday
that those killed include two English and one Portuguese. In
addition, 34 others are still missing. The armed bandits
destroyed mining facilities, vehicles as took away other
properties from the mine which belongs to a Canadian company
Diamondworks.
</P>
<P>
This is the second large scale killing in the province within
the year. On July 21, about 150 innocent people were killed by
armed bandits in Bula Mine in Lunda-Norte. The Angolan
government believed the attack was made by the former UNITA rebel
movement, however, the U.N. observer mission in Angola failed to
identify the attackers. 
</P>
