<HEADLINE> U.S. Seizes Colombian Plane With Drugs Aboard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The United States seized a
Colombian cargo plane at a Florida airport Monday when it had
found the plane was carrying an unknown amount of cocaine.
</P>
<P>
The Colombian Air Force C-130 has been detained at the Fort
Lauderdale International Airport since Monday, U.S. officials said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Customs crews found cocaine aboard the aircraft. But U.S.
authorities could not immediately confirm news reports that 1,200
to 1,500 pounds (544 to 680 kg) of the drug had been on board the
plane.
</P>
<P>
Customs agents were continuing to search the aircraft Tuesday.
Airport and Customs officials said they expected to make a more
detailed announcement later Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Colombian Air Force Chief General Manuel
Sandoval had offered President Andres Pastrana his resignation
over the incident.
</P>
<P>
Three junior Air Force officers were sentenced last week in
Colombia to prison terms for an incident on September 20, 1996,
when 4 kilograms of heroin were found aboard Colombia's
presidential jet shortly before it was to fly former President
Ernesto Samper to New York for a meeting of the U.N. General
Assembly. 
