<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strategies Formulated for Singapore's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The Committee on Singapore's
Competitiveness (CSC) formed by the Singapore government Wednesday
has made public its report of proposals on the strategies for the
country's future competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
The report underlines that even as Singapore takes steps to
deal with the current economic crisis, efforts should be focused
on the challenges that lie ahead beyond the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The CSC proposes that Singapore should develop into an advanced
and globally competitive knowledge economy within the next decade
with manufacturing and services as the twin engines of growth.
</P>
<P>
In order to realize the goal, CSC has recommended eight key
strategies for enhancing capabilities and managing cost
competitiveness in the economic area. They are:
</P>
<P>
-- To promote manufacturing and services as the twin engines of
growth and diversify dependence beyond any single industry, sector
or market;
</P>
<P>
-- To strengthen and diversify external economic wing by
incorporating a global dimension;
</P>
<P>
-- To increase the depth of corporate profile, broaden the
economic base for sustained and resilient growth and strive to
nurture a stable of own world-class companies;
</P>
<P>
-- To strengthen the base of small and medium enterprises to
entrench their relevance as important strategic partners to
multi-national companies and government-linked companies;
</P>
<P>
-- To develop a world class workforce comprising domestic and
foreign talent.
</P>
<P>
-- To leverage on science, technology and innovation
effectively as competitive tools;
</P>
<P>
-- To continually optimize allocation of the country's scarce
resources in a dual approach of increasing supply as well as
efficient usage;
</P>
<P>
-- And to highlight the importance of government's role in
economic and financial management.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Minister for Trade and Industry Lee Yock Suan, who
doubles as CSC Chairman, told a press conference Wednesday that
CSC is confident these recommendations on strategies will ensure
Singapore to develop into a vibrant knowledge economy of the
future.
</P>
<P>
The CSC was formed in May 1997 on the advice of Singapore Prime
Minster Goh Chok Tong and was assigned to make a thorough review
of the country's economic competitiveness over the next 10 years.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
