<HEADLINE> NATO Blames Provocative Incidents in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) on Wednesday said provocative incidents in
Kosovo have led to the deaths of two Serbian policemen and have
also menaced the cease-fire there.
</P>
<P>
A NATO official said on condition of anonymity that a great
deal of concern was shown over the deteriorating situation in
Kosovo during Wednesday's meeting of the North Atlantic Council
(NAC), the decision-making body of the military alliance.
</P>
<P>
"NATO condemns very strongly all the incidents and the groups
that provoked them," said the official.
</P>
<P>
The alliance insisted that the Kosovo Liberation Army comply
fully with the cease-fire and cease further provocation.
</P>
<P>
NATO is also concerned with reports that the Yugoslav police
force has been setting up "flying (mobile) checkpoints" in Kosovo
and a heavy Serbian police presence has been found in the
province, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
During the day's meeting, the NAC discussed the formation and
operation, in the event of an engagement inside Kosovo, of the
extraction force, but did not reach a final decision.
</P>
<P>
NATO would like to get things right from the beginning and has
been very meticulous in planning the extraction force mission,
said the official.
</P>
<P>
The alliance is expected to finalize the extraction force
mission later this week, he added.
</P>
<P>
The extraction force, composed of 1,500 to 1,800 troops under
the command of France, is designed to provide security for a
2,000-member monitoring mission in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The same official confirmed that NATO has withdrawn some of the
war planes deployed for a possible air strike that was
indefinitely suspended.
</P>
<P>
"NATO is not withdrawing all the planes from the theater and
the planes can be re-deployed should air operations become
necessary. The Kosovo crisis is not over," said the official.
</P>
</TEXT>
