<HEADLINE> Lishui Prefecture Seeks Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Lishui, a mountainous
prefecture in east China's Zhejiang Province, has listed 300
projects open to investments and cooperation with interested
parties from both at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at today's news briefing, Commissioner Zhong Xiaomao
said the move is designed to accelerate economic growth and enable
the prefecture to close the gap with the province's developed
areas.
</P>
<P>
The projects will involve investments ranging from 250,000 yuan
to 543 million yuan and will cover the infrastructure,
agriculture, tourism, machine-building and pharmaceutical sectors.
</P>
<P>
The Kaitan Water Conservation Project, the major project, will
require and investment of 543 million yuan. Kaitan will be the
first phase of a massive hydropower development program along the
Oujiang River, a major waterway in southern Zhejiang.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner noted that Lishui is blessed with abundant
forestry, mineral and water resources. The city of Longquan, one
of nine cities and counties in the prefecture, is well-known for
the large number of native citizens living abroad, while Jingning
She Autonomous County is China's sole autonomous county for
members of the She ethnic group, and Qingyuan County is the
country's major mushroom production base.
</P>
<P>
Lishui has established direct economic and trade ties with
dozens of countries and regions, said Zhong, adding that the
prefecture's investment environment has improved significantly
over the past decade with the completion of a new railway, 12
highways and a digital telecommunication facilities providing
direct links to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
Lishui plans to become a production center for basic materials,
agricultural products and hydropower, as well as a tourism
destination by 2010, according to Zhong. He expressed hope that
domestic and overseas investors will join the prefecture's
economic efforts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
