<HEADLINE> Japanese Games Hopeful Fails Drug Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese Olympic Committee
(JOC) said on Wednesday that one snooker player among its Asian
Games hopefuls had tested positive for a banned muscle-building
drug.
</P>
<P>
JOC officials said that Junsuke Inoue, 58, who would have been
the oldest Japanese competitor at Bangkok, would be banned for
two years from any event sanctioned by the ruling body.
</P>
<P>
Traces of methyltestosterone, a male hormone with similar
effects to testosterone, were found in Inoue's urine sample when
all 635 Japanese athletes bound for Bangkok underwent doping
tests on October 1.
</P>
<P>
The snooker player later admitted he had taken the drug
containing methyltestosterone to enhance his energy level, said
JOC officials.
</P>
<P>
Snooker is making its debut at the Asian Games and the use of
beta blocker-type drugs to counter nerves has been reported.
</P>
<P>
South Korea banned a swimmer and two gymnasts last week from
the Games, which start on December 6, after they tested positive
for banned diuretics which can be used to control weight. 
</P>
</TEXT>
