<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodian CPP Assures Security of Opposition Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Cambodian
People's Party (CPP) reiterated Wednesday that members of all
legal political parties, especially those sworn-in
parliamentarians will have full security and safety assurance.
</P>
<P>
"The King, Second Prime Minister Hun Sen and the Royal
Government will assure you personal safety and legal security
during your stay in the country," Chea Sim and Hun Sen said.
</P>
<P>
It was the response CPP's president Chea Sim and vice-president
Hun Sen had made to opposition FUNCINPE President Prince
Ranariddh, who wrote a letter to them demanding security
assurance.
</P>
<P>
In his letter to Chea Sim and Hun Sen earlier Wednesday,
Ranariddh seeks clarification from them about the politicians who
appear to be excluded from safety and security assurance, as a
statement by the Royal Government's spokesman on November 6 said:
"Those who have a prima facle case to answer to the Court, will
not be allowed to leave the country."
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh also demanded that an agenda be set for any summit
meeting. However, he added that he was encouraged by the ideas
about the government Second Prime Minister Hun Senin said in his
October 22 speech, in which he said he had some common ground with
the political platform of the two oppositions.
</P>
<P>
Chea Sim and Hun Sen in their letter put forward three agendas
for the summit, including the principle of cooperation between the
CPP and FUNCINPEC, the establishment of the system of the National
Assembly and the political platform of the new Royal Government.
</P>
<P>
They also noted the common point of view between Hun Sen's
speech and the political platform put forward by FUNCINPEC and the
Sam Rainsy Party (SRP).
</P>
<P>
Opposition members including Prince Ranariddh and Sam Rainsy
left the country in September, saying they were wary about their
safety. They demanded that any summit be held outside the country.
</P>
<P>
The King told opposition leaders on November 7 that he would
provide security and protection within the palace if they return
for a summit meeting with the CPP.
</P>
<P>
As the monarch is due to leave Cambodia for medical treatment
in Beijing on November 14, no more time is left to organize such a
meeting.
</P>
<P>
The CPP has insisted that any summit must be held in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the pressure from the international community
increased. The Japanese government Tuesday urged the opposition
leaders, particularly Prince Ranariddh, to return to their country
as soon as possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
