<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Date-Based Beef Export Scheme Proposed for Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission
proposed on Wednesday to the European Council of Ministers that
British beef can be exported again under a date-based export
scheme (DBES).
</P>
<P>
When approved by the council of ministers, Britain can expect
to resume exporting de-boned beef and meat products that are
obtained from cattle born after August 1, 1996, and are over six
months but under 30 months of age.
</P>
<P>
A date for the resumption of exports can be established after
the DBES wins approval from the council of ministers, and after the
DBES application and control have been verified.
</P>
<P>
The DBES includes strict rules on identification of cattle and
traceability of cattle and meat, as well as on the slaughter and
destruction of offsprings from mad cow disease-infected cattle.
</P>
<P>
The scheme has been endorsed by the scientific steering
committee under the European Commission, the executive body of the
15-nation European Union.
</P>
<P>
It was also approved by a majority of the member states in the
commission's standing veterinary committee.
</P>
<P>
The European council of agricultural ministers is expected to
deal with the DBES issue during its November 23-24 meeting in
Brussels.
</P>
<P>
If the council neither adopts the commission proposal by a
qualified majority nor rejects it by a simple majority, the
commission can make a final decision on its own. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
