<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Sends More Firepower to Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The United States will send
more warplanes to the Gulf to reinforce its firepower in case
President Bill Clinton orders a military strike against Iraq, a
senior Pentagon official said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The official, who asked not to be identified, said that the
additional forces, which could be ordered to the Gulf on
Wednesday, would include perhaps 50 attack and support jets as
well as several radar-avoiding F-117A stealth fighters.
</P>
<P>
"It could come as early as today," the official said of Defense
Secretary William Cohen's expected order for the move.
</P>
<P>
The United States currently has more than 170 warplanes and 20
Navy ships -- eight of the ships capable of firing long-range
Tomahawk cruise missiles -- poised in the Gulf region near Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon official would not say where the additional
warplanes would be based, although stealth fighters have been
previously based in Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
As the standoff escalated with Iraq over Baghdad's refusal to
cooperate with U.N. weapons inspections, Clinton's top military
strategist warned President Saddam Hussein that the United States
could strike without warning.
</P>
<P>
"From my perspective, I would say that Saddam Hussein has been
given adequate warning... We have seen very strong resolve on the
part of the United Nations," said Gen. Henry Shelton, chairman of
the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
"They are telling him that he needs to honor his commitments
and I think that alone should serve as enough warning," Shelton
said on Wednesday in separate appearances on several U.S.
television networks.
</P>
<P>
"We have a substantial capability. However, as of today, no
decision has been made... all options remain on the table,"
Shelton said.
</P>
<P>
"As we have said in the past, the ball is in Saddam's court. He
is the one that made the commitments after he was defeated in the
Gulf War in 1991... and we expect him to honour his commitments"
Shelton said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton was expected to address the crisis during a Veterans
Day speech at Arlington National Cemetery scheduled for 11:15 a.m.
EST (1615 GMT) on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials have repeatedly said that Clinton has not made a
final decision on whether force will be used against Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
