<HEADLINE> China to Open Downtown Tax-Free Shops in Large Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, November 11 (Xinhua) -- China plans to open a number
of downtown tax-free shops in several major cities next
year, an official source said here today.
</P>
<P>
Beijing, Shanghai and Guangzhou, capital of south China's
Guangdong Province, are the top candidates for the planned shops,
according to Ge Zhixin, general manager of the China Tax-Free
Commodities Company.
</P>
<P>
The introduction of the new shops represents China's latest
move into tax-free businesses, which has been developing for the
past ten years or so, Ge said.
</P>
<P>
Though Shanghai has four tax-free shops at the airport and some
other places with large concentrations of overseas people, this is
far from adequate for the rapidly growing number of overseas
people arriving in the city, he said.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that Shanghai's international tourism
industry has been growing at an average annual rate of 10 percent
in recent years, with overseas tourists numbering 1.65 million last
year.
</P>
<P>
Downtown tax-free shops will provide greater convenience for
overseas people in Shanghai, Ge said.
</P>
<P>
It is learned that Shanghai's first downtown tax-free shop will
be located at a spot convenient to traffic in Puxi, the older part
of the metropolitan, and will sell mainly high-grade brand-name
commodities imported from Europe and the United States.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
