<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EC President Appeals for Clinton's Attention to Banana Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission (EC)
has urged U.S. President Bill Clinton to personally attend to the
renewed banana dispute between his country and the European Union
(EU), a commission spokesman said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The EC president, Jacques Santer, has written a letter to
Clinton drawing his attention to a serious difficulty in bilateral
trade relations.
</P>
<P>
The problem risks much wider economic and political
repercussions, Santer warned.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. published a list on Tuesday of EU export products for
possible punitive tariffs.
</P>
<P>
The listed products, ranging from wine, toys, perfume,
ball-pens, bread and vacuum cleaners, are worth an estimated total
of 1.3 billion ECU (1.43 billion U.S. dollars), according to the
EC which is the executive body of the EU.
</P>
<P>
Santer described the U.S. unilateral action for trade sanction
as a "clear breach of the United States' World Trade Organization
commitments.
</P>
<P>
"No WTO member has the right unilaterally to determine whether
another member is in compliance with WTO rulings," Santer said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. publication of the list came as a shock only one day
after the EU foreign ministers endorsed a Transatlantic Economic
Partnership action plan to enhance bilateral trade.
</P>
<P>
Sir Leon Brittan, vice-president of the commission, and U.S.
Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky discussed the banana
issue Friday.
</P>
<P>
Santer said in his letter that pursuing the unilateral action
is a grave political misjudgement at a time when the
U.S. and the EU "should be working together in shared leadership
to alleviate the world's economic difficulties."
</P>
<P>
The commission chief also said the union would be obliged to
react if the U.S. chose to continue its unilateral action.
</P>
<P>
Santer notified Clinton that the EU would raise the banana
dispute at the November 23 meeting of the WTO Dispute Settlement
Body unless the U.S. decided to desist from the unilateral action
before the meeting.
</P>
<P>
After a WTO ruling against EU's banana import regime, the union
modified the regime in July this year.
</P>
<P>
However, the U.S. argued that the new regime is still not
compatible with the WTO regulations.
</P>
<P>
The EU and the U.S. are each other's single largest trading
partner in the world. In 1997, they traded goods worth 277
billion ECU (304.7 billion dollars), or one fifth of their total
world trade volume. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
