<HEADLINE> U.N. Humanitarian Program to Continue: U.N. Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. humanitarian program
for Iraq will continue though some non-essential staff of the
U.N. Office of the Humanitarian Coordinator for Iraq (UNOHCI) will
be "temporarily relocated," said a U.N. envoy Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Prakash Shah, representative of U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan in Iraq, said at a press conference here that about 30
essential officials of the UNOHCI will stay in Iraq and
humanitarian program will continue.
</P>
<P>
Shah said he held a meeting with Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister
Tariq Aziz Wednesday morning and informed him of the decision of
the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) to withdraw all its personnel
and the temporary relocation of some of the non-essential UNOHCI
staff.
</P>
<P>
He said Aziz has told him that Iraq will not reverse its
October 31 decision to halt cooperation with UNSCOM, which has
overseen the destruction of all Iraq's biological and chemical
weapons and long-range missiles, unless the U.N. Security Council
takes some actions that lead to the lifting of trade sanctions
imposed on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. exerted sanctions on Iraq following its invasion of
Kuwait in 1990, sparking the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council maintains that the sanctions will not be
removed unless UNSCOM certifies that Baghdad has eradicated all
its weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, at least 400 weapons inspectors and other
U.N. staff left Baghdad as the U.N. began withdrawing all its
"non-essential" personnel to prepare for a possible U.S. military
strike against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain have warned that force will be resorted to
try to force Iraq into obedience of U.N. resolutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
