<HEADLINE> Lebanese School Teachers on Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, November 11 (Xinhua) -- As part of their open-ended
strike, about 500 Lebanese public high school teachers Wednesday
staged a sit-in in front of the Education Ministry to protest
against the salary scales bill newly approved by the parliament.
</P>
<P>
The strike, beginning on Monday, followed a two-day warning
strike in October to protest the parliament's failure to recognize
the teachers' demands in the new salary bill, a source of High
School Teachers' Union said.
</P>
<P>
Public high school and primary school teachers demanded that
their end-of-service payments be based on 100 percent of their
final salaries in the new pay scale bill for the public sector.
</P>
<P>
The new bill, approved by the parliament last month, stipulates
however that end-of-service payments would only be based on 85
percent of the teachers' final salaries.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue our strike until our demands are met," Fouad
Saab, chairman of the teachers union told the protesters who
consist of teachers, students and a number of parliament members.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Minister of National Education, Youth and Sport Jean
Obeid told the angry teachers that he supported their demands but
called on them to move their sit-in protest to the parliament.
</P>
<P>
House Speaker Nabih Berri dismissed the protest as
"inappropriate" and called on protesters to stop it.
</P>
<P>
The strike halted classes for some 350,000 public school
students across the country, but those in 800 private schools are
not affected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
