<HEADLINE> France Marks 80th Anniversary of World War I Armistice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 11 (Xinhua) -- France on Wednesday marked the
80th anniversary of the World War I armistice under the shadow of
the Germany's refusal to attend a ceremony in commemoration of the
dead.
</P>
<P>
Queen Elizabeth II of Britain, who was invited to join the
traditional ceremony in Paris this year, laid flowers with French
President Jacques Chirac at the tomb of the Unknown Soldier.
</P>
<P>
The queen and Chirac also laid flowers before a statue of
Georges Clemenceau, the French prime minister during the World War
I. They were also due to inaugurate a statue of former British
Prime Minister Winston Churchill at the Cours de la Reine by the
Seine River late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Six former "Poilu" soldiers, aged from 98 to 107, who fought
during the World War I, attended the ceremony under the Arch of
Triumph.
</P>
<P>
At the request of German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, France
and Germany cancelled a plan to issue a joint communique on
November 8 during a planned ceremony at Vrigne-Meuse in the
northeastern province of Ardennes, where the last major battle of
the war was fought.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder turned down the invitation from Chirac to attend the
ceremony with the excuse of "timetable."
</P>
<P>
The French press, which widely commented on the event, said
that Schroeder preferred to ignore the anniversary rather than
reminding his German compatriots of the unfortunate days of the
war.
</P>
<P>
The anniversary was also preceded by a dispute between Chirac
and Prime Minister Lionel Jospin over a declaration by Jospin that
the reputation of 48 French mutinous soldiers executed in 1917 at
the order of Marshal Philippe Petain should be rehabilitated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
