<HEADLINE> Canada Will Send Relief to Starving Russians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Canada is preparing a
multimillion-dollar package of humanitarian relief for Russia's
remote Arctic regions to help avert starvation, the Globe and Mail
newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Canadian assistance will include food, clothing and
possibly medicine and fuel. One official was quoted by the
newspaper as saying that the aid will be worth about 2 million
Canadian dollars (1.3 million U.S. dollars) in the first phase of
what could became a larger program.
</P>
<P>
The assistance was discussed at a private dinner in Moscow
Tuesday night between Canadian Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd
Axworthy and his Russian counterpart Igor Ivanov, said the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Many people living in isolated towns and villages in the
Russian far north are facing the danger of malnutrition because
of the Russian economic crisis which has hampered the shipment of
supplies. Food and fuel shortages have left many northerners in a
desperate situation.
</P>
<P>
Russia's 200,000 aboriginal people, concentrated primarily in
the far north, are among the worst-hit by the crisis, said the
newspaper. 
</P>
