<HEADLINE> Kenya Shilling Remains Strong Against Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 11 (Xinhua) - The Kenya Shilling remained
unchanged against the U.S. Dollar in thin trade Wednesday,
commercial dealers said here.
</P>
<P>
Four leading commercial banks posted the Shilling at buying
rate of 59.55 and 59.65 selling to the Dollar, same as the
Tuesday's closing rates. Two banks quoted the Shilling at
59.50/62 to the Dollar.
</P>
<P>
"We have not seen inflows from the coffee and tea sector as it
is normally the case on Monday and Tuesday," one dealer said.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said some players in the two sectors were holding
Dollars, limiting the supply side.
</P>
<P>
"Most of these companies in the tea and coffee sector are
multi-nationals now preparing to pay their international
share-holders dividends in Dollars," said Philip Wambua, head of
foreign exchange at the Treasury Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Dealers' sentiment was shifting toward a weaker Shilling. One
dealer said that the central bank's presence in the market was
felt Wednesday, probably to fulfill its requirements.
</P>
<P>
The overnight interbank market was liquid, pegged at eight to
12 percent.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the rates would remain at the same level until
the second circle of the month when banks start paying out their
tax obligations.
</P>
<P>
The central bank posted a mean Shilling indicative rate of
59.5833 to the Dollar against 59.5911 Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Against the Pound, the Shilling was quoted at 98.6351 buying
and 98.87 selling Monday from 98.97 buying and 99.18 selling on
Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
