<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 11(Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt has approved the implementation of three
enterprises in the Delta governorate of Al-Sharqia, the Egyptian
Gazette newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Economic advisor to governor Diaa Eddin Omran said the
total capital of the enterprises stands at 860 million Egyptian
pounds (253 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
One project is an electrical appliances factory with a capital
of 260 million pounds (76 million dollars). It is expected to
produce an annual 180 million pounds (53 million dollars) worth of
products after its operation in five years.
</P>
<P>
A second is a car factory with a capital of 420 million pounds
(124 million dollars). It is located at an industrial zone on the
road linking Belbeis, a town 50 kilometers north of Cairo, with
the capital.
</P>
<P>
The third is an iron factory, which is designed to produce an
annual 100,000 tonnes of iron in the initial stage and increase
the production to 400,000 tonnes of iron within five years.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Egyptian General Authority of Investment and Free
Zones signed Tuesday an agreement with Belarus for bilateral
cooperation in free zones and training, it was disclosed Wednesday
by the authority chairman, Ibrahim Fawzi.
</P>
<P>
He said under the agreement, the two countries will cooperate,
through businessmen, investors and government circles in either
country, in exchanging expertise in the fields of establishing and
operating free zones, in putting up joint investment projects, and
in improving the related technical skills and the administration
of free economic and industrial zones.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Secretary General of the Arab League Economic Union
Council Hasan Ibrahim has announced effective implementation of
the rules of the common Arab market, within the framework of the
Arab economic union agreement.
</P>
<P>
Ibrahim said that on January 1, 1999, custom duties will be
reduced by 30 per cent, another 30 per cent in January 2000, and
the remaining 40 per cent reduction in January 2001. Likewise,
non-customs restrictions will be completely abolished by January
2000, taking into consideration the conditions of the least
developed countries.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Palestinian National Authority signed an
agreement Tuesday, under which the European Union would offer 200
European currency units (ECU) (about 23 million dollars) to
finance municipality projects in the West Bank and Gaza towns.
</P>
<P>
The signing ceremony between Palestinian Development and
Rehabilitation Establishment (PDRE) and European Union
representatives was attended by Palestinian President Yasser
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Ramallah quote PDRE director Mohamed Ashteh who
signed the agreement, as saying that it represents the third
EU grant to Palestinian municipalities, and that it has been
preceded by two other grants.
</P>
<P>
He added that the agreement would be implemented over four
years during which the PDRE would carry out a number of
infrastructure projects in Palestinian towns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
