<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Government Rejects Cannabis for Drug Use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 11 (Reuters) -- The British government on
Wednesday rejected a call from a House of Lords committee to make
cannabis available on prescription.
</P>
<P>
Home Office Minister George Howarth said more clinical trials
are needed before a change in the drug laws could be considered.
</P>
<P>
"Until we get a product that's gone through all of the same
testing regimes as any other drug, it would be irresponsible," he
told BBC radio.
</P>
<P>
Patients groups, politicians and even anti-drug campaigners
welcomed a report released by the House of Lords' Science and
Technology Committee that recommends licensing the drug to help
alleviate the pain caused by conditions such as multiple sclerosis
(MS) and cancer.
</P>
<P>
But the British Medical Association, which represents the
medical practitioners, describes the move as "misguided."
</P>
<P>
The Lords' committee chairman, Lord Perry, said, "There is
sufficient evidence of benefit to many patients to make it
unjustifiable and inhumane to make them wait.
</P>
<P>
"We remain fully supportive of the view that the recreational
use of cannabis should remain illegal.
</P>
<P>
"But the fact is that heroin, morphine and cocaine are all
licensed drugs and that doesn't increase their misuse at all."
</P>
<P>
The committee estimated that about 1 percent of MS patients
use cannabis for pain relief, effectively making themselves
criminals under current law.
</P>
<P>
British doctors were allowed to prescribe cannabis until
1973. It was then removed from a list of prescription drugs which
still includes heroin and morphine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
