<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's MPR Factions Respond Seriously to Calls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Public calls for a thorough
investigation of state officials allegedly involved in corruption,
collusion and nepotism (KKN) received serious response from
factions of the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR) here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the presentation of general views on the draft
decree during the second day of the MPR's special session,
spokesman for the ruling Functional Group faction Marwah Daud
Ibrahim said the more officials involved in such illegal
practices, the greater the impact on the legitimacy of the
government.
</P>
<P>
"Efforts to uphold the law must be stepped up, and those
allegedly involved in KKN-tainted practices must be dealt with,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The faction, he said, is also urging the judicial apparatus to
be probative in investigating former and present government
officials, including former president Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
He underscored the need to uphold the presumption of innocence
and the principles of human rights in probing these officials.
</P>
<P>
He made it clear that one of the demands for reform is the
creation of good governance free from corruption, collusion and
nepotism.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian nation, he said, is suffering from a crisis of
confidence originating from its economic and political crisis, the
result of poor control of administrative tasks due to the
concentration of power.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, spokesman for the United Development Party (PPP)
faction Aisyah Amini said since Soeharto was formerly Indonesia's
number one person, he must be the first person to be subjected to
the investigation.
</P>
<P>
She emphasized the need for the special MPR session to
stipulate a decree authorizing the government to look into
Soeharto's hidden wealth.
</P>
<P>
Some reports said the property of Soeharto and his family has
reached about 20 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing MPR special session, which opened on Tuesday, will
decide the timetable for the forthcoming general election in 1999
and approve some important decrees.  
</P>
</TEXT>
