<HEADLINE> Namibia Confirms Reinforcing Troops in Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Namibia Wednesday
confirmed that it was reinforcing its troops in the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC) ahead of an expected offensive in the
east of the vast central African country.
</P>
<P>
Namibian troops and equipment were being deployed in the east
of Congo (K), South African Press Association quoted Namibian
Defense Ministry spokesman Vincent Mwange as saying.
</P>
<P>
Mwange confirmed that the troops now being sent to Congo would
operate in the combat zone and would not be restricted to
logistical roles.
</P>
<P>
But he refused to comment on a weekend news report that the
number of troops was being increased to 2,000.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the decision to deploy more Namibian troops
was taken after Congolese President Laurent Kabila's allies
agreed in Zimbabwean capital Harare on October 28 to launch a new
offensive against the Tutsi-led rebels in east Congo.
</P>
<P>
Namibia, Zimbabwe and Angola sent troops to Congo in August to
prop up the embattled troops loyal to Kabila. Congo claimed that
Rwanda and Uganda were backing the rebels in the country.
</P>
<P>
Despite several regional peace initiatives to bring the
warring parties to the negotiation table in the past three
months, no solution is in sight to end the war in the Great Lakes
region.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Namibian troops and arms arrived on cargo
planes in Kananga in Congo's Western Kasai Province over the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
Namibia has so far confirmed two deaths among its soldiers in
Congo (K). 
</P>
</TEXT>
