<HEADLINE> 98'China Anti-Forgery Technology Exhibition Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The four-day 98' China
Anti-Forgery Technology Exhibition opened in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 80 technological research institutions and enterprises
from home and abroad are attending the exhibition, which is being
held jointly by the Ministry of Public Security and the
Anti-Forgery Technology Association of China.
</P>
<P>
The high-tech products on display, including anti-forgery
signets, watermarks, trademarks and technology applied in the
production of various cards and certificates, all reflect the
present state of such technology development in China.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of enterprises and research institutions will also
present lectures introducing their anti-forgery technology and
products during the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
Many of these products are beautiful in design, and the use of
techniques such as signatures, microphotos and fingerprints in the
products make them extremely difficult to copy.
</P>
<P>
Officials with the Ministry of Public Security pointed to two
reasons for the serious forgery problem in China: most enterprises
and consumers have not become aware of the importance of
anti-forgery technology, and the government's management system
has yet to be strengthened.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that local governments have cracked 4,527 cases
of forgery, uncovered 625 factories producing fake products,
levied fines or confiscated illicit income in the amount of 9.7
million yuan (1.17 million U.S. dollars), and burned 90 million
yuan (10.7 million U.S. dollars) worth of fake products, in just
the past two years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
