<HEADLINE> Pak Foreign Office Employees Sentenced for Espionage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 11 (Xinhua) -- A court in Pakistan has
awarded a ten-year imprisonment each to four Foreign Ministry
employees on the charge of providing sensitive documents on the
country's foreign policy and national security to India.
</P>
<P>
Abdul Hameed Khattak, Special judge of the central court in
Rawalpindi, twin city of Islamabad, announced the verdict on
Tuesday as the accused, who were on bail, were arrested from the
court room, the private News Net work International (NNI) reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Investigation Agency (FIA) had registered the
famous "Espionage Case" against the four on the charge of
providing key documents about Pakistan's security to India in
1989, NNI said.
</P>
<P>
The accused had been arrested by the FIA when they were
proceeding to hand over the documents to the Indian High
Commissioner, it said. 
</P>
