<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Ruling Golkar Agrees to Gradually Limit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's ruling Golkar
(Functional Group) faction in the People's Consultative Assembly
(MPR) agreed to limit the role of the Armed Forces (ABRI)
gradually and systematically as of 1999.
</P>
<P>
This was stated by Golkar faction's spokesperson Marwah Daud
Ibrahim while making the statement during a general review on
various draft decrees at the Assembly's 1998 special session here
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The faction holds that, gauging people's current aspirations,
discussion about ABRI's representation in the legislative
assemblies is urgent and needs to be carried out openly in the
special session.
</P>
<P>
Based on a comprehensive study and understanding on aspirations
of Indonesia's pluralistic people, the Golkar faction believes
that the limitation of ABRI's social and political role is closely
related with the development and empowerment of a civil society.
</P>
<P>
Ideally, the Golkar faction said, ABRI's presence in
legislative assemblies will only be retained in the MPR, and the
special session needs to emphasize that ABRI's representation in
the House of Representatives (DPR) is temporary.
</P>
<P>
The Armed Forces' sociopolitical role stems from the "dual
function" doctrine, accorded legitimacy during the heyday of the
New Order regime of former president Soeharto. Under this
doctrine, ABRI was recognized not only as a defense and security
force, but also as a sociopolitical one.
</P>
<P>
With Soeharto stepped down on May 21, Indonesian newspapers
said, the country is now striving to dismantle the repressive
political system that the autocratic ruler built. This includes
calls to review ABRI's political role, seen by critics as part and
parcel of the New Order regime.
</P>
<P>
In an attempt to restore its tarnished image, ABRI has agreed
to scale down its sociopolitical role. On Monday, ABRI Commander
Gen. Wiranto announced that he was scrapping the strategic
sociopolitical chief post in ABRI headquarters, and would require
all ABRI personnel to retire from the service if they wished to
serve in non-military posts.
</P>
<P>
ABRI has also agreed to reduce the number of its 75
representatives in the 500-member DPR, but has left it to the DPR,
which is deliberating the new political bills, to determine the
precise number.
</P>
<P>
Chief of ABRI faction in the MPR Lt. Gen. Soesilo Bambang
Yudhoyono said that the military is now prepared to see a gradual
elimination of its presence in the DPR. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Opposes Use of Force Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov on Wednesday reiterated Moscow's opposition to the use of
force against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov told reporters after his meeting with visiting Canadian
Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy that force would not resolve the
problem.
</P>
<P>
Instead, it "would wipe out the immense work done by the
international community over the past seven years and complicate
the situation in the region," Ivanov said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ivanov urged Baghdad to reconsider its "decision to
stop cooperating with the United Nations special commission for
the disarmament of Iraq and resume full cooperation."
</P>
<P>
Also on Wednesday, the U.N. announced that it would withdraw
its non-essential personnel from Iraq to neighboring Jordan amid
rising concern of possible U.S. air strikes.
</P>
<P>
"A comprehensive revision of Iraq's disarmament files should be
carried out to determine which of them can be considered closed
and which should be considered open," Ivanov said.
</P>
<P>
"This should pave the way for ending the sanctions against
Iraq," he added, noting Russia would continue working with other
countries, Baghdad and U.N. secretary-general Kofi Annan in
finding a way out of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has said it will not cooperate with U.N. inspectors until
the U.N. Security Council begins to lift an embargo imposed after
Iraqi forces invaded Kuwait in 1990. The Security Council
maintains the embargo won't be lifted until U.N. inspectors
certify that Iraq has surrendered its weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the Russian State Duma, or lower
house of parliament, rejected a proposal by the Liberal Democratic
Party of Russia (LDPR) on Wednesday that Russia stop observing the
international economic sanctions against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The proposal garnered only 126 votes, shorter than the 226
needed for passage.
</P>
<P>
The LDPR parliamentary group, led by Vladimir Zhirinovsky who
visited Baghdad last month, proposed that the Duma express concern
over the long duration of the sanctions and rule out their
extension.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq no longer represents a threat to international security
or the security of neighboring countries," said the draft
resolution prepared by the LDPR. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
