<HEADLINE> Israeli Cabinet Resumes Peace Accord Deliberation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli cabinet resumed
its deliberations on the Wye peace accord Wednesday afternoon and
will probably vote on it later in the evening.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet halted discussion of the accord last Friday after a
bomb attack in Jerusalem. Ministers said they would not reconvene
until they were satisfied that the Palestinians would wage all-out
war on anti-Israel militants.
</P>
<P>
The Wye accord, known as the Wye River Memorandum, provides
for the phased handover of 13 percent more of the West Bank to the
Palestinians over 12 weeks, matched by specific Palestinian steps
against Islamic militants.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and other officials have
expressed frustration at Israeli delays in endorsing the accord,
signed at the White House last month by Arafat and Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's legal counsel Yitzhak Molcho went to Ramallah
Wednesday morning to inform Arafat about Israeli cabinet's
scheduled meeting on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton phoned Netanyahu Tuesday evening
and urged him to go ahead with ratification of the accord.
</P>
<P>
If the accord was approved by the cabinet, it would be sent to
the Knesset (parliament) for approval probably on Thursday or next
Monday, according to a senior Israeli government official.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-five Israelis were injured and the two assailants were
killed in last Friday's car bombing near Jerusalem's Mahane Yehuda
market. The Palestinian Islamic Jihad (holy war fighters) claimed
responsibility for the attack. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
