<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exporters to Sterilize Packaging for U.S.-Bound Goods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Local exporters have been
ordered to obtain quarantine certificates for goods exported to
the United States, which has stepped up efforts to prevent the
entry of the Asian long-horned beetle.
</P>
<P>
The order was made in response to a decree issued on September
11 by the American secretary of agriculture who asked for
certificates on packaging for commodities imported from China, in
a bid to curb the spread of the pest which is said to be a greedy
eater of trees.
</P>
<P>
Under the decree issued by the related Chinese governmental
departments, local exporters now must obtain certificates from
quarantine departments to prove that the wooden packaging for their
U.S.-bound goods have been fumigated or treated with antiseptics.
</P>
<P>
For U.S.-bound items shipped in packing material other than wood,
exporters must produce certificates on their own.
</P>
<P>
U.S.-bound exports which fail to meet these requirements will
be refused entry, or will have their wooden packages destroyed,
with the consent of the U.S. side, the orders say.
</P>
<P>
To ensure the smooth flow of exports into the U.S., Chinese
authorities have urged local exporters to use packing materials
other than wood, and for goods that must be shipped in wood
packages, exporters must sterilize the packages and obtain the
certificates.
</P>
<P>
Authorities also have encouraged local exporters to use cheaper
and better packing materials, the orders say.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea Expects to Attract 42 Billion Dollars in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, November 11 (Xinhua) -- South Korea is expected to see a
inflow of 42 billion U.S. dollars in foreign capital in 1999 due
to a current account surplus and increased foreign investment, the
Bank of Korea said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In its report on the supply and demand of foreign exchange in
1999, the central bank said South Korea will receive enough
foreign currency to pay off 36 billion dollars of maturing
foreign debts and increase its foreign exchange reserves next year.
</P>
<P>
The bank predicted that South Korea would register a surplus of
18 billion dollars in current accounts in the coming year by
reducing imports and falling international oil prices.
</P>
<P>
Direct and indirect foreign investments are forecast to reach
15 billion dollars due to the nation's ongoing corporate and
financial restructuring.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's long-term borrowing by banks will reach five
billion dollars next year, while loans from the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) and other global organizations are expected to
hit four billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Overseas obligations maturing next year will amount to 31
billion dollars, excluding five billion raised abroad by overseas
branches of South Korean companies, said the bank.
</P>
<P>
The 31 billion dollars in liabilities include 17 billion
borrowed by financial institutions, four billion by private
enterprises, and 10 billion by the public sector.
</P>
<P>
"We won't have any trouble repaying foreign debts next
year. When corporate restructuring wraps up and our credit ratings
are upgraded, foreign investment is likely to increase further,"
said a spokesman of the central bank.
</P>
<P>
South Korea will also be relieved of its borrowing rate burden
next year if the United States and other advanced countries cut
interest rates again, added the spokesman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 12:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Stock Exchange Index Closes Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait Stock Exchange
index edged up by 6.8 points from that on Tuesday to close at
1,897.1 points Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The turnover also rose to 5.28 million Kuwaiti dinars (17.42
million U.S. dollars), compared with 2.32 million dinars(7.65
million dollars).
</P>
<P>
A total of 25.35 million shares changed hands Wednesday in 856
deals as against 11.05 million shares in 370 deals in the
previous day. 
</P>
