<HEADLINE> China Hands Over Water Facility to Swaziland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MBABANE, Swaziland, November 11 (Xinhua) -- An urban water
supply project was formally handed over to Swaziland Tuesday
afternoon by a Chinese engineering company.
</P>
<P>
The project, carried out by China Wanbao Engineering
Corporation, was part of a 50-million-U.S.-Dollar urban
development package funded by the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The project, which pumps about 230 cubic meters of water per
hour to an altitude of 210 meters, will benefit 2,500 people. But
the fact that it has a reservoir of 3,200 cubic meters means that
there could be far more beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
It consists of a sole powerful pump station and an
11-kilometer pipeline.
</P>
<P>
The two-million-U.S.-Dollar project starts from downtown
Mbabane and ends upon a nearby mountain which is to be developed.
</P>
<P>
Head of the technical support unit of the project, John
Lowsby, said that more development projects would follow up and
the water supply project was expected to have its first
beneficiaries by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Swazi Prince Masitsela and Wanbao President Wang Xiao attended
a brief hand-over ceremony at the reservoir.
</P>
<P>
The project is the first won by Wanbao in an African country
with which China has no formal ties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
