<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Launches Training Center for Sports Marketing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Asia's first-ever
commercial institute for the training of sports marketing and
entertainment management was launched here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
As the region's latest innovation in the high-profile field of
sports and entertainment, the Center for Sports Marketing &AMP;
Entertainment Management is designed to enhance the
professionalism of the event management/marketing industry, said
the center's chairman Steven Feuerstein.
</P>
<P>
It offers a highly specialized 12-week curriculum, addressing
subjects such as the sponsor's psychology, broadcasting and
advertising, public relations, negotiation and deal making, event
operations and logistics, client servicing promotional campaigns
and joint marketing ventures, he told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The center's target markets include mid-level managers, first
and second-time job seekers who are in need of vocational
expertise, artists and athletes, and government employees, said
Feuerstein, a ten-year veteran of the industry and president of
Hong Kong-based Sports International Ltd.
</P>
<P>
"The training needed to work professionally within all sectors
of our industry is simply not available in Hong Kong or anywhere
else in Asia. Whether you're a brand manager, event planner,
promoter, ad agency or public relations executive, the necessary
management skills are traditionally only learned on the job. And
that is exactly what the center is going to change," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Sports marketing and entertainment management is a
multi-billion dollars business, with over 17 billion U.S. dollars
being invested on event sponsorship alone each year, according to
Feuerstein.
</P>
<P>
Also attending the press conference was Andrew Ma, the chief
executive of the Sports Development Board. He said that the
center is exactly what the market needs and will clearly play a
major role in the further upgrading of the quality of the
industry in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The first series of the program started on October 19 and will
run through December 14, with participants meeting once a week
for a two-and-a-half-hour seminar held at the Sports Development
Board's Sports House. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
