<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier on Closing of Coal Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Shutting down coal mines that
are operating illegally or have been planned irrationally is
another major step in the current reform to pull China's coal
industry out of stagnation.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Premier Wu Bangguo made this remark today at a national
conference on closing down coal mines and reducing coal output.
</P>
<P>
Since China adopted the policy of reform and opening-up in the
late 1970s, the country has experienced a rapid increase in the
number of the coal mines, especially smaller ones, according to
Wu, who is also a member of the Political Bureau of the Communist
Party of China (CPC) Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the normal operation of the industry has been
plagued with problems such as redundancy and the over-opening of
coal mines, illegal mining, environmental pollution, and excessive
production.
</P>
<P>
The central government has adopted three measures to offset the
negative impacts of the rampant coal industry, including handing
over all 94 state-run coal mines, which were under the former
Ministry of Coal Industry, to provincial governments, closing some
mines to reduce output, and dispatching special inspectors to the
mines, according to the vice-premier.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1999, 25,800 small coal mines will be shut down
to bring down the national annual output by some 250 million
tons. Mines to be shut down are those which have been operating
without official approval, those operating on the sites of
state-owned mines, and those which have obtained official
certificates but are now regarded as irrationally planned.
</P>
<P>
Wu urged carrying out the program strictly in accordance with
the relevant state laws. While this program is being implemented,
he noted, no new coal mines will be allowed to open, and those
which have obtained illegal permission and are shut down will
receive certain compensations.
</P>
<P>
This program will be carried out in combination with a
prohibition on illegally mined coal entering the market, Wu said.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0129 </DOCNO>
