<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Botswana Probing 300 Namibian Secessionists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The Botswanan government
is investigating more than 300 Namibian secessionists who crossed
into Botswana in the past weeks seeking asylum, South African
state television reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Despite Namibia's request for immediate extradition of these
people, the Botswanan government said Wednesday that they would
assess each individual's status before making a decision.
</P>
<P>
"The circumstances of each member of the group have to be
individually assessed, and this will take some time," Botswanan
presidential spokesman Andrew Sesinyi said, adding that none of
them has been granted asylum.
</P>
<P>
"They are asking for protection against forcible return to
Namibia, where they claim their lives and freedom would be in
jeopardy," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Namibians, who illegally entered Botswana in several
groups, were believed to be from a group planning the secession
of the Caprivi strip in northeastern Namibia. They reportedly
fled their country after their planned armed secession was
unearthed recently.
</P>
<P>
"We are working amicably with the Namibians over the issue. We
have no sympathy for anyone who wishes to harm or negatively
affect the Namibian government," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, Sesinyi said the United Nations High Commissioner for
Refugees (UNHCR) had advised them not to sent these people back,
as they might face persecution upon return.
</P>
<P>
The presence of Namibians in Botswana has complicated the
already difficult relations between the two neighbors. The two
countries' dispute over the islands in the border river
Linyanti-Chobe is currently in front of the International High
Court for Justice.
</P>
<P>
Among the border jumpers are former Namibian opposition leader
Meshake Muyongo, a regional governor of Caprivi; Johnnie Mabuku,
a member of the Namibian House of Review; and national councilor
Francis Sizimbo.
</P>
<P>
About 100 border jumpers have already appeared before
Botswanan court, on charges of illegally entering the country and
being in possession of weapons of war, including AK-47 rifles,
mortars, bombs and anti-personnel mines.
</P>
<P>
Namibian President Sam Nujoma has called on Botswana to
extradite the "terrorist bandits" so they could be charged with
treason.
</P>
<P>
The Caprivi strip in Namibia's northeast covers an area of
about 20,000 square kilometers and has a population of close to
110,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
