<HEADLINE> China Further Standardizing Environmental Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 11 (Xinhua) -- China announced the
appointment of its first 549 registered auditors, six
certification organs, and 11 consultative institutes of
environmental management systems (EMS) here today.
</P>
<P>
An official from the State Environmental Protection
Administration said at a news conference that China's first group
of EMS-registered auditors and certification and consultative
organs will help standardize environmental control in the country.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Xingxiang, secretary general of the China Steering
Committee for Environmental Management System Certification, said
that the environment and resources are pressing issues for China
at present, and that the country has introduced ISO14000, a set of
international standards for environmental management, which will
help improve the environmental management system.
</P>
<P>
He said China established two special councils, the
Environmental Management Council of China Registration Board for
Auditors (EMCCRBA), and the China Accreditation Council for
Environmental Management System Certification Bodies (CACEB) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The EMCCRBA is in charge of examining qualifications,
registration, and training of environmental overseers, and the
CACEB is responsible for certifying environmental groups. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Benefits From Foreign Direct Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Uganda has been named among
the first eight African countries that benefit from foreign
direct investment (FDI).
</P>
<P>
According to a World Investment Report Launched Wednesday,
Uganda's FDI inflow from 1992 to 1997 were above the developing
countries' average, Uganda News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The FDI inflow in Uganda has mainly concentrated in the
primary sector of agro-processing, mining, tourism and
manufacturing. It increased from 121 million U.S. Dollars in 1996
to 250 million Dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The report was reportedly launched by the Minister of State
for Finance Sam Kuteesa who attributed the country's superior
performance to a stable macro-economic policy framework.
</P>
<P>
He also challenged the Uganda Investment Authority to maintain
the trend of FDI flow to expand on the number of policies that
investors view as constituting a good investment climate.
</P>
<P>
Other African countries listed in the report include Botswana,
Equatorial Guinea, Ghana, Mozambique, Namibia and Tunisia.
</P>
</TEXT>
