<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Closely Watch U.S. Attempts to Speed up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian delegation to a
forthcoming Summit of the Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation Forum
(APEC) will closely watch U.S. endeavors to get the meeting to
agree to an accelerated liberalization of the world economy, a
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a meeting with President B.J.
Habibie here Wednesday, Indonesian Ambassador to the U.S.
Dorodjatun Kuntjorojakti said the U.S. had been making the same
efforts at other international fora.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. would host a World Trade Organization (WTO)
ministerial meeting in Washington next year and use the meeting's
commitments as a platform to promote global economic
liberalization in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The superpower's interest in an accelerated liberalization
process was very obvious, particularly from its role in the
establishment of the Free Trade Areas for America which groups 34
countries in the American continent, from Canada to Argentina, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian media had not been sufficiently reporting on these
developments, he added.
</P>
<P>
Kuntjorojakti said the U.S. would use the APEC Economic Leaders
Meeting to be held in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia this month as a
springboard to take advantage of the first post-Cold War decade to
accelerate liberalization of the global economy.
</P>
<P>
This must be watched by the Indonesian delegations to (the APEC
meeting) and the APEC Business Advisory Council to be attended by
about 1,500 business representatives from all APEC members, he
said.
</P>
<P>
It seemed that current economic conditions were posing no
problem to the U.S. to achieve its goal, he added. 
</P>
