<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading French newspapers on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- France will memorize on Wednesday the 80th anniversary of
the end of the World War I, during which 870 French soldiers were
killed and 2,300 injured each day. The echo of this massacre is
still heard 80 years later, as France is still disputing whether
the day should be the celebration of patriotism or the souvenir of
a great butchery.
</P>
<P>
-- Germany will not mark the 80th anniversary of end of World
War I. German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder has turned down an
invitation by President Jacques Chirac to commemorate the dead of
the World War I, because he prefers looking forward to letting
Germany locked up in the role of the defeated and the eternal
guilty, said an expert on Germany.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- Queen Elizabeth II of Britain will join President Jacques
Chirac on Wednesday morning in paying homage to the tomb of
Unknown Soldier under the Arch of Triumph on the Champs Elysee on
the 80th anniversary of the end of the World War I, in which
1,383,000 Frenchmen and 1,822,000 Germans were killed, not to
account others who died.
</P>
<P>
-- Over the past 12 months, inflation rate in France stood at
0.4-0.5 percent, which was the lowest in Europe. The lowering of
the prices are due to the dropping costs of food and oil. 
</P>
