<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IPR System Faces Impact of Digital Technology (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The worldwide information
technology revolution has endangered the existing intellectual
property rights system which traditionally protected print and
audio-visual publications, trademarks and inventions.
</P>
<P>
"The emergence of various types of digital forms and the large
number computers connected to network and the Internet have
sparked a series of new copyright issues and had a strong impact
on the existing copyright protection system," according to Ying
Ming, a senior researcher with China's Ministry of Information
Industry.
</P>
<P>
"While digital technology has had a profound impact on the
current copyright system it is nonetheless unnecessary to abandon
the existing system," said Ying, an adviser with the ministry's
Computer and Microelectronics Industry Research and Development
Center."
</P>
<P>
"However, It might be necessary to introduce new concepts or
alter existing approaches in order to improve the current
copyright system," said Ying.
</P>
<P>
The existing Law on Copyrights focuses on various forms of
characters, figures, visual images and sound. A highly
sophisticated copyright protection system for related works has
been developed in many countries throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
However, broad applications of computer software have had a
strong impact on the existing copyright system and have sparked an
international debate in the field for the past 20-odd years.
</P>
<P>
In addition, high technology such as information
digitalization, multimedia and computer networking have greatly
altered our daily lives during the 1990s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
