<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Institute: S.Korean Economy to Grow in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, November 11 (Xinhua) -- South Korean economy will bottom
out in the second quarter of next year and see an annual growth of 2.3
percent, the Korea Institute of Finance (KIF) said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The KIF, composed of a group of South Korean bankers, predicted
that the consumer price index will be lowered to 4.8 percent next year
from 7.6 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
The institute also predicted that consumption will stop contracting
and investment in construction will increase next year.
</P>
<P>
"The economic recovery will be propelled by expanding domestic
demand following successful structural reform," it said.
</P>
<P>
Consumption will edge up slightly by 0.6 percent in 1999, a
turnaround from the projected shrinkage this year, and investment in
construction will rise by 2.7 percent, but facility investment will
shrink 1.0 percent, it added.
</P>
<P>
As the economy will pick up steam, the facility investment will
increase by 4.1 percent in the third quarter of next year and 5.8
percent in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the nation will register a current account surplus
of 29.02 billion U.S. dollars next year, 26.3 percent down from
this year's estimated 39.4 billion dollars, as a result of the
decline in exports, it said.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean exports are expected to drop 6.2 percent to
124.35 billion dollars next year as the markets in Asia and
other parts of the world will continue shrinking amid the global
economic slump, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
