<HEADLINE> Duty-Free Stores to Open in Three Chinese Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, November 11 (Xinhua) -- China plans to open duty-free
stores in Beijing, Shanghai and Guangzhou during 1999, according
to Gai Zhixin, general manager of the China National Duty-Free
Merchandise Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The move represents yet another major reform measure. The
Chinese government introduced duty-free stores at ports of entry
over a decade ago, said Gai.
</P>
<P>
The new stores will help meet the growing needs of foreign
visitors and diplomatic personnel living in the cities, according
to Gai.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, China's leading commercial and financial center, has
witnessed an annual 10 percent rise in the number of foreign
tourists in recent years, with the city hosting over 1.65 million
arrivals during 1997. However, the city's four duty-free stores
fell far short of increasing demand.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's first new duty-free store, which will be located in
the city proper, will offer high quality brand name products
imported from the United States and Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
