<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey: 22% of S. African Voters "Unable" to Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 11 (Xinhua) -- About 22 percent of
South Africa's voters do not have the right identity documents
which are required for voter registration for next year's general
election, a survey has found.
</P>
<P>
About 5.6 million eligible South African voters do not have
the necessary bar-coded identity books, more than double the
figure estimated by the Home Affairs Department, according to the
survey by Markinor, a major independent research institute in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The result of the extensive survey, conducted in September,
means the Home Affairs Department would not be able to complete
processing all the documents before registration, The Citizen
paper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Only 78 percent of about 25.6 million eligible voters had the
proper identity books to vote in the second democratic election
in five or six months' time, the survey found.
</P>
<P>
Significantly more black South Africans (82 percent) had the
correct identity documents than Indian (71 percent), colored (67
percent) or white (65 percent) people, the survey found.
</P>
<P>
This was because black people had had the most reason to get
the new, updated identity documents in the past four years to
replace their obsolete apartheid-era documents, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The survey also found more supporters of the ruling African
National Congress (ANC) and black-based opposition parties had
the correct documents than those of white-based opposition
parties.
</P>
<P>
About 82 percent of ANC supporters and 84 percent of Inkatha
Freedom Party (IFP) supporters had the right IDs.
</P>
<P>
But only 71 percent of those who favored the National Party
(NP) and 65 percent of likely Democratic Party (DP) voters had
the right documents.
</P>
<P>
Reacting to the poll result, opposition parties criticized the
ANC government's decision to bar those without new IDs from
voting.
</P>
<P>
They said if the ID issue was not handled properly, they would
take the matter to the constitutional court to ensure their
supporters' electoral rights.
</P>
<P>
The survey found eight in ten South Africans wanted to vote
and were likely to vote.
</P>
<P>
Taking into account of undecided voters, a voter turnout of
between 75 percent and 89 percent was expected next year, about
the same as the 86 percent turnout in 1994, according to the
survey.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
