<HEADLINE> Uganda, Rwanda Form Joint Military Command in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Uganda and Rwanda have formed
a joint military command of dozens of senior officers from both
sides in eastern part of the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
A New Vision daily report said Wednesday that the command was
in response to President Laurent Kabila's allies sending more
troops for a showdown with the rebels.
</P>
<P>
However, when asked for any comment on that in a telephone
interview Wednesday morning, officers in the Defense Ministry's
information office refused to confirm it.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the joint command, which is chaired
by Uganda's acting Chief of Staff James Kazini, is composed of 17
Ugandans, 10 Rwandans and five rebel commanders.
</P>
<P>
The joint command is aimed at helping strengthen command
tactics, deployment and logistics, the report added.
</P>
<P>
Analysts were quoted as saying that the move marks another
stage in the evolution of the internal conflict in the DRC toward
a full-scale six country war.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Rwanda both admitted that they have military
presence in eastern Congo (K), but for the purpose of
safeguarding their national interests against rebels crossing
from Congo to attack targets inside their respective countries.
</P>
<P>
They have been accused of backing the rebels fighting to
dethrone Kabila, a charge they have strongly denied. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
