<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Basic Salary Agreed on for Nigerian Civil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The Federal Government of
Nigeria and trade unions have agreed upon the basic salary of
1,299 Naira (about 15 U.S. Dollars) for three tiers of federal,
state and local government civil servants.
</P>
<P>
A communique issued at the end of an extraordinary meeting
held between the National Committee on Minimum Wage (NCMW) and
trade unions Tuesday in capital Abuja said it was also agreed all
fringe benefits should be negotiated by the various state and
local governments, media here reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Labor leaders believe that the new arrangement would put to
rest the raging feud between state civil servants and their
various governments over the 5,200 Naira (about 60 Dollars)
minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
Last September, the Federal Government of Nigeria announced
5,200 Naira minimum monthly salary for federal civil servants and
asked state and local governments to pay a total of 2,800 Naira
(about 32 Dollars) as the minimum wage or more if they could.
</P>
<P>
This directive aroused angry reactions from labor unions in
this West African country, leading to a wave of industrial crisis
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Following the threats of industrial actions by civil servants
in state and local governments, the Federal Government last month
set up the NCMW headed by the Chief of General Staff, Rear
Admiral Mike Akhigbe to have another look at the issue of minimum
wage.
</P>
<P>
According to the communique, the next meeting of the two sides
is scheduled on December 1 to receive feedback on the results of
the negotiations conducted at the state and local government
levels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
