<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Armed Forces Ready for Democracy: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Head of State General
Abdulsalam Abubakar has assured the nation that Nigeria's armed
forces are ready for democracy, saying that the military high
command is doing its best to prepare for a democratic government.
</P>
<P>
The New Nigerian newspaper Wednesday quoted the head of state
as saying in capital Abuja that their continued involvement in
governance was not in their best interest.
</P>
<P>
Receiving President Bill Clinton's special envoy to Africa
Reverend Jesse Jackson in capital Abuja Tuesday, he noted that
continued military rule had very adverse consequences for
professionism and discipline among the officers and men of the
service.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar advised the political leadership in the country that
would emerge on May 29, next year to realize that it had equal
responsibilities to both the civil populace and the armed forces
for the good governance of the nation.
</P>
<P>
To ensure the future political stability of the country, he
said that the next political leadership should avoid actions that
could alienate the military in the interest of peace and
stability.
</P>
<P>
Following the meeting with General Abubakar, Jackson who
arrived in the country Monday told reporters that "Nigeria has
gone from midnight to daybreak and now morning has come for
democracy in the country."
</P>
<P>
The special envoy noted that Nigeria's role to Africa's
stability made it imperative that the United States will continue
to show interest in the country, adding that "we expect to come
back to Nigeria because Africa's stability rests on this country
with its huge population and enormous potential."
</P>
<P>
Jackson who is on the first leg of his four-nation West
African tour told Nigerian people that "it is essential for you
to have democratic values, also democratic culture that resists
corruption. The military culture has to be emphasized."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. envoy who met with minority leaders in Niger Delta,
former Head of State General Ibrahim Babangida and others is
scheduled to leave for Ghana Wednesday and for Sierra Leone and
Guinea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
