<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Steady in Quiet Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar was
steady Wednesday at the close, having regained losses in offshore
trading Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
In a quiet day's trade the local currency scrambled back from
the low of 62.20 U.S. cents reached earlier Wednesday morning in
New York.
</P>
<P>
At the close of the day, the Australian dollar was steady at
62.93 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
After trading between 62.65 and 62.85 for most of the local
session the Australian dollar experienced a small spike up in late
afternoon trade to a high for the day of 62.95 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
IBJ foreign exchange dealer Scott Lewis said the local currency
suffered a fairly quiet day except for the afternoon when it
rallied due to a weakening in the U.S. dollar against the Japanese
yen.
</P>
<P>
At the close the U.S. dollar was buying 120.80 Japanese yen
from 122.11 Tuesday and 1.6804 German marks from 1.6888.
</P>
<P>
Lewis said the fall in the greenback against the Japanese
currency was largely due to a long market that was squaring up
ahead of the Veteran's Day holiday in the U.S. Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics labor force figures
scheduled for release Thursday are on average expected to reflect
a modest seasonally adjusted 3,500 advance in total employment for
the month, compared to a gain of 41,300 jobs in September.
</P>
<P>
This would leave the unemployment rate unchanged at an adjusted
8.1 percent, a survey of economists forecast by MMS Standard &AMP;
Poor's showed.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar also finished the local session at 76.02
Japanese yen from 76.86 and 1.0576 German marks from 1.0625.
</P>
</TEXT>
