<HEADLINE> Kurdish Rebels Continue Fleeing Towards Iranian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Rebels of the outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK) were continuing fleeing towards the Iranian
border amid a Turkish military operation in northern Iraq, the
Daily News reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of PKK rebels, who escaped from neighboring Syria,
were trying to force their way into Iran to take shelter from the
Turkish attacks.
</P>
<P>
Backed by fighters and military helicopters, about
20,000-strong Turkish troops started the cross-border military
operation in northern Iraq last Sunday in a bid to wipe out the
PKK militants.
</P>
<P>
Turkish officials said earlier that the PKK members had been
encircled by Turkish troops in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The forces of the Massoud Barzani-led Kurdistan Democratic
Party (KDP) were reportedly helping the Turkish government troops
fight the PKK militants.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Turkish troops were conducting military operations
against the PKK rebels in the southeastern Turkish province of
Sirnak, said Aydin Arslan, the governor of the Emergency Rule
Region.
</P>
<P>
The operations were mainly focused around the Gabar mountain
areas where six village guards were killed and seven others
wounded by the PKK militants, he added.
</P>
<P>
Turkish cross-border attacks were launched while Barzani and
Jalal Talabani, chairman of the rival Patriotic Union of Kurdistan
(PUK) operating in northern Iraq were holding talks in Ankara.
</P>
<P>
Talabani, who allegedly maintains close relations with the
PKK, had promised Turkey to close all the PKK camps in the
PUK-controlled areas in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The PKK, which has been fighting a 14-year-old separatist war
in southeastern Turkey, has camps in northern Iraq where they
often launch hit-and-run attacks on Turkey's military and civilian
targets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
