<HEADLINE> Zambia's Stock Market Trade Heading Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, November 11 (Xinhua) -- With Effectively six weeks of
trading remaining before the end of the year, business is headed
for a low point closing on the Lusaka Stock Exchange (LuSE),
Times of Zambia said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It has been a tale of contrasts about the stock market's
performance in the current year and its showing in 1997. As
reflected in the various trading indicators at the LuSE in the
last 11 months, the market has not been up to 1997 levels of
activity.
</P>
<P>
The trade during the year under review has been of flat growth
while trading volumes maintained a comparatively weaker profile.
</P>
<P>
Indicative of the waxing fortunes of the market has been the
falling levels of market capitalization. From a high 1,006,674
Kwacha (one U.S. Dollars equals 2000 Kwacha at present) at the
end of 1997, market capitalization levels had slid to 777,004 and
713,232 Kwacha by August and October this year respectively,
according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
The LuSE free float index has fallen in the same period by 19
percent in nominal terms after opening at 210 and falling to 170
to date.
</P>
<P>
The price earning (PE) ratios for the listed companies
excluding the Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines recorded modest
upward adjustments in the period reviewed.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Sugar, representing the agricultural sector has been
posting the highest PE ratios over this time at 10.5.
</P>
<P>
With favorable developments envisaged in the macro-sector, the
market is expected to post more positively by the beginning of
the new year.
</P>
<P>
Although not particularly a buoyant year for the investor,
said the paper, there is hope yet for both local and foreign
investors as the economy generally continues in a market
environment conducive of investment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 10B Dollar Package Proposed to Cut Business Costs in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The Committee on Singapore's
Competitiveness (CSC) formed by the Singapore government released
Wednesday a report on a 10 billion-Singapore-dollar package of
measures it has proposed with an aim to tide over the current
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the Singapore economy has slowed sharply with its
growth rates contracting from 7.8 percent last year to 6.2
percent, 1.8 percent and -0.7 percent respectively in the first,
second and third quarter of 1998, and the unemployment rate has
edged up to 4.5 percent in September with retrenchments exceeding
20,000 people, the committee proposes a 15 percent cut in business
costs or reducing the costs by about 10 billion Singapore dollars,
which is equivalent to about 7 percent of Singapore's GDP.
</P>
<P>
Measures contained in the proposed package include cutting by
10 percent employers' contribution to employees' account of the
Central Provident Fund(CPF); reducing the annual and monthly
variable components of wages; significant slashing land and
factory rentals; trimming charges for services like electricity,
telecommunications and port services, lowering vehicle-related
overhead costs including customs duty and petrol (diesel) duty,
extending existing property tax rebate and suspending stamp duties
on share transactions, and cutting government taxes like corporate
and personal income taxes in fiscal year 1999.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Minister for Trade and Industry Lee Yock Suan, who
doubles the CSC chairman, told a press conference Wednesday
morning that his committee recommends that the government promptly
implements the comprehensive and significant package of cost/tax
cutting measures to help companies compete during this difficult
period and minimize further job losses.
</P>
<P>
The CC was formed in May 1997 on the advice of Singapore Prime
Minister Goh Choke Tong and was assigned to make a thorough review
of Singapore's economic competitiveness over the next decade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
