<HEADLINE> Stock Prices Soar in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices rose sharply in
Tokyo Wednesday on expectations of an upcoming 10-trillion-yen
(about 81.9 billion U.S. dollars) government package aimed at
reviving Japanese slumping economy.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange advanced 319.93 points, or
2.27 percent, from Tuesday's close to end at 14,428.02.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, gained 19.80 points or 1.34 percent to
1,098.12.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section went slightly up to an estimated
380 million shares from Tuesday's 366.94 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Sakura Bank was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Banks took the lion's share of trading and rose by 4.17 percent
as a sector. Some traders said government-linked pension funds may
have bought these shares to shore up the market.
</P>
<P>
Investors are waiting to see the details of the stimulus
package to be revealed next Monday, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,345 issues listed on the First Section, gainers
outnumbered losers 811 to 309, with 151 issues remaining
unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
