<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 10:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Labor Wins Elections in 3 Major Israeli Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 11 (Xinhua) -- TV polls showed Israel's
Labor Party firmly in control of three of the country's major
cities after it captured two from the Likud in Tuesday's municipal
elections.
</P>
<P>
In Tel Aviv, independent Ron Huldai, who is identified with
Labor, Israel's major opposition party, won 50 to 52 percent of
the votes, while the ruling Likud's mayor candidate Doron Rubin
had won only 25 to 27 percent. Tel Aviv was controlled by Likud in
the past five years.
</P>
<P>
Ya'akov Terner, another independent candidate identified with
Labor, captured the mayor of Israel's southern city of Beer
Sheba from the incumbent mayor David Bunfeld (Likud) with 58
percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
Haifa Mayor Amran Mitzna of Labor was reelected by a large
majority.
</P>
<P>
But Likud's incumbent Jerusalem Mayor Ehud Olmert won at least
66 percent of the votes, while Likud's candidate Miriam Feierberg
won 40 to 50 percent of the votes in Netanya, making her the first
woman in Israel's history to win control of a city.
</P>
<P>
The Likud's Benny Kiryati had a clear edge on Shas' candidate
in the northern city of Tiberias, according to TV polls.
</P>
<P>
Politicians gave a different picture of polls about Tuesday's
municipal elections. Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu told the
Likud staff Tuesday night at Likud's Tel Aviv headquarters that
the Likud had preserved its power and the two major parties had
just changed places rather than changing the balance of power.
</P>
<P>
But Labor Party leader Ehud Barak was happy about the
results. He told his staff at Labor's Tel Aviv headquarters
Tuesday night that these elections would have an effect on the
national ones.
</P>
<P>
Israel has about 4 million eligible voters. On Tuesday, only
about 40 percent of them cast their votes. Final results will be
announced Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
