<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Infrared Detectors Being Used In Search of South China Tigers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists are using
infrared detectors to search for South China Tigers in south
China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region to solve an old problem.
</P>
<P>
They say that it may have been a tiger that killed two cattle
earlier this year, so they have installed infrared detectors in
several places in the Huaping Nature Reserve, only 170 kilometers
from Guilin, to look for the culprit.
</P>
<P>
In June and July, the nature reserve reported that two local
cattle had been killed. One was completely eaten and only a bloody
leg was left of the other.
</P>
<P>
Local people saw fur and 10-cm-wide footprints at the scene and
animal excrement and tracks were discovered on a grassland nearby,
indicating that the killer had a good rest after it had eaten.
</P>
<P>
A team of Hong Kong zoologists who are doing field studies in
the region thought that the animal could be a South China Tiger.
</P>
<P>
The South China Tiger is on the brink of extinction that is
found in Guangdong, Fujian and Hunan provinces. There are only
about 20 of these animals in existence.
</P>
<P>
The infrared detectors have found bears, silver pheasants and
monkeys, but never tigers, said Cao Taiming, director of the
nature reserve, which was founded in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
It has a lot of primitive forest and in the past three decades,
people have reported several cases of tigers eating cattles and
people, but since the 1990s, no traces of tigers have been found
there, he added.
</P>
<P>
Better-protected parts of the forest here may attract tigers in
neighboring districts, Cao explained.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
