<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Energy Development In Western China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists and
specialists met to discuss the development and allocation of
energy in western China at a recent symposium in Kunming, the
capital of Yunnan Province.
</P>
<P>
Western China has 56.5 percent of the country's land and 23
percent of its population.
</P>
<P>
It also has 70 percent of the country's hydro-electric power
resources, 64 percent of its coal resources, more than 40 percent
of its petroleum resources, and more than half of its natural gas
resources.
</P>
<P>
In addition, most of the country's exploitable coal-bed gas and
solar energy resources is in western areas.
</P>
<P>
But, a shortage of funds and lack of technology and transport
have held the development of these resources, resulting in a
shortage of energy. So, the country has developed policies to
speed up economic development in the western areas.
</P>
<P>
Priority is being given to the investment environment in these
areas, which need more technology for coordinated economic,
social, and enviromental development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 09:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> All U.N. Staff in Baghdad Pull out of Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 11 (Xinhua) -- All U.N. staff except core
officials are leaving Iraq Wednesday amid the current
Iraq-U.N. standoff, said a U.N. spokesman Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Eric Falt, spokesman for the U.N. humanitarian coordinator in
Iraq, told reporters that they had received instructions from the
U.N. headquarters in New York asking them to leave for Amman,
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
A convoy of 11 vehicles carrying U.N. personnel left the
U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) headquarters in Baghdad early
Wednesday to head for the airport.
</P>
<P>
The UNSCOM withdrew 15 of its inspectors from Iraq on Saturday
in response to the Iraq's decision to suspend cooperation with the
U.N. inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Iraq on October 31 announced its decision to halt all forms of
cooperation with the UNSCOM until the Security Council moves
toward lifting the U.N. sanctions imposed on Iraq in 1990 after
its invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council adopted a resolution last Thursday
which condemned the Iraqi non-cooperation with U.N. arms
inspectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
