<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official Says Philippine Economy in Good Shape </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines is in "the best
position" among Asian nations to take advantage of an improved
global economy along with the return of international investor
confidence, Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Euro-money conference here, Espiritu said that
the government will continue to deal squarely with the monetary
crisis, which has crippling effects on most Asian economies.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Philippines has "weathered the crisis quite
well" due to the following factors:
</P>
<P>
-- it has undertaken reforms much earlier that improved the
structure of the economy. The reforms include liberalization of
trade, investments and foreign exchange markets; deregulation of
the financial system, tax reform and privatization.
</P>
<P>
-- it has a very manageable and sustainable external debt
position; and
</P>
<P>
-- its banking sector remains strong as a result of
comprehensive banking reforms that have already been undertaken.
</P>
<P>
But the secretary admitted that the financial crisis has "a
significant social dimension" and "has severely affected large
sectors of society."
</P>
<P>
Espiritu said that the government will provide "safety nets"
for the vulnerable sectors, such as basic education, primary
health care and nutrition, and housing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
