<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poor Infrastructure Affects Kenya's Horticulture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The crumbling infrastructure
has become a major constraint to the growth of Kenya's
horticulture industry, according to a report available Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report, issued by the Horticultural Crop Development
Authority, said farmers are unable to market their crop due to
poor roads, railway system and telephone services.
</P>
<P>
"Power supply has been a hindrance to cooling facilities and
irrigation," the report added.
</P>
<P>
Other factors for low horticultural production include lack of
suitable credit for small-holder farmers, lack of high quality
seeds,low levels of research and few available experts.
</P>
<P>
There is inadequate wholesale and retail facilities in the
urban centers, said the report, adding that the wholesale markets
are too small, poor and congested, and often lack cooling
facilities to enable produce last longer.
</P>
<P>
Last year, horticulture earned Kenya over 15 billion Shillings
(some 25 million U.S. Dollars) in foreign exchange. Horticulture
is reported to have earned farmers another 35 billion Shillings
(about 58 million Dollars). 
