<HEADLINE> All U.N. Arms Inspectors to Pull out From Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Baghdad, November 11 (Xinhua) -- All U.N. weapons inspectors
will leave Iraq on Wednesday amid the current Iraq-U.N. standoff
in a sign that the U.S. will probably launch military strikes
against Iraq, U.N. sources here said.
</P>
<P>
The sources who asked not to be identified told Xinhua on
Wednesday morning that UNSCOM (U.N. Special Commission for
disarming Iraq) inspectors just received emergency notice asking
them to get ready to leave Iraq on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A convoy of 11 vehicles carrying U.N. personnel left the UNSCOM
headquarters in Baghdad early Wednesday to head for the airport.
</P>
<P>
The commission is holding a press conference to announce the
details of its plan to pull all its inspectors out of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The UNSCOM withdrew 15 of its inspectors from Iraq on Saturday
in response to the Iraq's decision to suspend cooperation with the
U.N. inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Iraq on October 31 announced its decision to halt all forms of
cooperation with the UNSCOM until the Security Council moves
toward lifting the U.N. sanctions imposed on Iraq in 1990 after
its invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council adopted a resolution last Thursday
which condemned the Iraqi non-cooperation with U.N. arms
inspectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
