<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review: China Punishes Tax Evaders to Ensure Fiscal Income (1) by Xinhua Writer Xu Xingtang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 11 (Xinhua) -- China's taxation departments
handled a number of major cases and rendered heavy punishment and
fines for tax evaders over the past week.
</P>
<P>
The effort marked the initiation of a nationwide campaign
against tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
China introduced tax reform in 1994 and has basically
established an effective modern taxation system which has
contributed greatly to the establishment of a market economic
system and sustained, rapid and healthy national economic
development.
</P>
<P>
However, taxation departments have exhibited great concern over
rampant tax evasions which have resulted in substantial losses in
state tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
The central government adopted a requirement for the taxation
sector to increase tax revenues by 100 billion yuan to raise the
annual total to 855 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
However, statistics through the middle of October indicated
fulfillment of only 73.4 percent of the target, or 11.3 percentage
points less than the scheduled volume.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the State Administration of Taxation (SAT) said
the only way to reach the tax income target is to render heavy
punishment for illegal practices in terms of taxation, and adopt
effective measures to clear tax arrears in the remaining two
months of the year.
</P>
<P>
He said SAT measures adopted for the ongoing campaign include
exposing serious tax evasion cases; strengthening tax inspections
of key industries, including the tobacco, power and oil sectors,
as well as private and foreign-funded enterprises; and
strengthening relations with financial institutions to clear tax
arrears.
</P>
<P>
He said related measures are expected to enhance social
consciousness of the necessity to voluntarily pay taxes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan, U.S. Start Non-Proliferation Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan and the United
States started their talks on export-control programs to limit
nuclear proliferation here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. expert team, which arrived here Tuesday evening, is
headed by Deputy Secretary of State John Barker.
</P>
<P>
The two sides are expected to study programs for export
controls, identify loopholes and find ways to close them and seek
a common position on the issue of technology exports.
</P>
<P>
This is the second meeting between the experts from the two
countries following their first meeting in New York last month.
</P>
<P>
The talks coincide with U.S. President Bill Clinton's
announcement of lifting some of the sanctions imposed on Pakistan
and India after their nuclear tests in May.
</P>
<P>
Washington is now pressurizing both India and Pakistan to sign
the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT).
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmed held parlays with
State Department officials in Washington on November 4-5 on
non-proliferation and security situation in South Asia among other
subjects.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif will travel to the U.S. capital
later this month and is expected to meet President Clinton on
December 2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
