<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review: China Punishes Tax Evaders to Ensure Fiscal Income (2) by Xinhua Writer Xu Xingtang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
One recent major tax evasion case involved 218 enterprises in
Jinhua County, east China's Zhejiang Province. An in-depth
investigation revealed that 218 enterprises in the county used
counterfeit value-added tax receipts to evade taxes of well over
6.3 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government handed down heavy punishment for local
officials involved in the case, with a number of individuals
expelled from the ruling Communist Party of China and dismissed
from their posts. Others were referred to legislative
departments in accordance with the law, and a few individuals
involved in the case received death sentences.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has attempted to encourage investments
by formulating a series of favorable taxation policies covering
overseas-funded enterprises. However, various unqualified
enterprises resorted to illegal acts to gain tax exemptions and
created substantial losses in tax incomes.
</P>
<P>
Last week's case involving the Enwei Group in Chengdu, capital
of southwest China's Sichuan Province, was typical of related
practices. An investigation of the tax evasions of two of the
group's subsidiaries resulted in taxes and fines of 108 million
yuan.
</P>
<P>
Taxation departments has also paid great attention to
individual income taxes, with famous pop star Mao Amin recently
ordered to pay all back taxes and a heavy fine.
</P>
<P>
Taxation departments are preparing to publicize additional tax
evasion cases in the near future. Public security, industrial and
commercial bureaus, banks and taxation departments will jointly
work to strengthen taxation, and effective measures will be
adopted to promote public awareness of the importance in paying
taxes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
