<HEADLINE> CMC Vice Chairman Meets U.S. Naval Commander </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 11 (Xinhua) -- General Zhang Wannian, vice
chairman of China's Central Military Commission, met today with
Admiral Joesph Prueher, Commander-in-Chief of the U.S. Pacific
Command, and urged the U.S. government to strictly abide by the
principles in the three Sino-US joint communiques, related
commitments and rules guiding international relations.
</P>
<P>
Zhang expressed China's serious concern over U.S. Energy
Secretary Bill Richardson's recent visit to Taiwan, as well as
recent meetings between U.S. leaders and the Dalai Lama.
</P>
<P>
China and the United States both bear great responsibility for
ensuring the maintenance of world peace, stability and prosperity,
as well as promoting the health growth of stable relations,
according to Zhang.
</P>
<P>
The development of current Sino-US relations has been
accomplished due to the active efforts of both presidents, said
Zhang.
</P>
<P>
He called for military leaders in the two nations to work hard
to achieve the goal of establishing a constructive strategic
partnership oriented to the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
He said the two presidents agreed to enhance mutual
understanding and trust through bilateral exchanges and
cooperation, and in turn promoting the further development of
relations between the two countries and armies.
</P>
<P>
Zhang expressed appreciation for the active role Prueher and
the Pacific Command have played in accelerating the development of
Sino-US military relations.
</P>
<P>
Prueher echoed Zhang's call for recognizing the importance of
developing Sino-US relations, and noted that the two nations
should strive to fulfill the task of ensuring the healthy
development of stable relations.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that the U.S. government recognizes only one
China.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. delegation will also visit Xi'an, Hangzhou and
Shanghai. 
</P>
