<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Building Competitive Power Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WEIHAI, November 11 (Xinhua) -- China has decided to separate
power plant and power grid operations and let companies operate as
commercial entities, according to sources at the State Economic
and Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
They said that power plants will have to compete in the years
ahead, and this is a major step in China's power industry reforms.
</P>
<P>
China's power sector has long been monopolized by the state and
a regional power corporation supervises both power plants and
local grids now. And, because of a lack of competition, there have
been management and pricing problems that keep it from being
efficient.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of the 1980s, the country decided to develop
the power industry by pooling funds from various sources and a
current reform scheme will mean replacing the existing pricing
system with a more market-oriented one.
</P>
<P>
Rural and industrial electricity prices will depend entirely on
the market, but electricity for agricultural use will not go up a
great deal.
</P>
<P>
The country is now considering drafting laws and regulations to
coordinate the reforms.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0211 </DOCNO>
