<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four Killed by Heavy Snow in U.S. Midwest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Snow and killer winds
raked a wide area of the central United States Tuesday, killing at
least four people and closing roads, airports and schools.
</P>
<P>
A 50-year-old woman was missing and feared drowned after
falling into the wind-whipped Wisconsin River in the Town of
Dekorra.
</P>
<P>
Three other storm-related deaths were reported, including one
in a traffic accident in Minnesota and two by falling trees in
Louisville of Kentucky state and Genoa of Wisconsin state.
</P>
<P>
The brunt of the snowstorm stretched from Missouri and Kentucky
north to the Canadian border, cutting power to hundreds of
thousands of people in several states.
</P>
<P>
In the Chicago area more than 100,000 homes and businesses were
without power.
</P>
<P>
In southeastern Wisconsin, Wisconsin Electric Power
Co. reported 50,000 customers without electricity.
</P>
<P>
In South Dakota, snowstorms forced the closing of all 250 miles
of Interstate Highway-29, from the Nebraska state line to North
Dakota. Also shut down was 400 miles of Interstate Highway-90 from
Ellsworth Air Force Base in western South Dakota to Jackson,
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
Poor visibility and heavy snow closed South Dakota's Sioux
Falls Regional Airport, which has about 25 commercial flights per
day. Chicago's O'Hare and Midway airports reported 30-minute
delays and several cancellations.
</P>
<P>
Schools in several states closed early or never opened.
</P>
<P>
This is the first big snowstorm of the season in U.S. Midwest.
Meanwhile, heavy rainstorms dumped on sections of Illinois and
Indiana. Farther south powerful thunderstorms raked Tennessee and
Mississippi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
