<HEADLINE> World Bank to Aid Hurricane-hit Central America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank Tuesday
announced the availability of 200 million U.S. dollars to assist
the Central American countries devastated by Hurricane Mitch.
</P>
<P>
This figure does not include any future support under emergency
loans, which are also in active preparation, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
For Honduras, the World Bank is making available about 100
million dollars for immediate emergency and reconstruction needs.
</P>
<P>
For Nicaragua, a total of 60 million dollars will be made
available.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the World Bank Tuesday also had a separate
announcement of approving a 45-million-dollar credit to help
finance the Third Social Investment Fund in Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
The project will support the government of Nicaragua's poverty
alleviation efforts as well as its immediate emergency and
reconstruction needs in the wake of Hurricane Mitch.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the bank will also disburse some 21 million dollars
for four projects of Guatemala and 20 million dollars out of an
ongoing agriculture project, a secondary education project and a
basic education project for El Salvador. 
</P>
