<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poor Roads, Disease Threaten Kenya's Pineapple </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Pineapple farmers in Malindi,
coastal Kenya, have asked the government to take urgent measures
to repair poor roads around and help them fight a disease that
has hit pineapples in the area.
</P>
<P>
Poor roads, banditry, pests and diseases led to loss of more
than half of the pineapple production in the east African country
last year and now are bringing the industry to the total
collapse, the farmers warned.
</P>
<P>
The road around Malindi were wrecked by the heavy El Nino
rains which had lasted five months from October, 1997 and have
not been repaired so far, shooting up the transportation
expenditure, the Daily Nation newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The rains made the roads to Malindi completely impassable at
a time when the pineapple crop was flourishing and good returns
were expected," a farmer, Issac Kitsao, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Bawazir Fruit Processing factory, the only large scale
market for pineapple farmers in the area, is too far for most
farmers and much of the crop fetches poor prices at the factory
because it arrives damaged, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Large and small-scale farmers all complained that they are
unable to service loans advanced by the Agricultural Finance
Corporation as a result.
</P>
<P>
"If the extension officers do not help us control the disease
which broke out in the area last year, pineapple farming will
collapse in Malindi," pineapple farmer Paul Masha said.
</P>
<P>
The vice chairman of the Malindi County Council, George Baruk,
who is also a leading pineapple farmer, added that lack of fruit
processing factories and exploitation by middle men affected
farmers' morale and incomes in the coastal Kenya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
