<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Returns to Happy Life in Lhasa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Zhaxi Wangdue, a 74-year-old
Tibetan, was born into a military family, and was once a lama at
Salra Temple, but he left the country in 1959.
</P>
<P>
He returned to China and settled down here in 1985, and lives
in a 50-square-meter house provided by the Tibet Regional
Government and says that he feels exuberant and is becoming
younger and younger.
</P>
<P>
He was elected a deputy to the Fifth Lhasa City People's
Congress in 1987 and proposed that Tibetan youth be educated more
in the law, something that attracted a great deal of attention
from the local government.
</P>
<P>
He was then elected to the Sixth People's Congress of Lhasa and
became a member of the Lhasa City Committee of the Fifth People's
Political Consultative Conference. A dozen of his proposals have
been made into regulations.
</P>
<P>
Zhaxi recalls 15 years of miserable life when he lived in a
refugee camp abroad and says that he was very confused about
guarding a land that did not belong to his.
</P>
<P>
In 1953, he returned to China for the first time. He said that
the government arranged a special car for him to visit Lhasa,
Xigaze and Shannan, and he also visited his sister in Qonggyai
County in Shannan Prefecture.
</P>
<P>
"My sister was very poor and her family lived in a run-down
house when I went abroad in 1959," he reports, but now she has a
two-story house and a tractor. Her family is provided with plenty
of rice and flour which were lacking in the past, he
continues. And concludes that, what is more important, is that
Tibetans have the freedom of religion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
