<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia to Introduce Landmine Bill in Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The Australian federal
government will introduce legislation banning the use of
anti-personnel landmines into Australian federal parliament
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer said he would
personally introduce the bill, which is supported by all sides of
politics, after it was approved at Wednesday's ruling coalition
party meeting.
</P>
<P>
"The government recognized early in its first term that more
needed to be done to rid the world of the landmines scourge,"
Downer said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"We were quick to announce Australia's support for a global ban
on anti-personnel landmines (APL) as well as the suspension of the
operational use of APL by the Australian Defense Force," he said.
</P>
<P>
Downer overcame strong opposition from the military last year
and succeeded in having the cabinet reverse its opposition to the
treaty banning the use of landmines.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Australia was one of the original signatories to
last year's Ottawa Convention, which prohibits the use,
production, stockpiling and transfer of anti-personnel mines.
</P>
<P>
Once the bill becomes law, Australia will be required to
destroy its entire stockpile of anti-personnel mines, apart from a
small number retained for training purposes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
