<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at GMT 0800, November 11 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Two Israeli soldiers were wounded near a Jewish
settlement in the West Bank Tuesday night, Israel Radio reported
Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the incident occurred near the Jewish
settlement of Otniel when the two soldiers were apparently
ambushed by Palestinian militants who hid by the side of a
road. The Israeli army said findings of its initial investigation
were given to the Palestinian police. And the Palestinian police
set up roadblocks around Hebron and searched cars.
(Israel-Shooting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- All U.N. weapons inspectors will leave Iraq on
Wednesday amid the current Iraq-U.N. standoff in a sign that the
U.S. will probably launch military strikes against Iraq,
U.N. sources here said.
</P>
<P>
The sources who asked not to be identified told Xinhua on
Wednesday morning that UNSCOM (U.N. Special Commission for
disarming Iraq) inspectors just received emergency notice asking
them to get ready to leave Iraq on Wednesday. (Iraq-UN-Standoff)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi left here for
Moscow Wednesday on a three-day visit to Russia for talks with
Russian leaders in a bid to resolve a decades-old territorial
dispute between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, the first official trip to Russia by a
Japanese prime minister in 25 years, Obuchi and Russian leaders
are expected to have wide-range discussions on bilateral ties as
well as negotiations on a peace treaty. In their summit talks
Thursday, Obuchi and Russian President Boris Yeltsin will reaffirm
previous agreements reached by the leaders of the two countries in
November, 1997 and April, 1998 to work for a conclusion of a peace
treaty by 2000 after resolving the territorial row.
(Japan-Russia-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korean President Kim Dae-jung left here for
Beijing Wednesday afternoon for a five-day state visit aimed at
establishing a comprehensive and cooperative relationship with
China.
</P>
<P>
Before his departure, Kim said he will discuss various
bilateral, regional and international issues with Chinese leaders,
with an emphasis on ways to cooperate in maintaining peace and
stability on the Korean peninsula, to strengthen cultural
exchanges as well as to realize peace and prosperity in the East
Asian region. The South Korean president also said he will voice
his support for China's entry into the World Trade Organization.
(SKorea-China-Visit) 
</P>
