<HEADLINE> Philippine Govt Assures PAL Employees of Job Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government
Wednesday assured Philippine Airlines (PAL) workers of job
security even if new investors take control of the airline's
management.
</P>
<P>
In a radio interview, Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu said
that PAL will honor the agreement reached by the airline's
management and labor union, which PAL employees overwhelmingly
ratified in September.
</P>
<P>
"Personnel will be retained, and excess personnel to be retired
will be given their separation pay," he said.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu expressed optimism that PAL employees would cooperate
with the new management should Hong Kong-based Cathay Pacific
Airways take over PAL operations.
</P>
<P>
Cathay and PAL's interim rehabilitation receiver announced
Tuesday that Cathay's conditional proposal for a possible
investment in PAL had been accepted.
</P>
<P>
The two parties would draw up together a comprehensive
rehabilitation plan for PAL and submit it to the Securities and
Exchange Commission and creditors for approval.
</P>
<P>
PAL shut down its operations on September 23 after the ground
crew union turned down a recovery plan proposed by the airline's
management.
</P>
<P>
The proposal included a 10-year suspension of labor's
collective bargaining agreement, in exchange for 20 percent
ownership of the airline, three board seats, no pay cuts, full
medical benefits and other privileges.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was approved by the workers in a second
referendum, enabling PAL to resume operations last month.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu said that Cathay will limit its investment in PAL to
40 percent, as stipulated in the country's constitution.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that Cathay is expected to raise 4 billion pesos
(100 million U.S. dollars) of the 6 billion pesos (150 million
dollars) needed to make PAL viable again. 
</P>
</TEXT>
