<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia Faces Epidemic of Heart Disease: Researchers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Asia faces an epidemic of
heart disease, Australian researchers said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Hypertension, high cholesterol and smoking are contributing to
rising numbers of men and women developing cardiovascular disease,
they said.
</P>
<P>
The first study to investigate how many people in the
Asia-Pacific region are in hospital for heart problems and why,
has alarmed Australian researchers.
</P>
<P>
The researchers presented the data to the American Heart
Association congress in Dallas, Texas, of the United States,
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The study, which involves 4,000 patients at 135 hospitals in 10
countries or regions, found surprisingly similar levels of
cholesterol to that in the West, said Professor Anthony Keech of
the University of Sydney.
</P>
<P>
"While obesity is not generally a problem in Asia, we are
seeing higher rates of diabetes and hypertension than in the
West," said Keech, who is chief investigator for the study.
</P>
<P>
"Lifestyle changes as these countries modernize, start eating
more saturated fat and replace exercise with cars, which is
starting to have an impact on death rates," he told the Australian
Associated Press from Dallas.
</P>
<P>
"In the West these problems have peaked but we are quite
fearful that Asian countries are now starting to climb the hill
and their governments are not yet ready for the impact," he
warned.
</P>
<P>
Professor Keech and study coordinator Gemma Ritchie found
smoking rates dramatically higher than similar Western
populations, and little effort to counter the habit.
</P>
<P>
The prevalence of hypertension was as high as 80 percent in
some countries, compared to an average 50 percent in Western
countries.
</P>
<P>
Diabetes was much higher than in Western populations and
although treated with drugs, dietary advice was less often
provided.
</P>
<P>
The big shock was the prevalence of high cholesterol, which has
been traditionally low.
</P>
<P>
In Thailand, only 20 percent of heart patients had levels at
5.5 or higher, but other nations had a greater problem, with
Singapore reaching 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
The study was conducted in Australia, Indonesia, Japan, Korea,
Malaysia, New Zealand, Philippines, Singapore and Thailand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eight People Feared Dead in Kenya Landslide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Eight people are now feared
to have died following a landslide struck Sunday in Maragua
District, Central Province of Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Of the eight, three children were confirmed dead while five
people were missing, the Daily Nation reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A single mother was left childless after her two children,
aged one and five respectively, were buried alive.
</P>
<P>
An eyewitness said Tuesday that the missing persons were with
him at the affected area as the land started tilting at a point
where a water pipe had burst two days ago before the incident.
</P>
<P>
The area affected is half a kilometer long and just over 10
meters wide.
</P>
<P>
During the catastrophe, an earth road connecting western parts
of the province was completely paralyzed and Irati River blocked.
</P>
