<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Enhances Anti-Corruption Effort </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The South African
government is to quadruple the size of the public protector's
office in a bid to crack down on corruption, Business Day paper
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The office's complement would be increased from 32 to 150 to
deal with the backlog of 2,500 cases, Public Service Minister
Zola Skweylya said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It also emerged that Justice Minister Dullah Omar could lead a
review of the role of agencies against corruption, such as the
Heath special investigating unit and the public protector.
</P>
<P>
More funds and resources would be granted to these units,
which are often cash-stripped, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The move coincided with the government's two-day conference
against corruption, which ends Wednesday. Deputy President Thabo
Mbeki, delivering a keynote speech at the conference Tuesday,
warned that corrupt officials would be severely punished.
</P>
<P>
"Zero tolerance will be offered to the parasites of our
land... who have sought their own self-enrichment at state
expense," Mbeki said.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki said government's campaign would include a review of
anti-corruption legislation, drafting of new laws, more efficient
monitoring and management systems, and a more comprehensive
"whistle-blowing" system.
</P>
<P>
Omar said if the cabinet decided that he should lead a review
of agencies against corruption, "I would be quite happy to do
that".
</P>
<P>
More than 200 delegates, including cabinet ministers,
parliamentarians and corruption-fighting officials, attended the
conference, which is aimed at stemming rampant corruption in the
public sector at all levels of government.
</P>
<P>
Omar said they would look at the experience of other regions
and countries such as Hong Kong, Germany and France, where all
role players are mobilized to improve the quality of the fight
against corruption.
</P>
<P>
The conference will pave the way for a national summit on
corruption in February next year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
