<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Motorists to Face Stiff Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Transport costs and passenger
fares may spiral upward in Kenya if the parliament passes a bill
on a Road Safety levy.
</P>
<P>
The new levy is also expected to push up insurance premiums
and the various fees levied by the Registrar of Motor Vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Attorney-General Amos Wako, when issuing the Traffic Amendment
Bill Tuesday, said that proceeds of the proposed levy will be
used to set up a national road safety fund and create the Kenya
Road Safety Authority.
</P>
<P>
The bill proposed stiffer penalties of up to 15 years in jail
for dangerous driving.
</P>
<P>
Reckless driving will expose a first offender to a fine
ranging from 5,000 Shillings (83 U.S. Dollars) to 50,000
Shillings.
</P>
<P>
Second or subsequent reckless driving offenders will face a
fine of up to 75,000 Shillings and imprisonment for up to 12
months.
</P>
<P>
Conviction for dangerous driving will also lead to
disqualification from obtaining or holding a driving license for
three to five years.
</P>
<P>
Overloading public service vehicle with passengers will
attract an enhanced penalty ranging from 20,000 Shillings to
50,000 Shillings.
</P>
<P>
The bill further seeks to prescribe the alcohol limit for
drivers to 35 micrograms of alcohol in 100 milliliters of breath
and a blood concentration of 80 milligrams in 100 milliliters of
blood.
</P>
<P>
Wako explains that the hefty charges are deliberate and
intended to be in line with the inflation rate and moves to
regulate and improve general road safety in the east African
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
