<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Facing Difficult Keeping Crested Ibis From Extinction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAN, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Even though the number of the
crested ibis is increasing, ornithologists are sceptical about how
long the rare bird can survive.
</P>
<P>
One hailstorm could very likely kill all of them, and there is
still a lot to be done, according to Shi Dongchou, a fellow
researcher of the Northwest China Rare and Endangered Species
Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
The crested ibis is a wading bird that mainly feeds on small
fishes in Siberia, Korea, Japan and parts of China. It
disappeared from China in the 1960s, by the 1970s it was seldom
seen in Russia and Korea and it has fared no better in Japan where
there is reportedly only one still living, in captivity.
</P>
<P>
Fortunately, Chinese zoologists discovered some of the species
in the southern Qinling Mountains, its old habitat, in the early
1980s and have taken steps to protect it. Two breeding centers
were set up in Beijing and Yangxian County to breed the birds in
captivity. This has increased the number of crested ibis in China
to 136, with 70 kept at the breeding centers.
</P>
<P>
This is still no guarantee that the species is out of danger,
Shi warned, who continues the field work in Qinling.
</P>
<P>
In addition to natural disasters, inbreeding poses another
threat. The remaining birds are actually descendants of three
couples found in the wild.
</P>
<P>
To ensure that the birds have enough to eat in winter, some
winter paddy fields need to be provided, but the most important
thing is to remove the threats to the natural habitat from human
beings, said Shi.
</P>
<P>
The ibis raised in captivity can not be relied on to continue
the species, Shi warned, saying that the birds' natural habitat
needs to be protected and experiments done on training the birds
to be released back to nature.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 07:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Israeli Soldiers Wounded in West Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Two Israeli soldiers were
wounded near a Jewish settlement in the West Bank Tuesday night,
Israel Radio reported Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the incident occurred near the Jewish
settlement of Otniel when the two soldiers were apparently
ambushed by Palestinian militants who hid by the side of a road.
</P>
<P>
The assailants opened fire on the military truck as the
Israeli soldiers stopped it at a junction.
</P>
<P>
One soldier was hit in the chest and in serious condition. And
the other had small fragments of glass in his head and his wounds
were mild.
</P>
<P>
Following the shooting, dozens of Israeli troops arrived on
the scene and sealed off the area.
</P>
<P>
The Otniel settlement is to the south of the West Bank city of
Hebron.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli army said findings of its initial investigation
were given to the Palestinian police. And the Palestinian police
set up roadblocks around Hebron and searched cars.
</P>
<P>
The shooting happened just hours after Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu announced that his cabinet would continue
discussing the new peace agreement signed with the Palestinians
on Wednesday after two weeks of delay.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said that he had received new assurances from
Palestinian National Authority that it would take necessary steps
to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The radio said that the cabinet meeting is scheduled for
Wednesday afternoon. However, it is not clear whether the
shooting incident will delay the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
