<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Market Survey Business Growing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Market surveys have found
their way into China as the country moves faster towards a market
economy.
</P>
<P>
At a recent seminar on market surveys, it was reported that
China has about 1,000 agencies involved in the business, with
300,000 employees, and 500 million yuan in business annually.
</P>
<P>
Surveys of economic life here started in the 1950s, when local
statistics offices were told by the central government to make
studies of social conditions and incomes of urban workers.
</P>
<P>
But, the business did not become popular until the 1980s when
different provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions all
established their own survey teams.
</P>
<P>
Market survey companies, most of which are based in urban
areas, now fall into three categories: government, private firms,
and overseas-backed agencies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean President Begins Visit to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, November 11 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim
Dae-jung left here for Beijing Wednesday afternoon for a five-day
state visit aimed at establishing a comprehensive and cooperative
relationship with China.
</P>
<P>
Before his departure, Kim said he will discuss various
bilateral, regional and international issues with Chinese leaders,
with an emphasis on ways to cooperate in maintaining peace and
stability on the Korean peninsula, to strengthen cultural
exchanges as well as to realize peace and prosperity in the East
Asian region.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean president also said he will voice his support
for China's entry into the World Trade Organization and the
Bangkok Agreement, which calls for reducing tariffs among the
member nations of the Economic and Social Commission of Asia and
the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
During his first state visit to China, Kim is expected to meet
with Chinese President Jiang Zemin, Premier Zhu Rongji and some
other Chinese leaders.
</P>
<P>
China and South Korea have witnessed rapid development of
bilateral relations since the two countries established full
diplomatic ties in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral trade volume, which stood at 6.4 billion
U.S. dollars in 1992, rose to 23.7 billion dollars in 1997. Since
1992, South Korea's investment in China has amounted to 35.6
billion dollars, making itself China's third largest foreign
investor.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China also becomes South Korea's third largest trade
partner.
</P>
<P>
"It is widely said that the progress which the two nations have
made in the bilateral relations within six years is comparable to
what it takes other countries 50 years to accomplish," said Kwon
Byong-hyon, South Korean ambassador to China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
