<HEADLINE> Japanese PM Leaves For Talks With Russian Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi left here for Moscow Wednesday on a three-day visit to
Russia for talks with Russian leaders in a bid to resolve a
decades-old territorial dispute between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, the first official trip to Russia by a
Japanese prime minister in 25 years, Obuchi and Russian leaders
are expected to have wide-range discussions on bilateral ties as
well as negotiations on a peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
In their summit talks Thursday, Obuchi and Russian President
Boris Yeltsin will reaffirm previous agreements reached by the
leaders of the two countries in November, 1997 and April, 1998 to
work for a conclusion of a peace treaty by 2000 after resolving
the territorial row.
</P>
<P>
The focus of the summit is Russia's response to a demarcation
proposal Japan reportedly made to resolve the dispute over four
Russian-held islands off Hokkaido, according to Japanese official.
</P>
<P>
The dispute over the islands has prevented Japan and Russia
from signing a peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Russia, Obuchi is also expected to meet with
Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov and visit Moscow State
University before leaving for home Friday evening. 
</P>
</TEXT>
