<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Improved Environment in Eastern Chinese Lake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Some progress has been made
in Zhejiang Province in dealing with the pollution problems of
Taihu Lake, one of China's biggest lakes, according to a recent
environmental protection team's inspection.
</P>
<P>
Some 76 percent of 257 enterprises discharging pollutants into
the lake have been equipped with pollution treatment facilities
and 61 enterprises are supposed to speed up construction, the
team, headed by Xie Zhenhua, director of the State Environmental
Protection Administration, found.
</P>
<P>
Taihu Lake, covering an area of 2,400 square kilometers, is an
important source of water for Jiangsu, Zhejiang and Shanghai. The
lake valley in Zhejiang contains the cities of Hangzhou, Jiaxing
and Huzhou in the northern part.
</P>
<P>
The central government has a goal of making all polluters
around the lake reach certain standards by the end of the year,
and the provincial government has formulated policies to support
the effort.
</P>
<P>
Huzhou has spent 98.2 million yuan (about 12 million
U.S. dollars) on pollution treatment, and 49 enterprises have
reached standard levels of discharge and nine seriously polluters
have been closed down.
</P>
<P>
The Minfeng Group, which owns a paper mill in Jiaxing, has
spent more than 10 million yuan on a waste water treatment plant
with a daily capacity of 20,000 cu.m.
</P>
<P>
Hangzhou has combined industrial pollution treatment with urban
environmental protection, with an 80 million yuan fund for 87 key
pollution treatment projects, and stress has been placed on waste
water treatment with a major waste water treatment project
increasing capacity from 400,000 tons to 600,000 tons.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
