<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of five Bangladeshi
prominent chambers and trade associations have reiterated their
fervent appeal to the political parties to shun the path of
"hartal" politics and to cultivate the culture of mutual tolerance
and accommodation, a newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement issued in Dhaka Tuesday, leaders of these
business bodies stressed that using "hartal" as the means of
expressing political difference "serves" no purpose because of the
harm it "inflicts" on the economy.
</P>
<P>
Their appeals, also made in a similar way in the past, would
continue to be ignored but they had no option other than voicing
it once again, they said, adding that their deep concern over the
problems caused to the economy.
</P>
<P>
"Trade and industry regrets that its repeated appeals during
the last several years to the political parties to make an
objective review, if 'hartal' serves any purpose, do not appear to
have been given any consideration," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The trade and industry is deeply aggrieved at the indifference
of political parties to such appeals and indiscriminate uses of
"hartal" to express their grievances, ignoring how "hartal"
affects the economy and hurts the poorer sections of the people,
small traders, rural industries and export trade, it added.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that "hartal" programs which ignore such
aspects of economic life of the people, can not be termed to have
the support of the people, particularly when nearly all sections
of the people have been badly affected by the recent floods.
</P>
<P>
Hartal is a special political phenomenon in Bangladesh. The
opposition party often finds reasons to hold hartals in opposing
the ruling party, while the latter always adopts some counter
measures to control the situation. Clashes between the two sides
always take place.
</P>
<P>
During hartals, all shops are closed, transport stops and
pedestrians are rarely seen in the streets. Therefore, almost all
the economic activities in the capital city and other major cities
in the country are at a standstill for a day or two days or even
more.
</P>
<P>
A day-long nation-wide hartal in Bangladesh will make the
national economy incur an estimated loss of over 3.8 billion taka
(78 million U.S. dollars), Finance Minister S.A.M.S. Kabria said
at a press conference Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
