<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Government to Curb Sugar Dumping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
said it will make tough measures to curb dumping of imported
sugar so as to save local industries from collapse.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture Minister Musalia Mudavadi said Tuesday the
government had already raised the tax on per ton of imported
sugar to 50,000 Shillings (834 U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
"The cost incurred during the processing of a ton of local
sugar is about 36,000 Shillings, which is far lower than the cost
incurred in importing a similar amount of the commodity," he was
quoted by Wednesday's Daily Nation newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the high taxation, among other measures being
undertaken by the government, would ensure there was no more
dumping of the commodity.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he urged local farmers not to sell their maize
stocks at the prevailing low prices as the prices are likely to
rise.
</P>
<P>
"The government is also encouraging relief organizations such
as the World Food Program to consider buying their crop supplies
meant for refugees from the National Cereals and Produce Board
instead of solely relying on imports," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
