<HEADLINE> Jilin Guarantees Basic Subsistence for Laid-off Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Jilin Province in northeast
China will allocate a total of 140 million yuan (7 million US
dollars) this year to guarantee basic subsistence for laid-off
workers.
</P>
<P>
The allocation doubles the 1997 figure. More than 53 million
yuan was done in September alone, and some 307,000 laid-off
workers had received related allowances in the nine months to
September, with 5,800 provincial employment centers finding new
jobs for 230,000 people.
</P>
<P>
According to the rule of the provincial government, working units
and individuals are prohibited from diverting funds earmarked for
laid-off workers, and leading cadres are responsible for ensuring
the basic subsistence of unemployed people.
</P>
<P>
Some 410,000 Liaoning residents are currently unemployed.
</P>
</TEXT>
