<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Tamil Rebel Leader to be Tried in Absentia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Tamil rebel leader
Velupillai Prabhakaran and seven other rebel cadres including his
intelligence chief Pottu Amman are to be tried in absentia in
connection with the Central Bank bomb blast.
</P>
<P>
The application by the Attorney General to try Tamil rebel
leaders in absentia was allowed by Colombo High Court Judge A. W.
Somawansa Tuesday in a hearing, justice sector sources said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
State Counsel Sanjeeva Samaranayake told Mr. Somawansa that the
accused were absconding and living in areas that are not under the
control of the security forces.
</P>
<P>
Warrants had been issued for their arrest but attempts to
arrest them had proved abortive.
</P>
<P>
Therefore the Court allowed the accused to be tried in
absentia, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
The accused are indicted with conspiracy, exploding a bomb at
the Central Bank that resulted in the killing of 90 people and
injuring 1,400 and in causing damage to property on January 31,
1996.
</P>
<P>
The Tamil rebels have been fighting a war against the
government for a separate state in the north and east of the
country since 1983.  
</P>
</TEXT>
