<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India, Largest Source of Toxic Chemicals in S. Asia: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 11 (Xinhua) -- India is the largest source
of highly toxic chemicals in South Asia with several restricted or
banned compounds freely available and stored in huge stockpiles
all over the region, Greenpeace said in a report published here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
India exported a total of nearly 800,000 kilograms of toxic
chemicals called POPs to a number of countries including the
United States and Japan, said the report entitled "Toxic Legacies;
Poisoned Futures; Persistent Organic Pollutants in Asia".
</P>
<P>
India exported about 175,795 kilograms of DDT, which was banned
in most countries of the world, to its neighbors and other
countries like New Zealand, Switzerland and the United Arab
Emirates between April 1997 and January 1998, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
It alleged that India is one of the three countries which
continue to manufacture and export DDT sometime to countries where
its usage is officially banned.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the porous border shared by Nepal and
Bangladesh with India facilitates the smuggling of large
quantities of hazardous chemicals by unscrupulous private
companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
