<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Post-Flood Agri-Loans Disbursed in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
disbursed 5.89 billion taka (121.4 million U.S. dollars)
agri-loans among the flood-hit farmers till October 31 and the
process is still going on, Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina was quoted
as saying by press reports Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The agri-loans are being disbursed among the farmers as her
proper guidelines, she told the parliament Tuesday, asking the
parliament members to monitor the process to check any
irregularities.
</P>
<P>
The government plans to disburse a total of 32.69 billion taka
(674 million dollars) for agri-loans to help flood-affected
farmers minimize their huge crop loss by producing rice without
facing any financial problem.
</P>
<P>
Her government has also suspended realizing the previous year's
agri-loans up to 15,000 taka (206 dollars) and is also
distributing fresh loans to the farmers, the prime minister added.
</P>
<P>
She also stated that the government had distributed 65.5
million taka (1.35 million dollars) in cash as gratuitous relief
and 22.43 million taka (462,470 dollars) for the reconstruction of
houses destroyed by the recent flood.
</P>
<P>
Besides, 120,000 tons of foodgrains have already allocated and
another 120,000 tons will be allocated under the food-for-work
program, and under the test-relief program, 50,000 tons of
foodgrains have been allocated and 50,000 tons more will be
allocated, she said.
</P>
<P>
For tackling a possible good shortage, she said that the
government has imported one million tons of foodgrains while 1-1.5
million tons are being imported at the private level and 700,000
tons coming from the donors.
</P>
<P>
The worst-ever flooding in a century in Bangladesh, which
gripped as much as two thirds of the country and seriously
affected over 30 million people for ten weeks, washed away about
one million hectares of paddy-field and paddy-seedlings, causing
an estimated loss of two million tons of rice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
