<HEADLINE> New Zealand to Permit Armed APEC Bodyguards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand Government
is to amend the law to enable foreign armed bodyguards to
accompany leaders at the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC)
forum in Auckland next September.
</P>
<P>
The Dominion newspaper said Wednesday that the change is to
ease the concerns of U.S. authorities who "threatened that the
U.S. might not attend if bodyguards could not carry weapons".
</P>
<P>
The Wellington-based newspaper quoted Foreign Affairs and Trade
Minister Don McKinnon and Police Minister Clem Simich as saying
Tuesday that the Arms Act amendment would enable selected
bodyguards accompanying "some world leaders" at APEC meetings to
carry guns.
</P>
<P>
Police Commissioner Peter Doone would personally issue permits
to the approved bodyguards.
</P>
<P>
the paper said the two New Zealand ministers said the permits
would be given "only to world leaders", but neither they nor Mr.
Doone would say who those leaders were.
</P>
<P>
"Background information they made public mentions the leaders
of the United States, Russia, and China in particular", the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
Minister McKinnon said the law change is not something the
government is taking lightly.
</P>
<P>
"APEC is an unprecedented event for New Zealand. We are
expecting the world leaders of 20 economies to visit. The event
requires a level of security we have never had to provide before,"
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
