<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand to Launch Breast Screening Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, November 11 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand's first
national free breast cancer screening program will start next
month.
</P>
<P>
The program was suggested in 1995 by Prime Minister Jenny
Shipley, who was then health minister, and was to have started
last year but was postponed after the merger of the four regional
health authorities into one agency.
</P>
<P>
The Dominion newspaper Wednesday quoted Bernie Mullin, manager
of public health program of the Health Funding Authority, as
saying that the breast screen program would help reduce the
number of premature deaths caused by breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
The Wellington-based newspaper also quoted authority figures as
showing 10 percent of New Zealand women develop breast cancer and
600 die from it each year.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Mullin said all women aged 50 to 64 with no symptoms of
breast cancer would be invited to receive a free mammogram
(breast X-ray) every two years.
</P>
<P>
"The mammograms will be checked by at least two radiologists
who will be looking for small cancers. Women will be sent the
results within two weeks."
</P>
<P>
Dr. Mullin said women who needed further checking would be
called back for more X-rays, an ultrasound scan or a biopsy.
</P>
<P>
During the next five years the aim is to get 70 percent of the
eligible 241,000 women enrolled in the program and tested, Dr.
Millin said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Population Growing Slowly in New Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, November 11 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand resident
population was estimated at 3,797,100 at the end of September this
year, Deputy Government Statistician Dianne Macaskill announced
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a media release, Macaskill said this represented an increase
of 26,900 or 0.7 percent over the figure a year ago. The growth
rate was half the average annual growth rate of 1.4 percent
recorded for the previous five years.
</P>
<P>
The release said that a substantial turnaround in the external
migration balance was the main factor in the slower growth.
Permanent and long-term departures exceeded arrivals by 3,900
during the year to September, compared with a migration gain of
12,900 in the previous year. Over the same period natural increase
(excess of births over deaths) rose from 30,000 to 30,800.
</P>
<P>
According to the release, the median age of the New Zealand
population was estimated at 33.8 years at the end of September,
compared with 31.6 years in 1991. The population aged 65 years and
over now makes up 11.7 percent of all New Zealand residents, and
56.5 percent of these are women. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Trade Deficit Narrows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, November 11 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand merchandise
trade balance has shown an improving trend over the past five
months, turning around the decline that began in August 1997,
Government Statistician Len Cook said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a media release, Cook said this is because the exports trend
is rising, assisted by the lower New Zealand dollar, while imports
are showing a declining trend.
</P>
<P>
According to the release, New Zealand reported a merchandise
trade deficit of 210 million NZ dollars (111.3 million U.S.
dollars), down from a deficit of 308 million NZ dollars (163.2
million U.S. dollars) in the same month last year.
</P>
<P>
Merchandise exports in September, 1998, were 1,837 million NZ
dollars (975 million U.S. dollars), 9.6 percent higher than in
September 1997.
</P>
<P>
In addition to an increase of 23 percent in New Zealand exports
to Europe in September, exports to Asia also grew despite the
Asian economic crisis. New Zealand exports to Asia, at 632
million NZ dollars (335 million U.S. dollars), were almost the
same level as a year ago, the release said.
</P>
<P>
For the year to September, 1998, merchandise exports of New
Zealand were 22,102 million NZ dollars (11,714 million U.S.
dollars), 4.8 percent higher than in the previous year, it added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
