<HEADLINE> Argentina, Brazil to Build Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Argentina and Brazil will
jointly build a 350-kilogram satellite ready for launch in the
year 2003, according to an agreement signed here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The satellite will be used to monitor the environment and the
growth of crops as well as in natural calamity forecasts in the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
Under the pact aimed at increasing bilateral cooperation on
space technologies, Brazil will also provide Argentina with a
rocket for testing Argentine-made flight, navigation and control
systems, so that Argentina will be able to launch its own
satellites in the future.
</P>
<P>
The two countries will also exchange information received by
their ground stations.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Chairman of the Argentine Space
Commission Conrado Varotto and Chairman of the Brazilian Space
Agency Meira Filho.
</P>
<P>
They described the agreement as a big step toward the regional
integration of the member nations of Mercosur (South American
Common Market). 
</P>
</TEXT>
