<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Nightmare for Filipinos by Chen Hegao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 11 (Xinhua) -- It is a true story. When a
Filipino-
Chinese millionaire invites his friends out for dinner in evening,
he
never uses his luxurious Mercedes-Benz, but always sits in a
Toyota, or
Honda of his friends, for fear of being kidnapped.
</P>
<P>
He has become very nerves since one of his family members was
kidnapped for a ransom of 75 million pesos (about three million
U.S.
dollars) five years ago.
</P>
<P>
This is not an individual case any more in the country. For
many
Filipinos, particularly some well-to-do Filipino-Chinese, they
have been
living with a nightmare of kidnapping for many years, as such
incidents
are increasing year by year, despite the continuous crackdown by
the
government.
</P>
<P>
When a U.S. magazine described the Philippines as the capital
of
kidnapping in Asia last year, the Ramos administration was
outraged,
dismissing as "exaggeration" of the figures cited by the magazine.
</P>
<P>
Then, Ramos ordered an all-out war against the kidnappers, and
claimed
victories soon.
</P>
<P>
But cracking down on kidnappers is like fighting an endless
war,
kidnapping cases have not declined in the Philippines, but
increased
rapidly.
</P>
<P>
According to Kidnap Watch, a crime watch organization in the
Philippines, in 1993, 107 incidents were reported with 179 victims
and
the total ransom paid amounted to 2.5 million U.S. dollars, but in
1997,
152 incidents were reported with 249 victims. The total ransom
paid in
the year increased to 10.4 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
When President Joseph Estrada came to office on July 1, he
vowed to
improve his country's image by wiping out kidnapping syndicates in
six
months.
</P>
<P>
But to his dismay, since June 30, 61 people have been kidnapped
in 32
incidents.
</P>
<P>
On August 26, a 38-year-old businessman named Willyson Ong was
kidnapped and was killed by the abductors 39 days later before his
family
could pay any ransom.
</P>
<P>
Ong's death aroused strong reactions from the Filipino-Chinese
community. On October 11, some 2,000 Filipino-Chinese marched
during Ong's funeral procession to protest against the kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
Seven Major Filipino-Chinese organizations issued a statement,
urging Estrada "to use all his power to direct his men to go after
Ong's killers and all remaining kidnap-for ransom syndicates."
</P>
<P>
In response to the appeal, President Estrada ordered the
national police and the intelligence to work together against
kidnapping syndicates. In the past three weeks, scores of
kidnappers have been arrested and millions of pesos been
recovered. The government expressed its confidence that kidnapping
groups would be caught by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
But in the Filipino-Chinese community, people are less
optimistic about the situation. In Manila's China Town, people
dare not go out for any functions after dark.
</P>
<P>
On November 3, just a week after the police arrested nine
suspects in the kidnap-murder of Willyson Ong, an old lady working
for her brother in a furniture shop in China Town expressed her
dismay to new kidnapping incidents. She said that her family
members are worried about her safety even when she was staying in
the shop during the day time.
</P>
<P>
She doubted that the government could wipe out all kidnapping
syndicates in such a short period, as Estrada's predecessors tried
their best for so many years but failed in the end.
</P>
<P>
Now, time seems running short. There are less than two months
left before the deadline, but many victims, including some foreign
nationals, are still in the hands of kidnappers.
</P>
<P>
Who should be blamed for the increasing number of abductions?
</P>
<P>
The authorities say that the increasing kidnappings take place
simply because the families of victims failed to report the
incidents to the police.
</P>
<P>
But the victim families allegedly say that some criminal groups
have good connections with some policemen.
</P>
<P>
In Mindanao, the Southern Philippines, rebel groups often
kidnap people for political reasons.
</P>
<P>
As the problem is not so simple that kidnapping will not
disappear in the country quickly, at least in the coming months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
