<HEADLINE> U.S. Pledges to Control Small Arms Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The United States -- the
world's number one arms seller -- will strengthen controls over
the export of small arms, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The State Department has increased scrutiny of export licenses
"to make sure end users are the real end users" and laws have been
tightened to prevent Americans from facilitating arms deals abroad
that would be illegal at home, Albright said in a speech.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Customs Service has also increased efforts to block
illegal arms shipments and the Justice Department has stepped up
prosecutions of traffickers caught smuggling arms into Mexico, she
said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the International Rescue Committee at an awards
dinner in New York, Albright talked about the challenge presented
by the "uncontrolled flow of arms, ammunition and explosives into
tense areas of the world."
</P>
<P>
"It is a tragic truth of our times that in many places where it
is impossible to find a wholesome meal or a warm bed, it is easy
to find a gun or a grenade," she said.
</P>
<P>
Albright said the U.S. would also work to create an African
center for technical assistance and training, in order to
establish stronger law enforcement networks to fight uncontrolled
small arms trafficking. 
</P>
</TEXT>
