<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's "Universal-Joint King" Has Farmland Roots (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Lu Guanqiu is sitting in
front of a computer in his office, pulling up information about
the companies in his Wanxiang Group and the movement of China's
stock market.
</P>
<P>
"In the next five years, I hope my stocks can be listed on the
New York and Tokyo exchanges," the 53-year-old chairman of the
board of China's largest universal joint manufacturer says.
</P>
<P>
It's been a long road to this position. Lu was born into a
peasant family in the town of Ningwei in east Zhejiang province,
and 20 years ago never went any farther than the paddy fields
around his village. In the past, poor transportation kept China
backward.
</P>
<P>
In 1969, during the turmoil of the Cultural Revolution, Lu and
six of his fellow villagers started a blacksmith shop, but they
continued to live in poverty. It wasn't until 1978, the year China
started its ambitious reform, opening-up, and modernization drive,
that the chance to change arrived.
</P>
<P>
In 1979, Lu and his companions started manufacturing universal
joints, which they believed had a promising future in China, which
was trying to improve its transportation sector, because the
U-joint was such an important part of all vehicles.
</P>
<P>
These farmers-turned-industrialists started from scratch, doing
everything by themselves because of China's planned economy, with
everything under the sun controlled by state businesses.
</P>
<P>
They worked on drawings of universal joints and scoured state
factory dumps for raw materials, scavenging around for half-burned
lumps of coal, scrap iron and steel, and any old equipment.
</P>
<P>
Not only that, but they had to develop their own market, Lu
recalls, because in a planned economy, factories produced and
delivered everything in accordance with government orders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Universal Joint King" (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
To make matters worse, the tiny township company soon ran into
a lot of competition from 54 state manufacturers with the same
product. But, Lu felt confident that lower costs and higher
quality could help a product survive on the market.
</P>
<P>
However, their first products failed to meet customers'
expectations and about 60,000 U.S. dollars worth of these products
went down the drain and were sold to scrap dealers. The company's
annual sales were only 500,000 U.S. dollars. "My employees will
never forget this costly lesson," he says.
</P>
<P>
But, that lesson made the budding industrialists aware of the
importance of information, and they now have a night school to
train personnel, and have even hired at least 1,000 college grads,
some with masters or doctors degrees.
</P>
<P>
Lu's businesses took off in the late 1980s, when the government
increased reforms. As early as 1984, this ambitious man began to
eye overseas markets and managed to sell 30,000 U-joints to Panax,
which was the largest U-joint maker in the U.S. at that time.
</P>
<P>
Then, in 1990, his Wanxiang Group came into being in the city
of Xiaoshan in Zhejiang, when they merged eight state factories,
because the government was selling some money-losing state firms
as part of its reforms. It soon had 65 percent of the domestic
market. Wanxiang's products are now doing well in 34 countries and
regions, and this year, Wanxiang started supplying the
U.S. automotive giants GM and Chrysler.
</P>
<P>
Since 1994, Wanxiang has had companies in the U.S., Britain,
Canada, and Latin America, and a number of warehouses in the U.S.,
Mexico, and Britain.
</P>
<P>
Although Wanxiang is still a township enterprise, it had 2.89
billion yuan in sales and 100 million U.S. dollars worth of
exports last year. The State Council has listed it among the
country's 120 enterprises that are experimenting with a modern
enterprise system and one of Wanxiang's companies has been listed
on China's stock exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Lu recently told an international seminar on enterprise
strategies in Shanghai that was attended by business people and
officials from all over the world, including Britain's Prime
Minister Tony Blair, "The flourishing township enterprises in
China have contributed not only to the development of the rural
economy, but also to the improvement of Chinese farmers."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
