<HEADLINE> Coffee Harvest Drops Sharply in Hurricane-Hit Costa Rica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Coffee output in southern
Costa Rican plantations, severely affected by Hurricane Mitch in
October, has fallen by 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rican Coffee Institute president Guillermo Canet said
Tuesday that Mitch had damaged saplings, reducing the country's
targeted output of three million bags of coffee by 92,000 bags
(each bag weighing 60 kilograms).
</P>
<P>
He warned that losses could increase if the government fails to
repair roads and bridges soon to allow trucks to carry coffee to
the docks.
</P>
<P>
Coffee matures earlier in southern Costa Rica, compared with
the north of the country where most producers are gathered.
</P>
<P>
Fortunately, Mitch did not affect the country's banana crops as
they were mostly planted on the Caribbean coast which was left
intact by the hurricane. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
