<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukrainian National Debts Mount $14.9 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine's national debts reached
14.9 billion U.S. dollars by the end of September, amounting to
48.4 percent of the country's gross domestic product (GDP) in the
period.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Minister of Finance Igor Michukov in a
speech to the parliament Tuesday. According to the minister,
foreign debts stood at 10.9 billion dollars and internal debts at
3.9 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that there is a slim possibility for his
country to encounter a debt crisis in the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
According to international standard, the minister said, the
amount of the current national debts does not come up to the level
of crisis.
</P>
<P>
He told the legislators that foreign debts increased 1.4
billion dollars, or 14.4 percent over the same period of last
year, which were mainly used to balance budget deficit and provide
export credit guarantees.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the repayment of foreign debts cost the government
1.2 billion dollars, according to Michukov.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that the total foreign debts are expected to fall
to 37.2 percent of GDP by the end of this year, and debt repayment
for 1998 will cost 25.7 percent of the government's spending, a
figure close to the internationally recognized crisis level of 25
to 30 percent, Michukov said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
