<HEADLINE> China, Britain Have Their First Financial Dialogue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 10 (Xinhua) - Chinese Financial Minister Xiang
Huaicheng held talks Tuesday with British Chancellor Gordon Brown
on the occasion of the first China-UK Financial Dialogue in London.
</P>
<P>
Their discussions ranged widely over both domestic
macroeconomic and microeconomic policies and international
economic and financial issues.
</P>
<P>
Both sides recognized the importance of China's contribution to
international financial stability via its positive, commendable
and responsible policy with regard to the RMB exchange rate and
agreed on the importance of an orderly and progressive approach to
capital account liberalization.
</P>
<P>
Xiang outlined the measures implemented throughout the course
of the year to stimulate China's economy and to ensure sustainable
growth.
</P>
<P>
He also reiterated China's commitment to moving towards a
socialist market economy, particularly to restructuring both its
state-owned enterprises and its financial system.
</P>
<P>
Brown set out the action taken to build a stable economy
capable of sustained and steady growth in Britain.
</P>
<P>
He also mentioned the Pre-budget Report, a strategy to address
the fundamental structural weaknesses that had held back the
British economy in the past.
</P>
<P>
Both sides recognized how the two issues of enterprise and
financial sector reform were inter-related, and how recent
experience elsewhere in Asia highlighted the need for sound
financial and regulatory systems.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers also noted the numerous bilateral schemes
aimed at assisting with the development of the financial services
infrastructure within China.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed to take forward the China-UK Financial
Dialogue in China within the next 18 months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
