<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Families Now Better Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, November 11 (Xinhua) -- A recent study has shown that
90 percent of the families in Shanghai are living comfortable
lives and 98.8 percent have annual incomes above 10,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
A similar 1990 study showed that 23.4 percent of the families
considered themselves comfortable, but only 5.6 percent reported
annual incomes above 10,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
The standard of living in Shanghai has obviously improved since
1994, and by 1997 about 93 percent of the families are living at a
comfortable level.
</P>
<P>
There is also a widening gap between different income
groups. Low-income families have seen a relatively moderate rise
in incomes, while high-income families have doubled or even
tripled their incomes.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that the changes are a result of Shanghai's
economic and industrial restructuring of the past decade, with the
unified income structure of the planned economy broken up and the
country developing a more diverse income structure.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy, Albania to Curb Illegal Immigration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Italian and Albanian leaders
Tuesday pledged to work together to fight organized crime and
gangs engaged in illegal immigration across the Adriatic.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed following talks between Italian Prime
Minister Massimo D'Alema and his visiting Albanian counterpart
Pandeli Majko, Italian police would "advise and assist" Albanian
authorities in fighting organized crime, including smuggling of
illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
With help from Italian gangs, Albanian illegal immigrants
arrive on an almost daily basis on the southeastern coast of
Italy, in the Puglia region.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema said at a press conference that Italy also promised to
promote political, economic and cultural cooperation with Albania
and help the country forge closer ties with the European Union and
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
</P>
<P>
Italy also agreed to encourage Italian businesses to invest in
Albania.
</P>
<P>
The Albanian prime minister said on the same occasion that the
purpose of the bilateral cooperation was to "create a hopeful
living environment and create more jobs in Albania."
</P>
<P>
The Italian electric utility Enel and its Albanian counterpart
Kesh also signed an agreement on Tuesday, under which Italy will
provide 6 billion lire (3.6 million U.S. dollars) to help cope
with the energy crisis in the Albanian capital of Tirana this
winter.
</P>
<P>
Majko arrived here Monday for a two-day official visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0307 </DOCNO>
