<HEADLINE> Indonesian Football Association to File to FIFA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia will file an
appeal to the International Football Association (FIFA), unless
the Asian Football Confederation (AFC) cancels its life-long
suspension of Mursyid Effendi, Antara News Agency reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the All Indonesia Football Association (PSSI) Agum
Gumelar said here Tuesday he was very dissappointed with AFC's
decision last week to suspend Mursyid from domestic and
international soccer matches permanently.
</P>
<P>
"AFC has put an end to our player's career, which is not
human, and we therefore hope they review their decision. If AFC
refuses to change the suspension, we will file an appeal to world
football federation," Gumelar said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian defender Mursyid had scored a controversial own
goal in the Tiger Cup tournament in Ho Chi Minh city, Vietnam,
last August.
</P>
<P>
In the last Tiger Cup qualification rounds, Indonesia and
Thailand, who have secured a place in the semi-finals, did not
wish to win the game, so they played for a defeat to avoid the
Vietnamese team.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN Football Association has punished PSSI by a fine of
20,000 U.S. dollars for playing "negative football".
</P>
<P>
This week, PSSI general secretary Nugraha Besoes will leave
Jakarta for Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, where AFC's headquarters is
located, for talks with AFC officials.
</P>
<P>
Gumelar argued that the punishment on Mursyid should not be
heavier than on a player involved in bribery or doping. 
</P>
</TEXT>
