<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Beer Market Becoming Competitive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 11 (Xinhua) -- China's beer producers are
gradually scaling down production to adjust to a market glut and
decreasing efficiency, according to a recent issue of China
Business Times.
</P>
<P>
China produced 9.7 million tons of beer in the first half of
this year, an increase of 5.88 percent from the same period last
year. This compares with a growth of 14.39 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
A State Statistics Bureau study found that beer stockpiles are
increasing and that nearly half of the brewers are losing money.
</P>
<P>
And, as the market becomes saturated, competition gets fiercer,
with the market share of small brewers being taken by bigger ones.
</P>
<P>
In Hebei Province, for instance, 69 percent of the brewers
produced less beer than last year but the province's total output
had an annual increase of 15.4 percent, with a few brewers
increasing output by more than 20 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
