chairman of DPJ Executive Board.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Statistics from the People's Bank of China (PBC) show that
China's financial sector continued its smooth operation through
the end of October, with the central bank's policy of
appropriately increasing the money supply producing obvious
results.
</P>
<P>
The outstanding amount of broad money (M2) at the end of
October was 10.086 trillion yuan, up 16.3 percent from the same
period last year, and reaching the control target of 16-18 percent
growth named by the PBC at the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the outstanding amount of narrow money (M1)
was 3.6785 trillion yuan, up 13.5 percent; the outstanding amount
of money in circulation (M0) was 1.05 trillion yuan, up 10.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
-- Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien will pay an official
visit to China from November 19 to 21 at the invitation of Chinese
Premier Zhu Rongji.
</P>
<P>
President Juan Ignacio Barrero of the Spanish Senate will pay a
goodwill visit to China from November 14 to 21, announced foreign
ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao at yesterday's routine press
conference.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The State Drug Administration (SDA) is strengthening control
over the quality of imported medicines, by requiring the products
have registration certificates and a validation stamp. The
initiative was implemented this month.
</P>
<P>
-- Anti-flood campaigns should not just be labor-intensive
undertakings in the future, but should use technology to keep
damage to a minimum, according to a government minister. The
Ministry of Science and Technology has drawn up short- and
long-term disaster-relief plans.  
</P>
