<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy: European Central Bank Must Be More Decentralized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Bank of Italy governor Antonio
Fazio said Tuesday that Europe's national central bank chiefs must
fight to retain significant influence over monetary policy when
the single currency is introduced next year.
</P>
<P>
In a front-page interview with the Financial Times, Fazio said
that the European Central Bank, which is set to take over monetary
policy from the national central banks, could be the scene of
power clashes between the 11 national governors and the six
members of the permanent executive who together form the ECB's
governing council.
</P>
<P>
He said, "Everything that can be decentralized must be
decentralized.
</P>
<P>
"This is the basic principle even of the Maastricht Treaty."
</P>
<P>
Stressing the importance of the national central banks, he
said, "It is important to remember that the credibility and
strength of the council derives from the credibility and strength
of the national central banks themselves."
</P>
<P>
Italy, whose economy is expected to grow by 1.5 percent this
year, lower than that of the other 11 single currency states,
would have to fight harder for a euro zone interest rate that
suits its needs.
</P>
<P>
Fazio has often warned that Italy is not sufficiently prepared
for the rigor that the economic and monetary union entails.
</P>
<P>
"We have bought time," he said. "The country is enjoying a
virtuous circle of declining interest rates and lower interest
payment on its debt. I hope structural adjustments can be made,
otherwise the circle will turn vicious."
</P>
<P>
Fazio disagreed with the interest rate cuts proposed by Germany
and France.
</P>
<P>
"It is one thing to reduce (interest rates) from seven percent
to five percent but to go from four percent to two percent would
have no significant effect on the economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also said it would be necessary to cut costs and introduce
flexibility into the labour market in order to boost economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
"We need more flexibility in both (public and private)
sectors," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Now that we are moving to what is effectively a hard money
standard, the failure to create more flexibility will lead to
reduced employment."
</P>
<P>
Refuting criticism of his tight monetary policies in the
lead-up to joining the euro, Fazio said, "I delivered the right
dose of hawkishness for Italy given the circumstances of our
past." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
