<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northwestern Chinese Kazaks Ending Nomadic Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The Kazaks of northwest China's
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region are leaving the nomadic life
they've led for over 2,000 years behind.
</P>
<P>
The Kazak ethnic group began its nomadic life in the Altay
Grassland, Junggar Basin, Tianshan Mountain, and Ili River areas
as early as 2,000 years ago. A kingdom set up by Kazaks north of
the Tianshan Mountains was called the "Moving Kingdom" in Chinese
histories.
</P>
<P>
One family couldn't get used to the new life when they first
moved to a village in Xinyuan County in the eastern valley of the
Ili River.
</P>
<P>
"My great grandfather lived on the Kunes grassland and I lived
a nomadic life on the grassland for more than 70 years," said
Tohuda Mishi.
</P>
<P>
But, natural disasters and a tough climate in the region's
pastureland affected their daily lives a great deal.
</P>
<P>
And now he's quite satisfied with his changed lifestyle. His
family raises around 300 sheep and nearly 40 cows, about six times
the number they kept in the past. They feed the cows and sheep
with hay they put in storage except on the grasslands in summer.
</P>
<P>
They sell 100 sheep annually and make 30,000-40,000 yuan
(3,600-4,800 U.S. dollars), said Tohuda, adding "Mine is just an
ordinary family."
</P>
<P>
To date, more than 10,000 Kazak households, 70 percent of the
total, with more than 60,000 people, have given up their nomadic
life since the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Kazaks have tried their hand in other areas
like growing maize and cotton, transportation, restaurants, and
other businesses. And improvements in their lives has caused them
to pay more attention to telephones, automobiles and
information. Many have even visited Australia and New Zealand, or
other countries that used to be just a dream several years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0314 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
