<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Four Prominent Figures Hold "National </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian four prominent
national figures finally were able to meet on Tuesday, issuing a
united stance on President B.J. Habibie's administration and the
Armed Forces' role in politics.
</P>
<P>
Dubbed a "national dialogue", the meeting was held at the house
of Abdurrahman Wahid, chairman of the 40 million-strong Muslim
organization Nahdlatul Ulama, in south of Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
Other participants were Amien Rais, chairman of the National
Mandate Party, Megawati Soekarnoputri, who leads a popular faction
of the Indonesian Democratic Party, and Yogyakarta Governor Sri
Sultan Hamengkubuwono.
</P>
<P>
The four top political leaders agreed at the meeting that the
country should have had a legitimate new government three months
after a snap election, scheduled for next May, was held to replace
the current transitional government under Habibie.
</P>
<P>
"By the end of next year, Habibie should no longer be the
president," said Amien, reading out the results of the 30-minute
meeting which students had strived to organize since Friday.
</P>
<P>
The "national dialogue" was a much-anticipated affair, given
the high profile and political clout of the participants. Hundreds
of students camped outside the residence to make sure that it took
place.
</P>
<P>
The four leaders supported growing public calls for the
sociopolitical role of the Armed Forces to end "within six years".
</P>
<P>
Several quarters including some students have demanded the
revocation of the Armed Forces' socio-political role.
</P>
<P>
Abdurrahman said it would not be possible to bring the era of
military involvement in politics to a close overnight.
</P>
<P>
"Nahdlatul Ulama respects the Armed Forces dual function, but
the role is now an anachronism," he said.
</P>
<P>
The four leaders called for national unity consistent and
demanded the return of the people's sovereignty by maximizing the
role and function of elected representatives.
</P>
<P>
They called for a fair and just general election monitored by
an independent team to be held next year.
</P>
<P>
They said the fight against corruption, collusion and nepotism
must be intensified, with Amien at this point adding that the
drive should begin with an investigation into the wealth of former
president Soeharto, his family and his cronies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
