<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN's FAO Helping Southwestern China Reduce Grain Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Using grain storage techniques
from the UN Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO), Sichuan
Province has cut grain losses by some 10 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
A traditional grain production base in southwest China, Sichuan
has an annual grain output of over 35 billion kg, 70 percent of
which is stored by farmers themselves. But, about two billion kg
of grain is lost annually because of problems with traditional
bamboo and wood storage methods.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, Sichuan introduced FAO storage methods using brick
rooms and fumigants, effectively putting an end to grain lost to
pests and rot.
</P>
<P>
This technique has been used in more than 60 towns in Sichuan,
with 6,000 new storage rooms. Each room can hold 1,500-2,000 kg of
grain and save about 10 percent in losses.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0319 </DOCNO>
