<HEADLINE> Devastated Central America Appeals for International Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Five Central American
presidents Tuesday urged the international community to help
rebuild their countries which were shattered by Hurricane Mitch.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement issued after a meeting in San Salvador,
the presidents of Costa Rica, El Salvador, Honduras, Nicaragua and
Guatemala said their rescue capacity could not cope with the huge
damage in the region, where at least 11,000 were killed and
millions made homeless by the deadliest Atlantic storm in two
centuries.
</P>
<P>
"We call on the World Bank, the International Monetary Fund,
the Interamerican Development Bank and the Central American
Integration Bank to collaborate with countries in the region to
prepare a rescue and reconstruction program for Central America,"
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The five presidents called for an emergency group to coordinate
financial aid to the region.
</P>
<P>
"Central America also hopes that the international community
support will include free access to its markets for all our
exports products, to contribute to our economic rehabilitation and
to the creation of jobs," the statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
