<HEADLINE> NBA Union to Discuss Strategy Tomorrow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The NBA union's
negotiating committee and several player representatives will
meet Wednesday to discuss strategy on how to present another
proposal to the owners.
</P>
<P>
The sides haven't met since last Friday after a 90-minute
meeting failed to produce any results.
</P>
<P>
"My guess is we'll hear something from the union after their
meeting Wednesday," NBA deputy commissioner Russ Granik said
today.
</P>
<P>
Union director Billy Hunter has spent the past several days
speaking with players and agents by telephone, an action to fend
off what commissioner David Stern did in the past few days. Stern
lifted the ban that prevented team personnel from discussing the
lockout with players, and encouraged team general managers and
coaches to persuade players to accept owners' proposal.
</P>
<P>
Phoenix Suns owner Jerry Colangelo reportedly has talked with
at least five players, but wouldn't comment on the discussions.
</P>
<P>
The season should have started on November 3, but now it will
not be possible to begin until mid-December at the earliest.
Stern has said a deal needs to be reached before mid-December,
otherwise the cancellation of the entire season would be possible.
</P>
<P>
The league and union are fighting over how to divide about 2
billion U.S. dollars in annual revenues. The players, who
received 57 percent last season, now want 60 percent, while the
league is offering only a 50-50 split. 
</P>
</TEXT>
