<HEADLINE> Sheffield Wednesday Chairman Attacks Italian Duo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Sheffield Wednesday chairman
Dave Richards said he will happily sell the club's two Italian
forwards for the good of the team.
</P>
<P>
He is bitter at having to pay Paolo Di Canio's wages while he
sits idly on the sidelines completing an 11-match ban for his
shove on referee Paul Alcock.
</P>
<P>
Fellow Italian Benito Carbone has also come in for criticism
from Richards for his contribution, although the chairman has
expressed relief that a bid for Pierre van Hooijdonk did not come
off.
</P>
<P>
Richards has revealed that Di Canio's enforced lay-off is
costing the club 119,000 in wages alone.
</P>
<P>
That is despite Wednesday apparently fining Di Canio 68,000 --
two lots of two weeks' wages for each incident.
</P>
<P>
The chairman believes Di Canio should have had to pay the
price -- with a record-breaking 250,000 fine by the FA -- and
just a three-match suspension.
</P>
<P>
Instead, the FA's disciplinary commission only gave the
28-year-old a 10,000 slap on the wrist with the 11 match ban.
</P>
<P>
Richards is angry that he club is paying the price and not the
player.
</P>
<P>
"It's about time we started telling the truth. The club are
still paying his wages and yet we cannot use his services," said
the frustrated Hillsborough chairman.
</P>
<P>
"We paid 4.75 million pounds for this striker who is ever so
talented and is a nice guy. But these guys have got to perform on
the pitch, " he said.
</P>
<P>
He admits he would not stand in boss Danny Wilson's way if he
decided to get rid of Di Canio, as well as Carbone.
</P>
<P>
"If he said Di Canio and Carbone have got to go, then they've
got to go.
</P>
<P>
"To me, as an individual and a supporter, I love to watch
them. But I think their contribution to the team is not
sufficient, " he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
