<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Female Football Agent Attacks PFA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Britain's only female football
agent Rachel Anderson attacked the Professional
Footballers'Association (PFA) as "dinosaurs".
</P>
<P>
According to local reports on Tuesday, the female agent made
her comments when she began a legal battle against the PFA - the
players' union - for alleged sex discrimination.
</P>
<P>
The 41-year-old, from Westcliff in Essex, was invited to the
PFA annual awards ceremony in April by West Ham defender Julian
Dicks, because she is his agent.
</P>
<P>
But the PFA refused to let her attend, saying it was a "men
only" event.
</P>
<P>
The mother-of-two is claiming "exemplary damages" against the
PFA for alleged breach of the Sexual Discrimination Act and
"injury to feelings".
</P>
<P>
A private hearing, which will decide if Mrs Anderson has a
claim, took place at Central London County Court on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The 15-minute hearing was adjourned until a later date which
was not fixed.
</P>
<P>
Afterwards Mrs Anderson, who did not attend the hearing, said:
"I find the PFA's attitude more insulting to their sex than to
mine, it's not the common attitude of men in today's world - they
are truly dinosaurs.
</P>
<P>
"They are out of their little minds. How can they say I
haven't got a case? If it was a private affair they would be
quite right to say they can invite who they like, but the mere
fact that I can't go because I'm a girl ... that's absurd."
</P>
<P>
Mrs Anderson has been a football agent for seven years and is
the only woman agent accredited by FIFA, the sport's world
governing body.
</P>
<P>
She also represents Everton midfielder Don Hutchison and the
Wimbeldon and Northern Ireland international Michael Hughes.
</P>
<P>
The incident sparked outrage among some football officials and
politicians.
</P>
<P>
British Sports Minister Tony Banks and FA chief executive Gra
ham Kelly both boycotted the ceremony in support of her.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair also wrote a letter of
support which stated: "The government deplores discrimination."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0340 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNHCR: Conflicts Block Solutions to Refugee Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Increasing Conflicts
were slowing down and often blocking solutions to refugees
problems, the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Even when political settlements are reached and people
voluntarily return to their homes, the peace established can at
best be described as fragile," Sadako Ogata told the United Nations
Security Council.
</P>
<P>
"From our perspective, the increasingly blurred lines between
war and peace, and the necessity to reach out to victims of
forced displacement across those lines, make the protection of
refugees and returnees a more complex exercise than ever
before," she continued.
</P>
<P>
"Where peace efforts are insufficient, or ineffective, the
ability of humanitarian agencies to help refugees, returnees and
other victims of conflict is greatly diminished," she stressed.
</P>
<P>
"My request to you is that when you discuss ongoing or
potential conflicts, you do not overlook the human displacement
factor, which is often an effect, but can also be a cause of
conflict," Ogata told the Council.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0341 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Davenport in Action Tuesday at Advanta Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Top-ranked Lindsay
Davenport of the United States begins her final tuneup for next
week's Chase Championships when she takes on fellow American
Kimberly Po tonight in second-round play at the Advanta
Championships indoor tennis event in Philadelphia, the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Davenport has won a WTA Tour-leading six titles this year,
including a victory over Switzerland's Martina Hingis in the
U.S.Open final to win her first Grand Slam singles title.
</P>
<P>
She has reached the final of three of the last four
tournaments she has played, including a victory at the European
Championships in Zurich in her most recent event. A sore right
arm kept Davenport out of action until this week.
</P>
<P>
The 22-year-old, who lost to Hingis in a thrilling three-set
final here last year, leads the second-ranked Hingis by only 266
points in the rankings heading into the final two events of the
year.
</P>
<P>
Three first-round matches were completed in the day session,
with one upset. Elena Likhovtseva of Russia was leading eighth
seed Sandrine Testud of France 7-6 (7-2), 6-7 (4-7), 1-0 when
Testud retired with a right knee injury.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Japan's Ai Sugiyama, fighting for a berth in next
week's Chase Championships, crushed Maria Alejandra Vento of Ve
nezuela 6-1, 6-2; and American qualifier Brie Rippner beat
Alexandra Fusai of France 7-6 (7-1), 6-2.
</P>
<P>
Former top-ranked Steffi Graf of Germany is battling for a
berth in next week's season-ending event in New York.
</P>
<P>
In her first tournament following wrist surgery, Graf claimed
her 105th career singles title, and first as an unseeded players,
at the Sparkassen Cup in Leipzig. Her victory moved her up to
17th in the Chase Championship standings, as only the top 16
qualify.
</P>
<P>
Graf, who won this event in 1992 and 1995, will take on
American Mary Joe Fernandez on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
Like Davenport, Hingis and Wimbledon champion Jana Novotna of
the Czech Republic are also coming back from injuries.
</P>
<P>
The second-seeded Hingis has won only four events this year,
none since early May. Hampered by an injured ankle, Hingis lost
not only her quarter-final match in Filderstadt, Germany, last
month, but her 80-week reign as the world's No.1 player came to
an end.
</P>
<P>
The third seed Novotna strained her lower back in Filderstadt
and has not competed since. She has won four titles this season
and is currently ranked third behind Hingis.
</P>
<P>
French Open winner Arantxa Sanchez Vicario of Spain is seeded
fourth, followed by Monica Seles of the United States, Nathalie
Tauziat of France. The top four seeds received first-round byes.
</P>
</TEXT>
