<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Circulates "Serbs to Jasenovac" Photo at U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The Yugoslav Mission to
the United Nations Tuesday circulated a photo which the mission
said was taken at a basketball game in Croatia showing supporters
of a local team holding a banner reading: "Serbs to Jasenovac," a
World War II death camp in Croatia where thousands of Serbs were
killed.
</P>
<P>
A news release, which was issued together with the photo, said
the basketball game was played in Zagreb, the Croatian capital, on
November 5 between "Cibona" of Zagreb and "Red Star" of Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
Josenovac "was the largest concentration camp outside the Third
Reich," the Nazi regime in Germany (1933-1945), and was "set up
and run by the 'Independent State of Croatia,' the most loyal ally
of Nazi Germany in World War II," the news release said.
</P>
<P>
"The poster is not only illustrative of the way in which the
local fans displayed support for their club, but also of the
environment in which the Serbs in Croatia live and to which the
refugee Serbs now living in the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia and
many other European countries are expected to return," the news
release said.
</P>
<P>
The news release said that the banner was "tantamount to
(Maccabee) Basketball Club of Tel Aviv, for instance, being
'greeted' in a German sports arena with a poster reading 'Juden
nach Auschwitz'," which means "Jews to Auschwitz" in English.
</P>
</TEXT>
