<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FA Appoint 'Sleazebuster' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The head of the Football
Supporters' Association (FSA) was appointed as the Football
Association's new so-called 'sleazebuster' on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Graham Bean, a 37-year-old serving police officer and the
national chairman of the FSA for the past two years, takes up his
post as the FA's first compliance officer in January.
</P>
<P>
Bean's role will be to oversee issues of financial
irregularities, drug abuse, racism, violent play and general
misconduct within the game.
</P>
<P>
An FA statement said on Tuesday: "As compliance officer, he
will be responsible for investigating and, where appropriate,
prosecuting disciplinary cases and alleged breaches of the FA's
rules and regulations.
</P>
<P>
"He will also be responsible for developing best practice in
the game as a whole through the promotion of codes of conduct and
policies such as anti-discrimination and child protection, " the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
In high-profile cases of alleged misconduct by players,
managers or clubs, Bean will investigate the evidence and then
recommend to FA chief executive Graham Kelly - who remains the
overall decision-maker on such issues - whether action should be
taken.
</P>
<P>
If a personal hearing is then requested before an FA
disciplinary committee, Bean will take on the role of prosecutor,
which does not currently exist.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the FSA said: "We welcome the establishment of
the post and hope that the compliance officer and hopefully in
time any future compliance unit will make a significant
contribution to tightening up regulation within the game,
particularly in relation to the financial affairs of individual
clubs." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
