<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0354 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Stresses Importance of Foreign Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Foreign aid has been highly
successful in reducing poverty in countries with sound economic
management and strong government institutions, the World Bank
stressed in a new report released here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The number of countries that use foreign aid efficiently has
increased dramatically in the 1990s. However, aid from the wealthy
countries has fallen to its lowest point in more than 50 years,
according to the bank's report entitled "Assessing Aid: What
Works, What Doesn't And Why."
</P>
<P>
"Aid is more than just money; it is about ideas or knowledge
creation," said Joseph Stiglitz, senior vice president and the
chief economist of the World Bank who presented the report.
</P>
<P>
Stiglitz said that with more developing countries moving to
sound policies and donors promoting reform and
institution-building in these nations, there never has been a
better time for giving aid.
</P>
<P>
"The bad news is that just as aid is poised to be its most
effective, the volume of aid is declining and is at its lowest
level" since the end of World War II, Stiglitz said. In the 1990s,
the report said, foreign aid has declined from 69 billion U.S.
dollars in 1991 to some 48 billion dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
While the list of countries that can use aid effectively has
risen, foreign aid has fallen to only 0.22 percent of donor
countries' GDP in 1997, its smallest volume since it was first
institutionalized with the Marshall Plan in 1947. Taking into
account inflation, financial aid from rich countries to poor
countries is one-third lower today than in 1990.
</P>
<P>
At times, foreign aid has been a spectacular success, in South
Korea in the 1960s, Indonesia in the 1970s, Bolivia and Ghana in
the 1980s and Uganda and Vietnam in the 1990s, the report said.
But there also have been some failures in using aid.
</P>
<P>
"Foreign aid has thus been highly effective, totally
ineffective and everything in between," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report estimated that if yearly aid was increased by 10
billion dollars and the new money was targeted to poor countries
with sound economic policies, it would raise an extra 25 million
people out of poverty. However, the same 10 billion dollars in
aid, allocated across the board in the way aid is currently
distributed, would lift only 7 million people out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
"Donor countries could do a better job of allocating aid,
focusing a larger amount on poor countries with sound policies,"
said David Dollar, the lead author of the report and a senior
research economist in the bank.
</P>
<P>
The report said such policies include open trade, secure
private property rights, the absence of corruption, respect for
the rule of law, social safety nets and sound macroeconomic and
financial policies.
</P>
<P>
The report found that in countries with these characteristics,
every dollar of foreign aid attracts 2 dollars of private
investment, because aid increases the confidence of the private
sector and helps to provide public services that investors need,
such as education and infrastructure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981111.0355 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Studies Idea to Review Cuba Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. administration
sees some merit in a proposal to review policy toward Cuba through
a national commission, a State Department spokesman James Rubin
said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Last month, a group of 15 senators, backed by former U.S.
officials, wrote to President Bill Clinton proposing such a
commission carry out the first comprehensive review of Cuba policy
since 1959.
</P>
<P>
As one of the substantial responses from the administration,
Rubin told his daily briefing that Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright was studying the idea.
</P>
<P>
"Secretary Albright sees some merit in that idea. But she has
not made a final decision and the president hasn't made a final
decision," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are studying the proposal. We need to consider several
issues, such as the composition and mandate of the commission,
whether in view of (Cuban leader Fidel) Castro's unwillingness to
undertake any reform," the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
"We are reviewing our options and studying the possibilities
that it could entail," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, Rubin also defended the old U.S. policy of trying to
isolate Cuba diplomatically and economically.
</P>
<P>
"We think our policy has been very effective. We think
increasingly around the world there has been a rejection of the
ways of Fidel Castro," he said.
</P>
<P>
The letter from the senators, led by Virginia Republican John
Warner, said more and more Americans were concerned about the
effects of Washington's Cuba policy on U.S. interests and on the
Cuban people.
</P>
<P>
The commission should include representatives of U.S.
interests, including the public health community, the military,
the churches, human rights groups, the business community and the
Cuban American community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
