<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FDI May Reach Record High in 1998: U.N. Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Global foreign direct
investment (FDI) may reach a record of 430-440 billion U.S.
dollars in 1998, after rising 19 percent in 1997, the U.N.
Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD) said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This year's growth is projected despite slower world economic
growth and the crises in financial markets, UNCTAD said in its
annual world investment report.
</P>
<P>
FDI flows to developing countries amounted to 149 billion
dollars in 1997, accounting for 37 percent of the global total,
double the share at the beginning of the decade.
</P>
<P>
Despite the financial crisis, FDI inflows in Asia have remained
strong and outflows have been significant, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Considering the impact of the crisis, the report predicted that
Asian and Pacific is to remain at the best at the same level of
1997 in FDI inflows.
</P>
<P>
The region attracted a total of 87 billion dollars of FDI, a
8.75 percent rise over 1996.
</P>
<P>
More than 90 percent of FDI inflows occurred in East and
Southeast Asia with China, including Hong Kong, sharing 48 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Latin America saw a 28 percent FDI inflow surge, the highest
among the developing world. Total FDI flows to the continent
amounted to 56 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Increases in FDI flows to the region accounted for two-thirds
of the overall rise in flows to all developing countries in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Brazil stood as number one FDI attractor for the region with an
inflow of 16.3 billion dollars for 1997 against 1.3 billion
dollars in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Central and Eastern Europe saw a significant rise in FDI to a
record of 19 billion dollars in 1997. Russia accounted for one
third of the region's total FDI inflows.
</P>
<P>
FDI flows to Africa, excluding South Africa, captured only 3
percent of total flows to the developing world with a volume of
4.7 billion dollars, against 4.8 billion dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
FDI flows to South Africa rose to 1.7 billion dollars in 1997
from 760 million dollars in 1996, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
