<HEADLINE> Germany Car Industry Stays in High Gear </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Despite signs of a slowdown in
new orders, Germany's automotive sector continued to speed along
in high gear in October, producing 583,200 vehicles, a 32 percent
increase over October 1997 levels, the industry said Tuesday in
Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
The Automobile Industry Association (VDA) in Frankfurt
cautioned about a slowdown in new orders at home. These fell in
October by 10 percent, at the same time foreign orders rose by
four percent.
</P>
<P>
The VDA said Germany's carmakers were starting to live off the
robust order book volumes chalked up during this year, with
production remaining high despite a slackening seen in demand.
</P>
<P>
The October production figures included 546,600 private cars
and vans, up 33 percent from October 1997 levels, with commercial
vehicles output up 17 percent to 36,600, the VDA said.
</P>
<P>
Exports in the month came to 322,100 cars and vans, up 30 per
cent, while those of commercial vehicles were up 22 percent at
22,600.
</P>
<P>
For the first 10 months, German carmakers produced 4.73 million
vehicles, or 13 percent over the volume for the same period last
year. Exports amounted to 2.8 million, up 14 percent in the
10-month period, the VDA said.
</P>
<P>
But new vehicle registrations in Germany - one measurement of
the strength of the domestic market - came to 3.4 million in the
first 10 months, up five percent. In the month of October, the new
registrations came to 355,500, up seven percent over October 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
