<HEADLINE> North Atlantic Assembly Starts Annual Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
EDINBURGH, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Assembly,
the parliamentary body of NATO, Tuesday started its 44th annual
session in Edinburgh, Britain, attended by delegates from its 16
member countries and 15 associate delegations from Central and
Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
With NATO'S 50th anniversary six months away, the four-day
conference will focus on the alliance's future role, or "NATO in
the 21st Century," as is the subject of a special report by
assembly President William Roth, which will be presented to the
assembly in the plenary session.
</P>
<P>
The conclusions and recommendations arising from the report
will be submitted for consideration to NATO governments and
parliaments as the alliance prepares for the next stages of
enlargement and plans for the future, according conference
sources.
</P>
<P>
However, the Kosovo crisis, NATO's response and the
implications for the organization's future role in regional
peacekeeping are expected to be at the forefront of discussions.
</P>
<P>
Also, the ongoing revision of NATO'S strategic concept, the
document that will guide the alliance's policies and actions in
the coming years, the evolving relationship with Russia, and the
process of NATO enlargement, including the imminent entry of three
new members, are key issues of concern to the legislators,
according to sources.
</P>
<P>
The assembly's five committees started discussions Tuesday, but
the annual session won't formally open until Friday, when keynote
speakers, including British Prime Minister Tony Blair, North
Atlantic Assembly President William Roth and NATO Secretary
General Javier Solana will address the plenary session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
